<FIRST>r i PM-EndangeredSturgeons     03-06 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Endangered Sturgeons,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Dam Killing Off Chinese Sturgeons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chinese sturgeon, a 10-foot ocean fish, is in danger of extinction because a <LOCATION> Yangtze </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> dam is blocking it from the breeding grounds it has used for 300 million years, an official newspaper reported today. The <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said the number of mature Chinese sturgeons, known scientifically as <PERSON> Acipenser </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinensis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, has fallen to 5,000 and at least 400 are being killed each year. There are even fewer of the smaller white sturgeon, it said. The fish, which weigh between 330 and 550 pounds when they lay eggs, are unable to reach their breeding grounds in the upper reaches of the Yangtze because of the newly completed <ORGANIZATION> Gezhouba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dam </ORGANIZATION> in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hubei </LOCATION> province. The dam, under construction since 1974 and partially operating since 1981, prevents the fish from reaching 19 of their 20 breeding grounds 1,800 miles upstream in the <LOCATION> Jinsha </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Yangtze </LOCATION> tributary. The dam builders originally agreed to put in a passageway for the fish around the dam, but abandoned the idea because of the expense. Every year, about 30 dead sturgeons are found at the base of the dam. The newspaper quoted <PERSON> Ke </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuen </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Yangtze </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> River </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aquatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, as saying female sturgeons reach maturity at age 13 or 14, when they begin their 20-month journey into <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s largest river. Because the fish eat nothing while they are in the river, they are exhausted by the trip and are not ready to breed again for four or five years. An average sturgeon, he said, lays about 18 pounds of eggs, or about 450,000 fry. But 80 percent are eaten by other fish and most of the young sturgeon do not survive their six-month journey to the sea. <PERSON> Ke </PERSON> said about 370 sturgeon a year are caught at the mouth of the river by fishermen unaware the fish is now under state protection. Ke's institute, which has a budget of only $ 6,750 a year for sturgeon research, is now trying artificial breeding to save the fish from extinction. It has been putting about 350,000 sturgeon fry into the river a year. The dam, with a designed capacity of 2.7 million kilowatts, will supply 20 percent of the central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> network's electricity when it is fully operating.
</TEXT>
