<SECOND>AM-BRF--Liquor Deaths, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0706,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>100 Die After Drinking Homemade Liquor</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: UPDATES thruout with at least 100 people reported dead, 200 fighting
for their lives. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At least 100 people, most of them poor laborers, died and more than 200 others were battling for their lives after drinking homemade liquor in the western city of <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION>, news reports said Monday. Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and said at least 100 of the 251 people hospitalized after drinking the illicit brew Saturday were in critical condition. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said survival chances were bleak for virtually all the patients. Both news agencies said the death toll was at least 100 and was expected to rise. The mass poisoning in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>, the only Indian state where sale of alcohol is banned, was the country's worst known liquor poisoning case, the news agencies said. Many victims are likely to go blind if they live, doctors treating the patients said, according to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>. Press Trust quoted doctors as saying some of the victims could have been saved if they had sought treatment earlier. It said many victims became dizzy and fell into stupors after drinking the illegal brew in the city 560 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said police arrested three people who had supplied the liquor. A son of one supplier and the son of a prominent local politician were among those killed by the poisonous brew, it said. <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>'s chief minister, <PERSON> Amarsinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaudhary </PERSON>, ordered an investigation and promised `` drastic action'' against the police officials who failed to avert the tragedy, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The newspaper said most of the victims were poor laborers who bought the liquor Saturday morning after receiving their monthly wages. The first deaths were reported about midnight Saturday, it added. As news of the first deaths emerged, police fanned out across <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION> with loudspeakers blaring warnings that anyone who had consumed the liquor should seek medical help immediately. The liquor, known locally as `` lattha,'' is made from industrial spirits and methyl alcohol. About 300 people have died in about seven illicit liquor tragedies in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> during the last decade, <ORGANIZATION> UNI </ORGANIZATION> said. Two of the previous cases occurred in <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION>, with others reported in <LOCATION> Ahmedabad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Surat </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
