<FIRST>r i PM-RushdieDebate     03-06 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rushdie Debate,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Thoughts And Gritted Teeth On `The Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No one in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> outside of the Moslem community has endorsed the Iranian death sentence against <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, but some are supporting the author of `` The Satanic Verses'' through gritted teeth. `` An insidious outbreak of ` yes-but' has entered the public debate on the rights and rightness of his case,'' the Observer newspaper said in an editorial Sunday. The debate even popped up at a Writers' Day conference organized by British Pen, the association of poets, essayist and novelists. Most wrote supportive greetings to <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> in a book that was left open for messages, but one entry said: `` Personal freedom is constrained by personal responsibility. You are shown to be wanting in the latter.'' Below it, another writer asserted: `` Freedom is freedom. It does not imply restraint.'' The liberal Observer said it was disturbed by statements by Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> and Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> last week that the book was offensive, and by the opinion of Lord <PERSON> Jakobovits </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s chief rabbi, that such books should be banned. They are not alone in their criticisms. `` Mr. <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s life has to be defended at all costs, but not necessarily his book,'' The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative newspaper, said in an editorial last week. A cartoon in The Sunday Express showed <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> dressed like <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, with a flowing beard of pound notes labeled `` my royalties,'' and threatening the foreign secretary. `` Blasphemy, Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON>,'' the caption said. `` I shall call upon the authors of the world to spear you with their pens.'' <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> sentenced him to death. Iranian clergymen have offered a bounty of as much as $ 5.2 million. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said Saturday that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> still insists <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> repudiate the death sentence before diplomatic relations can be normalized. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has withdrawn its diplomats from <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. The Majlis, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s legislature, has set Tuesday as a deadline for breaking diplomatic relations unless <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> `` clarifies'' its position on the book. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official news agency said Sunday that `` the withdrawal of all copies of ` The Satanic Verses' and banning of its reprinting by the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> government would certainly bring <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> closer to the implementation of the Iranian conditions.'' Many of those in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> who criticize the book stop short of calling for it to be banned. <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON> <PERSON> Shawcross </PERSON>, a prominent attorney and a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, wrote to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> that <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> had committed `` a deplorable abuse of the freedom which he shares with the rest of us, but which we must nonetheless defend.'' `` The <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> book has done incalculable harm to the interests of all people, not with any intention of contribution to scholarship but in order to sensationalize a novel in the hope of securing its better sale,'' <PERSON> Shawcross </PERSON> wrote. In its editorial, The Telegraph said that `` free speech to some degree depends on responsibility in exercising it.'' `` A civilized society is unwise to insist that all abuses of freedom of expression within the law, regardless of the damage done, form part of the ark of the covenant and so are sacrosanct,'' the newspaper said. <PERSON> Auberon </PERSON> <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON>, fuming over <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s past criticisms of British imperialism and racial prejudice, wrote in The Spectator magazine: `` Perhaps the real debate is not so much whether <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON> should be executed ... but just how much we should exert ourselves, as deeply stained white imperialists, to protect him from his own people.'' `` I really do not think it unreasonable in the circumstance of <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s having made several million pounds through insulting <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>, to suggest that he should pay for any police protection he may judge advisable,'' said <PERSON> Waugh </PERSON>, a columnist for The Spectator and The Sunday Telegraph. A letter to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> from <PERSON> Jeremy </PERSON> <PERSON> Treglown </PERSON>, editor of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Literary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supplement </ORGANIZATION>, argued that <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s critics might want a broader revision of the literary canon. `` <PERSON> Milton </PERSON>'s pamphlets and <PERSON> Dryden </PERSON>'s and Pope's satires, which caused deep and violent feeling in those they attacked, should obviously have been toned down. Many readers have been made uncomfortable by the moral insights of <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Austen </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Dickens </LOCATION> _ clear cases for sensitive editing,'' <PERSON> Treglown </PERSON> wrote. `` Would n't we be easier in our minds if there were no books at all?''
</TEXT>
