<HEAD>Group Threatens Medieval Poet's Monument For Islam Slight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT mayor's name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAVENNA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group has threatened to blow up a monument to <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Alighieri </PERSON> because the medieval poet's famed `` Divine Comedy'' places the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> in hell, officials said Sunday. Mayor <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Dragone </PERSON> said he ordered increased security around the monument to the poet, who died in <LOCATION> Ravenna </LOCATION> in 1321, after receiving a threatening letter from a group calling itself `` Guardians of the Revolution.'' `` It is an initiative taken in a prudent way because I am more inclined to think that the letter, which also was sent to a local newspaper, is a joke orchestrated in bad taste or a provocation,'' <PERSON> Dragone </PERSON> was quoted as saying by the Italian news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANSA </ORGANIZATION>. However, the mayor said he warned police and demanded stepped up security because he believes the potential danger from such threats should not be underestimated. He said the letter also demanded that he repudiate `` the false poet <PERSON> Dante </PERSON>'' and declare publicly `` that <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> lied and that these verses can no longer be read or studied.'' The `` Divine Comedy'' is considered a literary masterpiece that established the Tuscan dialect as the literary language of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The work, a poem of more than 14,000 lines in 100 cantos, recounts a poet's journey through hell, purgatory and heaven. It places <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> in the ninth pit of hell. It comes in the midst of the controversy over `` The Satanic Verses'' by author <PERSON> Salman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>, a native Indian now living in Briton. Iranian clerics have offered a $ 5.2 million reward for <PERSON> Rushdie </PERSON>'s death because they say the book blasphemes <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION> by portraying <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>'s wives as prostitutes and suggesting that <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>, not God, was the source for the Koran, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holy book.
