<HEAD>Pentagon Helping Support Adoptions by Service Members</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, in a test program ordered by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, has begun reimbursing some of the expenses of active-duty servicemen who adopt children. The unusual program, which provides up to $ 2,000 to offset the expenses of legally adopting a child, is set to last through the end of the current fiscal year _ or until Sept. 30 _ unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> votes to make the benefit permanent. The adoption reimbursement program was formally launched by the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s personnel chief, <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, last September and as of Dec. 31, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> had processed 69 claims. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> lagged behind the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in publishing their regulations and are only now handling claims. The test was ordered in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s fiscal 1988 budget bill and was championed by Rep. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Colo </LOCATION>. It was proposed not only as a morale-building benefit that might play a role in keeping men and women in the military, but also as a benefit for adoptive parents that parallels the cost of health care provided to women bearing babies in military hospitals. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> nonetheless opposed the program, arguing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was n't providing any extra money for the payments and it could n't afford to tap other accounts. `` In the current fiscal climate, this program might negatively affect the other personnel and family initiatives that benefit a greater percentage of the military population,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> argued unsuccessfully. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has not requested any funding for the program in the fiscal 1990 budget pending before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but promised it would `` look at the results of the test program to determine further action.'' The reimbursement payments are available to anyone on active duty `` who initiates adoption proceedings after Sept. 30, 1987, and before Oct. 1, 1989,'' the Pentagon regulation states. `` Benefits paid under the test program may be paid only after the adoption is final. The adoption of stepchildren does not qualify for reimbursement under this program.'' Service members who adopt more than one child can claim a maximum $ 5,000 per year, the regulation adds. According to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adoption </ORGANIZATION>, a group headquartered in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the average agency adoption fee was about $ 6,000 in 1987.
