<HEAD>Once Pages Together, Congressmen Are Linked By Memory Of 1954 Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once congressional pages together, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> both realized their dream of being elected to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. As if that were not unusual enough, both also were witnesses to the rarest of events: an attack by gunmen on the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON>, D-Pa., and <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, R-Mo., stood together on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor last Wednesday to mark the 35th anniversary of an event they said will always seem fresh in their The two were 16-year-old pages and roommates on March 1, 1954, the day that four neatly dressed Puerto Ricans walked into the public galleries, unfurled a flag, shouted `` Free Puerto Rico!'' and began shooting randomly from large automatic pistols. House Speaker <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> _ who had been counting heads in a quorum call on a bill dealing with migrant laborers _ banged the gavel. A few congressmen fell, bleeding. Some raced for the doors. Some hid under the tables. `` As one who has never been particularly age-conscious, I stand in awe of the fact that this event occurred 35 years ago, and I remember it as though it were yesterday,'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said last week. <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> had just gotten out of his seat on the Democratic side in the rear of the chamber when the shooting started. `` When the shots started to be fired, they sounded like firecrackers going off,'' <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> said last week. `` There were a lot of them and they were different-sounding because there were several weapons that were being used. The only thing that made it clear they were n't firecrackers is that I got sprinkled with some of the marble that flaked off.'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> thought the noise was firecrackers, too, `` but when I looked up, I could see fire coming out of the end of the barrels of those guns.'' Wounded were Reps. <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentley </PERSON>, R-Mich.; <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Jensen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>; <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON>, D-Md; <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, D-Ala.; and <PERSON> Clifford </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, D-Tenn. All Before it was over, a photographer snapped a picture of <LOCATION> Kanjorski </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> carrying one of them off on a stretcher. As bad as the moment was, the news photo gave <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> and <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> temporary celebrity status among their peers, and linked them together in time. `` All through our lives we have been very close friends,'' <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> said. He classified the odds of both becoming congressmen as `` remote,'' even though he said both dreamed about the possibility. One of the attackers died in 1979, and the other three were given presidential clemency the same year after 25 years in prison. <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> was elected to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1980, <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> four years later. `` I might say it was a great pleasure for me personally when my friend <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON> joined us here two terms ago,'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said. `` He and I were roommates and colleagues of that era, and it was great to see an old buddy come back to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have often thought it -LRB- the shooting -RRB- was a terrible thing to have happened, but since it did, I was glad I was here to observe that little anecdote in American history,'' <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON> said.
