of the congressional club, the beneficiary of special courtesies and favors. However, the normal scenario turned into chaos for Tower when <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Weyrich </PERSON>, a conservative activist, testified publicly about Tower's drinking. `` What <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Weyrich </PERSON> did was to present an uneasy group of senators who really did n't like <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> anyway with a fig leaf,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hess </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Brookings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> specialist on the presidency. `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> makes ethics and personal conduct almost a hallmark of his administration and gets hoisted on his own petard,'' <PERSON> Hess </PERSON> said. The White House has acknowledged shortcomings in handling Tower's nomination, blaming some of the problems on incompetence and inexperience among the new staff <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> traces the mishandling back to December, even before Tower was actually nominated. `` They let the naming of him dangle for two months. Secondly, after they named him they did n't do anything. They just let it sit there,'' <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> said. `` When the negative stuff came out they did n't seem to put together a campaign to support him,'' <PERSON> Nofziger </PERSON> added. `` The only support that I see is coming out of the White House and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators. `` Just as this thing is beginning to heat up,'' he added, `` <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> goes off to the <LOCATION> Far </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and takes with him his chief of staff and half his staff, leaving nobody to stay behind and fight the good fight.'' It was on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first full day in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <OR