<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell against the Japanese yen, while share prices also lost ground on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> at the end of the trading day Monday. The dollar opened at 127.55 yen and moved higher to peak at 127.68 yen before closing the day slightly lower at 127.63 yen. It was down 0.49 yen from last Friday's 128.12-yen finish. On the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, a 73.63-point loser last week, also shed 123.24 points, or 0.38 percent, for 31,876.86 points by the end of the trading day. Dealers said trading was directionless in the absence of major market-affecting news, but concern over possible Japanese discount rates hikes was sending the dollar and <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> lower `` There is talk of rate hikes here and market participants are taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' said a dealer at a major Japanese securities firm. `` Otherwise, trading is directionless.'' He added that the currency fluctuated in wide ranges last week because of technical adjustments and economic news, including a West German decision not to raise its interest rates. `` This week, people are waiting for a conference Wednesday by <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> Gov. <PERSON> Satoshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sumita </PERSON> and the release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unemployment figures due out Friday,'' the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity. In stock trading, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> fell as investors moved to the sidelines ahead of the settlement of March futures contracts scheduled for Tuesday, dealers said. They said brokerage firms, including <ORGANIZATIO