shipment to <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>. All the shipments had arrived by Sunday. `` None have been used, because there are sometimes serious reactions to antivenins and -LRB- doctors -RRB- do n't want to give them to him unless they have to,'' <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> explained. The reactions could include lung and kidney problems, he said. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said `` we want to express our appreciation to everyone who has worked so hard in obtaining the antivenins.'' The viper's venom attacks its victim's ability to produce fibrinogen, an element of blood that regulates coagulation. A lack of fibrinogen can cause uncontrolled bleeding. <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s fibrinogen level was near zero Wednesday. Doctors were replacing it with transfusions and it appeared <PERSON> Haast </PERSON>'s body had begun to produce the substance. His fibrinogen level improved to about one-third of normal by Sunday, still `` dangerously low,'' <PERSON> Dwan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Haast </PERSON> had been treated earlier with antivenins from the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> and from a lab in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, but they did not work as well as expected. <PERSON> Studdert </PERSON> said the Iranian government apparently did not interfere with the shipment of the antivenin despite the strained relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Iranian leader <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> has often called the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the `` great Satan.''
