 A concert billed as an `` Aryan Woodstock'' for skinheads and white supremacists turned out to be `` boring and uncomfortable'' because of rain, a lack of food and a court-ordered ban on music. About 100 people representing half a dozen white supremacist groups gathered Saturday at a private ranch about 40 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, but were far outnumbered by about 400 protesters and 500 police officers. `` They talked about girls. They gropingly discussed ` white power.' They pranced about with <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> flags and insignia, but they never discussed the ideology of fascism or of anything else,'' wrote <PERSON> Cherie </PERSON> <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>, a former reporter who gained entrance to the event. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>, who did not specify how she managed to attend the rally in the heart of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s wine country, described the event in an article in today's editions of the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was simply boring _ and uncomfortable,'' she said. `` The great majority had brought neither rain gear nor food. Morale hit bottom when police refused to let the daughter of white supremacist <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzger </PERSON> return with $ 100 worth of pizzas.'' The event originally was touted as something to bring together thousands of white supremacist youths. The skinhead bands Midtown Boot Boys from <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, the Hammerheads from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> annd <PERSON> Kakenkreuz </PERSON> from <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> were expected to perform. But <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Superior Judge <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Snowden </PERSON> ruled Friday that rally organizers could n't have music without a permit. So participants spent most of the day glaring at reporters and protesters from a hill. The gathering was held out of view of the public, which was not allowed entrance to the ranch. There were a few clashes between white supremacists and protesters but no arrests or major violence. `` What you find is that the people of <LOCATION> Napa </LOCATION> rallied against this group that has no purpose other than hate. I was real proud of the way people stood up,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>. Early Sunday, the last five white supremacists left the property. Sheriff <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> estimated the cost of law enforcement at about $ 400,000.
