<HEAD>Judge Orders Release of 188 Sikhs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge today ordered the release of 188 Sikhs jailed in a northern city since a 1984 army raid on the holiest Sikh shrine during which 1,200 people were killed, a senior government official said. Among those to be freed is <PERSON> Gurcharan </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tohra </PERSON>, head of the Sikh temple management committee. The body, which controls most Sikh shrines and temple funds, is considered the most powerful Sikh organization. The prisoners' release is part of a package announced last week by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> to try to end ethnic violence that has wracked the northwestern state of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> for seven years. Militants are fighting for an independent homeland. In June 1984, then Prime Minister <PERSON> Indira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> ordered the army to raid the <ORGANIZATION> Golden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> to rout Sikh militants inside. Four months later, she was assassinated by two Sikh bodyguards in retaliation for the raid. Most of those killed in the raise were Sikhs and authorities arrested about 300 people, many of them pilgrims held for questioning but never charged. <LOCATION> Jodhpur </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Khemchandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharma </PERSON>, acting on a request by prosecutors, today ordered the release of 188 of the prisoners jailed in <LOCATION> Jodhpur </LOCATION>, said a Home Ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The prisoners will be taken back to <LOCATION> Amritsar </LOCATION> on Tuesday, the official said. <LOCATION> Jodhpur </LOCATION> is in <LOCATION> Rajasthan </LOCATION> state, southwest of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>. Authorities had already released 118 prisoners, the official said. At least 2,400 people were killed by Sikh militants last year, more than double the number in 1987. More than 340 people have died this year. Sikhs make up 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population, but they are a slight majority in the northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state. Militants claim Sikhs are discriminated against by <PERSON> Hindus </PERSON>, who comprises 82 percent of the national population.
