<HEAD>Black Seeks Historic Victory In Mostly White Deep South District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tuskegee Mayor <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON> enters Tuesday's Democratic primary runoff with a historic bid: to become the state's first black congressman this century, and in a district that is three-fourths white. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> is considered the underdog in seeking to become the 25th black in the 435-member <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the first from a <LOCATION> Deep </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> district where whites are in the vast majority. `` The members are watching it very closely,'' said <PERSON> Amelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> victory, she said, `` would be an extraordinary message at this point in the history of our country. Despite the symbolism, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and his opponent, Secretary of State <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> Browder </PERSON>, have sought to keep race out of the campaign for the 3rd Congressional District seat in mostly rural east <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. The runoff winner will face state Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Opelika </LOCATION>, who was a Democrat until he switched to Republican ranks last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, 46, worked for <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s ill-fated 1968 presidential campaign, but he later formed political ties to then-President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> and former Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, supporting <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> in his 1974 gubernatorial bid. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has enlisted the aid of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in seeking a strong black voter turnout, but has said repeatedly that race is not an issue. `` I am very confident we will win support from people of both races who are interested in the best qualified candidate regardless of the color of the candidate's skin,'' he said. <PERSON> Browder </PERSON>, also 46, a former professor who narrowly led <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> in a splintered Democratic field Feb. 14, is considered the frontrunner. He has the support of organized labor and has gained recognition for advocating campaign finance reform. He has not targeted Ford or made race a factor in the three-week campaign. `` Both candidates realize that going into such a short time-frame there is no advantage in going after your opponent,'' said <PERSON> Browder </PERSON>'s campaign manager, <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> `` Race is certainly not an issue in our campaign.'' `` Race is not as much an issue as it has been in the past,'' said state Sen. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Preuitt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Talladega </LOCATION>, a conservative who ran a close third in the primary and has since blasted <PERSON> Browder </PERSON> as a liberal who `` sold his soul to big labor bosses.'' `` He does n't want to be known as just a black candidate,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, a white high school principal from <LOCATION> Notasulga </LOCATION> who is co-chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s campaign. `` But he understood that just to make the runoff was historic.'' The last time a black reached a Democratic runoff for a congressional seat in the state was in 1978, but <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> McNair </PERSON> lost to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> in west <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s 7th District. <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON> now sits in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. In the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, Reps. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellums </PERSON>, D-Calif., and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheat </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., are the only blacks to represent districts with majority white populations on the scale of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s 3rd In the Deep South, Rep. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> won a <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> district that was about evenly split racially in 1986 and won re-election easily last year with strong white support. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Espy </PERSON>'s administrative assistant, said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> entered the race with `` a proven track record with white politicians that <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Espy </PERSON> did n't have.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has been mayor of Tuskegee since 1972 and helped found state and national conferences of black mayors as well as a multi-racial organization called the World Conference of Mayors. The 3rd District seat was vacated by the death in December of Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>. He had kept the seat Democratic for 22 years with generally conservative, defense-oriented politics. <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, 37, is expected to get support from white conservative voters who backed <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, but he is a relative newcomer in state politics.
