<HEAD>Murder Charge Dropped Because Police Can't Produce Informant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The man that detectives most want to bring to trial for allegedly killing one of their colleagues is free because police played fast and loose in getting a search warrant for a drug raid, prosecutors say. Three detectives have been suspended while perjury charges are considered. The case has focused attention on how easy, and tempting, it is for police officers to obtain search warrants by citing fictitious informants. Defense lawyers contend the practice, though illegal, is routine in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and many other cities across the nation. But prosecutors and police say if the use of confidential informants is curbed, they will lose a key weapon in the war against drugs. Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON>, who has spent 22 years on the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> bench in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, said judges have little choice but to trust police when they say they have an informant. `` Assuming that they were trying to trick me, how would I know it?'' <PERSON> Weinstein </PERSON> said. `` The informant is n't subject to cross examination, I do n't even see the informant. I have to rely on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney and the law enforcement agencies. If they wanted to deceive me, it would be easy to do so.'' In the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> case, a <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge dismissed all charges against <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> two weeks ago after police failed to produce a mysterious informant _ identified only as <PERSON> John </PERSON> _ who supposedly tipped them off to a cocaine dealer in the city's <LOCATION> Dorchester </LOCATION> section. On Feb. 17, 1988, as four detectives prepared to break into the dealer's apartment, two shots were fired from inside the apartment. One pierced the door and felled 36-year-old detective <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON>, a veteran member of the elite anti-drug task force. When the detectives finally knocked down the steel-reinforced door, the apartment was empty. They rushed down a back staircase and arrested <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> and three other people on a lower floor. Prosecutors later dropped charges against the other three in return for testimony against the 33-year-old <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>, who maintains he is innocent. From the outset, a weakness in the prosecution's case was that <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> did not match the informant's description of the crack dealer who occupied the apartment and presumably fired the fatal shot. According to the affidavit police submitted to obtain the search warrant, <PERSON> John </PERSON> said the dealer was Hispanic and about 5-foot-6. <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> is a 6-foot Jamaican. In pretrial hearings last month, <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>'s attorney said <PERSON> John </PERSON> was a vital defense witness, and Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grabau </PERSON> ordered detectives <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Luna </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Amate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON> to bring him into court. When the detectives said they were unable to find the informant, <PERSON> Grabau </PERSON> threw out the charges and lambasted the detectives, saying he believed they had willfully disobeyed his orders. Last week, <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Meara </PERSON>, assistant district attorney for <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> went back into court to make an extraordinary accusation. He said the detectives had lied to him and the court about the informant, either to strengthen the case against <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> or to protect the search warrant. And <PERSON> O'Meara </PERSON> contended the charges against <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> should not be dropped. He said the actual informant was not <PERSON> John </PERSON> _ who may or may not exist _ but another man, identified in court as `` Y.'' <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>'s lawyer maintains that `` Y'' is still not the right man. The judge is scheduled to consider reinstating the charges this week. In the interim, the state attorney general is considering perjury charges against the suspended detectives. None of the three officers could be reached for comment. One is on vacation in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and the other two did not respond to repeated messages asking them to call. Deputy Superintendent <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, supervisor of the three, has repeatedly said he accepts full responsibility for the actions of the team.
