<HEAD>Court Turns Down Appeal by Northeastern States on Air Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today turned away an appeal by northeastern states seeking to force the federal government to crack downn on acid rain and other pollution they say is caused by smokestacks in other states. The court, without comment, refused to order the federal <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> to take steps to limit interstate air pollution. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here said last July 22 that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> acted properly in dismissing bids by <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> officials to force federal action against pollution originating in other states. The appeals court ordered the federal agency to restudy a petition by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> officials in light of newly available data. Officials from <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> joined those from <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> in asking the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn the appeals court ruling. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> officials did not join the appeal to the high court. The case acted on today stems from petitions filed with the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 and 1981 by <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> claiming that soot, smoke and sulfur dioxide were blowing in from hundreds of miles away. They argued that pollutants from coal-burning utility plants and factories in seven other states made it impossible for them to meet federal air quality standards. The seven states complained about are <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. The northeastern states said federal law requires the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to force the other states to revise their air pollution control plans. Federal clean air laws give the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> broad power to enforce state air quality programs. If a state's program is inadequate, federal officials can order industries to clean up or face stiff fines or closing down operations. But in the case acted on today, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials said there was insufficient evidence to prove that air pollution in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> originated hundreds of miles away. The agency also argued that federal law is not designed to cover such long-range pollution. The appeals court here gave deference to the agency's expertise. `` This court is being asked to second-guess the scientific judgments of the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>,'' the appeals court said. `` We can not say that the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s assessment of the scientific evidence was unreasonable.'' The case is <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, 88-684.
