<HEAD>Court to Decide Inmate Rights on Anti-Psychotic Drugs in Washington
State Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to decide whether prison inmates are entitled to a court hearing and other safeguards before being forced to take anti-psychotic drugs. The justices said they will hear an appeal by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state officials who say judges should not be allowed to interfere with the professional judgment of prison administrators and doctors. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last July that convicted robber <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> must be given a court hearing before he is forced to take anti-psychotic drugs. The state court also said that prison officials must show a compelling state interest for giving <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> the medication, and show the drugs will be effective. The state's compelling interest can be demonstrated by a need to preserve life, to protect other individuals who might be harmed by <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, to prevent his suicide and to maintain `` the ethical integrity of the medical profession,'' the state court said. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was imprisoned in 1976, and for the next four years was incarcerated primarily in a mental health unit where he agreed to take anti-psychotic drugs. He was paroled in 1980 on condition he agree to receive psychiatric treatment. His parole was revoked after he attacked two nurses at <ORGANIZATION> Saint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cabrini </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Back in prison, <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was placed in a unit for offenders with serious behavioral or mental disorders. He agreed to take anti-psychotic drugs until November 1982, when he refused to take the medication any longer. A committee of prison officials decided <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> should be given the drugs against his will, and that decision was upheld by the prison superintendent. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> filed a civil rights suit in 1985, seeking to block officials from giving him the medication and to win monetary damages for violations of his rights. A state judge dismissed the suit. But the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> revived it, ruling that `` competent adults have a right to determine what shall be done to their bodies.'' The state court said treatment with anti-psychotic drugs is no less intrusive than electro-shock therapy. While the drugs are beneficial to acutely ill patients, they also can have serious side effects _ ranging from involuntary spasms to permanent brain damage, the state court said. It noted that a court hearing will ensure the prisoner the right to be represented by a lawyer, to cross-examine witnesses and to examine the state's files. Such a hearing also will guarantee other due-process protections, the state court said. State officials said the state court's ruling improperly will `` insert the state and federal judicial systems into medical and institutional administrative decisions.'' The case is <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, 88-599.
