o go on television He said demonstrators had assembled outside party headquarters for a half hour before `` several hundred officers and men from the police went into the crowd. They ripped down banners and confiscated cameras. At least 30 people were arrested.'' Banners destroyed by police called for `` freedom of the press'' and `` a press without censorship,'' he said. The protesters screamed at police that they were violating the Soviet Constitution by breaking up a legal demonstration, <PERSON> Sokolov </PERSON> said. He said the police's action `` was unprecedented in recent months.'' In January, the <ORGANIZATION> Latvian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief, <PERSON> Janis </PERSON> <PERSON> Vagris </PERSON>, expressed alarm over rising tension in the republic, saying even the party was feeling the effects of `` ethnic stratification.'' Of <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>'s 2.6 million inhabitants, 54 percent are Latvians, and 33 percent ethnic Russians. On Jan. 7, a group was formed to challenge the <ORGANIZATION> Latvian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> activists and nationalists said the new group was Russian-dominated. <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and the other Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> were absorbed by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1940, one year after the Hitler-Stalin pact consigned the area to the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s sphere of influence. Political ferment has increased in the Baltic states under the liberalized atmosphere fostered by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Some residents say they want to regain their homelands' independence.
