<HEAD>Home-made Liquor Kills 130 in India</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede New Delhi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with new death toll; ADD quotes, details;
no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARODA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities said today at least 130 people died and 151 were critically ill after hundreds of laborers drank an illegal home-made liquor in the only Indian state where the sale of alcohol is banned. Doctors said hospitals were unable to cope with the rush of victims, and that there was little chance the most seriously injured of the 251 hospitalized victims would survive. At least 25 people were blinded by the tainted The local government announced police arrested three people who supplied the liquor. Several policemen were suspended for failing to avert the tragedy, the government said. Baroda is a major industrial center in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>, the only Indian state where it is illegal to sell alcohol. The city, 560 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, is home to 2.5 million people. According to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>, the son of one supplier and the son of a prominent local politician were among those killed by the moonshine. The boot-leg liquor is normally a mixture of ethyl alcohol, alum and natured spirits. But this time, industrial methyl alcohol was mixed to the brew known locally as `` lattha,'' which is sold in plastic sacks for the equivalent of 10 cents. Methyl alcohol paralyzes the central nervous system. Most survivors were too ill to speak, but one told the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency the only difference he noticed was that the liquor was `` sweeter than normal.'' Press Trust said many of the victims became dizzy and complained of nausea and stomach aches before losing consciousness. A doctor at the state-run Sir <ORGANIZATION> Siyaji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, which was treating most of the victims, said conditions at the facility were precarious, with groaning victims crowded against each other on the floor, on stretchers, and occasionally three to a bed. `` We do not have enough bottles of glucose to even administer first aid to the victims,'' the doctor said, speaking on condition of anonymity. `` There are no free stretchers to bring in more patients, because people are already sleeping on them.'' <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>'s chief minister, <PERSON> Amarsinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaudhary </PERSON>, ordered an investigation and promised action against the police officials who failed to avert the disaster, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> reported. The newspaper said most of the victims were poor laborers who bought the liquor Saturday morning after receiving their monthly wages. The first deaths were reported about midnight Saturday, it said. As news of the deaths emerged, police fanned out across <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION> with loudspeakers blaring warnings about the liquor. About 300 people have died in seven illicit liquor cases in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> during the last decade, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. Two of the previous cases occurred in <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION>, with others reported in <LOCATION> Ahmedabad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Surat </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
