<HEAD>Court Will Review Housing Desegregation Fines Imposed Against Yonkers
Councilmen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to review the stiff fines imposed against four <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, councilmen for defying a federal judge's order to adopt a housing desegregation plan. The justices said they will study arguments that the judge exceeded his power in imposing the contempt-of-court fines. The case attracted national attention last summer as the defiant councilmen were threatened with jail as well as fines and the city faced possible bankruptcy for refusing to obey <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sand </PERSON>'s order. Faced with massive layoffs of city workers, the city council voted last Sept. 10 to comply with Sand's order to build 1,000 low-cost homes to desegregate middle-class areas of the city. But <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, located just north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, had to pay $ 819,000 in fines. Each of the four councilmen was ordered to pay $ 3,500 for being in contempt of a desegregation order issued the previous Aug. 2. The case stemmed from a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawsuit begun in the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration's waning days in 1980. Sand in 1985 ruled that <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> officials intentionally and unlawfully promoted racial segregation through the city's housing and school policies. He ordered the city to desegregate the school system and build subsidized housing in predominantly white sections of the city. City officials agreed in January 1988 to build 200 units and make plans for 600 more. They later sought to back out of the agreement. The 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last August said Sand acted properly in holding the city and the four councilmen in contempt after the council voted 4-3 against a package of financial incentives designed to attract development of 800 low - and moderate-income homes Sand imposed fines against the city starting at $ 100 a day and doubling daily until officials lived up to their desegregation The appeals court put a cap of $ 1 million a day on the fines, and upheld the judge's $ 500-a-day fine for each councilman. The councilmen's jail terms were blocked temporarily by a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> order last September, and the threat of imprisonment was lifted after the council relented and adopted the desegregation plan. The four councilmen are <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Longo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> and Vice Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON>. The appeals court said the four are not protected by legislative immunity against the contempt order and fines because the city government previously consented to abide by a court-approved agreement to desegregate. `` No litigant, least of all public officials sworn to uphold the Constitution of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, may be permitted to avoid compliance with solemn commitments they have made in a consent judgment entered by a federal district court to remedy constitutional violations,'' the appeals court said. The 2nd Circuit court also rejected arguments that the free-speech rights of the councilmen were violated. They `` remain free to express their views on all aspects of housing in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>'' but not to violate lawful court orders, the appeals court said. The appeals court also turned back the city's argument _ in effect, one made in behalf of the city treasury and the taxpayers _ that it was powerless to compel the council members to adopt the housing desegregation plan. `` The city can not view itself as an entity separate from the city council for purposes of complying with the consent judgment'' to build the homes, the appeals court said. The justices today granted the appeals of the four councilmen but rejected an appeal filed in behalf of the city. The cases are <PERSON> Spallone </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-854; <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-855; <PERSON> Chema </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-856; and <PERSON> Longo </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-870.
