<HEAD>Court Bars Lawsuit Against Former New York Federal Prosecutor in
Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today barred a lawsuit against a former federal prosecutor who refused police protection to a witness gunned down before she could testify. The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the prosecutor was not legally responsible to protect the woman, killed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> along with three <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> employees who tried to come to her aid. Former assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON> was sued by the family of <PERSON> Lena </PERSON> <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON>. She was abducted from a rooftop parking area in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> on April 12, 1982, and later was shot to death along with the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> workers. <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Candor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was convicted of murder along with the hit man, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nash </PERSON>. The government had been investigating alleged fraud in <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON>' business Ms. <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON>, an accountant there, agreed to cooperate in the investigation. Prosecutors agreed to allow her to plead guilty to one count of fraud and recommend she not serve any jail sentence. In December 1981, <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON> allegedly told <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON>' lawyer, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostericher </PERSON>, that <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON> and another unnamed woman working at Candor were cooperating with the government. Court papers suggested <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON> was trying to put pressure on <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON> to confess to fraud. Soon after the Schlessinger-Ostericher conversation, another former Candor employee, <PERSON> Jenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Soo </PERSON> <PERSON> Chin </PERSON>, disappeared. Ms. <PERSON> Chin </PERSON>, a close friend of Ms. <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON>, apparently was suspected by <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON> of being the other witness cooperating with prosecutors. Ms. <PERSON> Chin </PERSON>'s body never was found but there was testimony that <PERSON> Nash </PERSON> displayed a photograph of her corpse to <PERSON> Margolies </PERSON> as proof he had killed her. Ms. <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON> then requested police protection for herself for the second time, and <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON> again denied it. The suit against <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON> accused him of violating her rights by negligetly and recklessly denying her protection that could have saved her life. The 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> threw out the suit in December 1987. The appeals court said prosecutors have qualified immunity from suit when their conduct does not violate clearly established rights of individuals. `` We can not say that it was clearly established that the government had created or assumed a special relationship with <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON>,'' the appeals court said. `` It would have been speculative at best to conclude that <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON> was entitled to police protection or that the government was otherwise obliged to safeguard her from those against whom she was going to testify.'' Just last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled in a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> case that the government has no constitutional duty to protect individuals from private violence or abuse. The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> case is <PERSON> Barbera </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Schlessinger </PERSON>, 87-2034.
