<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-LibelPrivilege     03-06 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Libel Privilege,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Leaves Intact Libel Award Against Six Newspapers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today left intact a $ 90,000 libel award won against six American newspapers serving Korean-American readers. The justices, without comment, turned away arguments that the newspapers should not have been legally liable for accurately reporting an announcement made by a South Korean government agency. At issue was the scope of the legal immunity a news organization enjoys when accurately and fairly reporting about government reports or public proceedings despite their defamatory nature. In the case acted on today, the 4th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the so-called fair report privilege does not apply to reporting about acts by foreign governments. Two intelligence agencies of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government issued a 62-page `` press release'' on Sept. 9, 1985, announcing the disruption of two <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> spy rings operating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The government agencies said one of the spy rings was run by students at <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, and identified <PERSON> Chang-Sin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> as one North Korean agent. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, who emigrated to this country from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1975 and graduated from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> in 1984, now lives in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. He recently became a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> sued six newspapers and a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> television station in federal court in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, alleging that their reports libeled him by reiterating the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> government's announcement. A federal trial judge threw out the suit, noting that <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law includes a fair report privilege. The judge said that <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> could not win his libel suit because he could not prove the newspapers and television station acted with malice. The 4th Circuit court reinstated <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s suit last June 20, ruling that the fair report privilege should not have been invoked. The appeals court, by a 2-1 vote, said the privilege never should apply to a news organization's reporting on information received from foreign governments. `` Because we find that foreign governments are not necessarily more reliable than domestic non-official sources, we are not willing to enlarge the scope of the -LRB- fair report -RRB- privilege to include information from such governments,'' the appeals court said. It added, `` Some countries may take advantage of our liberal First Amendment rights in order maliciously to defame or, carelessly and without adequate inquiry, excoriate private parties.'' The ruling meant <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> could win his libel suit against the news organizations by proving the government report about him was false and made negligently. The ruling also cleared the way for a libel trial, in which a jury earlier this year awarded a total of $ 90,000 against the six newspapers. The television station, WNVC-TV, was found not to have libeled <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the six newspapers argued that the fair report privilege for reporting on foreign goverments sometimes should be available. The newspapers are The <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, The Dong-A Iblo, <ORGANIZATION> Joong-Ang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilbo </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> Chosun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilbo </ORGANIZATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> Korea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> and The Sae Gae Shinbo. The case is The <ORGANIZATION> Dong-A </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ilbo </ORGANIZATION> v. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, 88-1145.
