<HEAD>Court Orders More Hearings in Pennsylvania Sexual Abuse Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered more hearings in the case of three <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> school officials sued by a former student who says she was sexually abused by her high school band instructor. The justices said a federal appeals court should review its ruling that the school officials sued by <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoneking </PERSON>, a former student at <ORGANIZATION> Bradford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Area </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, are not entitled to qualified legal immunity. The justices said the appeals court ruling should be restudied in light of their Feb. 22 decision in a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> case that government has no constitutional duty to protect individuals from private abuse or violence. Whether that decision controls the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> case is not clear, however, since the lawsuit alleges that a state employee _ not a private citizen _ administered the abuse. Ms. <PERSON> Stoneking </PERSON> was graduated from high school in 1983. Her 1987 lawsuit contends that school principal <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, assistant principal <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and school district superintendent <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuey </PERSON> violated her rights by failing to protect her. The suit alleges that beginning in Ms. <PERSON> Stoneking </PERSON>'s sophomore year, band instructor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> sexually harassed and abused her, and forced her to engage in various sex acts with him. The suit alleges that the school officials named as defendants knew of complaints against <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> involving other female students. It states that the school officials either knew or recklessly failed to discover that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was sexually abusing female band members. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was suspended in 1986, and later resigned. He pleaded guilty to criminal charges, including indecent assault, that same year. The three officials sued by Ms. <PERSON> Stoneking </PERSON> sought to have the case thrown out before reaching a trial. They said they were entitled to qualified immunity _ a legal doctrine shielding public officials from liability when their conduct `` does not violate clearly established statutory or constitutional rights of which a reasonable person would have known.'' A federal judge refused to throw out the case, and that ruling was upheld on a 2-1 vote by the 3rd <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last Sept. 12. The school officials then sought help from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The case is <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Stoneking </PERSON>, 88-802.
