<HEAD>Residents Outraged By Lenient Sentence For Convicted Rapist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAULT STE. MARIE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge who gave a rapist a lenient sentence because he said he did n't want to keep him from his goal of becoming a police officer has provoked outrage in this normally peaceful <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> community. Two weeks ago, Visiting Alger County Circuit Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> set aside his original verdict in the rape case and instead convicted <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> under a youthful offenders act for attacking a fellow college student. The move spared <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> jail time. He was ordered to spend three years on probation and pay $ 975 in court costs and $ 200 compensation to the victim. If he complies with the terms, his record will be expunged. His court file has been suppressed. <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> said he took the action partly because <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON>, 21, was a criminal justice major and the conviction would have prevented him from achieving his goal of becoming a police officer. The judge issued the original rape conviction Jan. 10, after a bench trial. If the judge had not revised it, <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> would have faced a minimum five-year prison sentence for two counts of first-degree criminal sexual conduct. <LOCATION> Chippewa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Prosecutor <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> said he will appeal the sentence. Stark's action has prompted more irate calls to the <LOCATION> Sault </LOCATION> Ste. Marie Evening News editorial offices than any story in recent memory, said the newspaper's editor, <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Fazzari </PERSON>. `` I think they would lynch the judge if they had him right here,'' <PERSON> Fazzari </PERSON> said. The victim was hospitalized for emotional stress after the incident and transferred from <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to a college out of state. She said she was devastated by the lenient sentence. The state Holmes Youthful Trainee Act allows for special treatment of a defendant whose crime occurred before age 20. Stark convicted <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> Jan. 10 of two counts of rape in the Dec. 18, 1987, attack. <PERSON> Stark </PERSON> said he could n't convince prosecutors to consider a lesser charge that would have allowed for reduced jail time. He invoked the youthful offenders act even though <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> already was 20 years old when the rape occurred. `` This was a very unhappy choice for us,'' the judge said. <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> has left <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and is studying criminal justice at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, said his attorney, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldenberg </PERSON>. The victim said <PERSON> Caballer </PERSON> followed her around at a small campus party and insisted on walking her back to her dormitory room at 3 a.m. When they arrived, <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> placed himself `` so that as soon as I unlocked and opened the door, he could get in.'' `` I said, ` I appreciate your walking me back here, but you're not allowed in here,''' the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> quoted her as saying. <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> then followed her into the room, forced her onto her bed and tore off her clothing, she said.
