<HEAD>Court Orders Pa. Beating Death Award Reconsidered</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ordered a federal appeals court to consider freeing a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> city and one of its police officers from paying a $ 66,000 award over a 1981 beating death. The justices said the appeals court should restudy the case in light of their Feb. 22 decision in a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> case. In that ruling, the high court said government officials have no constitutional duty to protect individuals from private violence or abuse. In the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> case, a federal jury awarded $ 66,000 to <PERSON> Mamie </PERSON> <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, whose son <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> was beaten to death at the <ORGANIZATION> Cash </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on Nov. 10, 1981. The jury found that the city and Police Sergeant <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> violated <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON>'s right by failing to protect him. The <ORGANIZATION> Cash </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, a private social club, was managed by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> `` Pope'' Flenory, a retired <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> policeman and a friend of <LOCATION> Dlubak </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Flenory </PERSON> allegedly summoned <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> to the club to frighten <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> into confessing that <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> stole some records from the club's disc jockey. <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> tearfully pleaded with <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> to take him out of the club but the officer refused, according to court records. <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> allegedly told <PERSON> Flenory </PERSON>, `` I guess you can take care of this yourself.'' After <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> left, <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON>, who also was suspected in the theft of the records, were beaten severely by club employees. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> survived but <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> died. While the beatings were going on, friends of <LOCATION> Powdrill </LOCATION> arrived at the club and then went to the police station a block away to ask for help. The two officers who arrived at the club to investigate left within a few minutes, after talking to <PERSON> Flenory </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Horton </PERSON> alleged that the police department for years had failed to investigate beatings and other criminal activities at Flenory's club. She sued the city and <LOCATION> Dlubak </LOCATION> under a federal civil rights law, and the jury awarded $ 65,899 to Mrs. <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, which upheld the award last August, noted that <PERSON> New </PERSON> <PERSON> Kensington </PERSON> had a `` hands-off'' policy toward complaints of drunkenness at the city's private clubs. The policy said, `` When a call is received from a private club, where the complaint is intoxication, the club should be tactfully encouraged to handle its own problem. Such a club is not a public place and arrests are invalid.'' The 3rd Circuit court said <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON>'s handling of the case was in line with that policy, and therefore the city can be held liable for violating <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON>'s rights. The appeals court said city officials argued that `` although <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> could reasonably foresee serious harm befalling <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON>, he owed <PERSON> Powdrill </PERSON> no duty. We disagree.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has ruled that cities may be sued successfully in such cases when someone's rights are violated in accord with a municipal policy or custom. In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> officials said <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> `` did not create or exacerbate the allegedly dangerous condition. At most he can be charged with failing to exercise due care in investigating a crime, the burglary at the Cash Club.'' The city's appeal said there was no evidence <PERSON> Dlubak </PERSON> relied on the so-called hands-off policy toward private clubs when he left the matter in <LOCATION> Flenory </LOCATION>'s control. In a criminal case stemming from the incident, <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> DeVaughn </PERSON>, a disc jockey at the club, pleaded guilty to murder and was sentenced to 15 to 20 years in prison. The case is <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Horton </PERSON>, 88-816.
