picking up 5th graf pvs, `In a...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The trial of a retired librarian will hinge on whether a jury believes he was temporarily insane when he fired on children, shoppers and police officers during a seven-hour siege, killing six people. Lawyers for <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON>, 61, planned to argue that alcohol and psychiatric problems caused him to open fire with a semiautomatic rifle, a shotgun and a revolver outside his home in the coastal community of <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and at two adjacent shopping centers. Jury selection began today, with Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoon </PERSON> convening a pool of more than 100 people from which to select a 12-member jury and several alternates. The shooting spree April 23, 1987, led to 36 felony charges that could send <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> to the electric chair: six counts of first-degree murder, 28 of attempted murder and two of kidnapping. The trial was moved 75 miles west to <LOCATION> Bartow </LOCATION> after a telephone survey suggested that many people in central <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Brevard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> believed <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> guilty. In a videotaped interview after his arrest, <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> calmly told police he believed neighbors, strangers and supermarket employees were constantly spreading rumors that he was homosexual. He said he had to stop it. `` I just wanted people to leave me alone,'' he said in the tape shown publicly for the first time Thursday during a hearing. `` I had to do something to stop them. I know I'm not queer.'' But he added, `` I was drunk and crazy and I just do n't remember hurting anyone.'' Seemingly meek, <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> has a reputation as an arrogant demanding prisoner at <LOCATION> Brevard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jail </LOCATION>, where he has been held without bond since his arrest. He quit eating at one point, claiming that jailers were trying to poison him, and he had to be force-fed through a tube in his nose for several days. Most of the time, he was kept in the jail's medical unit, not ill or suicidal, but because officers feared he might be killed by other inmates. `` He is not a very likable person,'' said Sheriff <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. A court-appointed attorney announced an insanity defense early on, and lawyers for the public defender's office now handling the case have been proceeding along those lines. <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> was found competent to stand trial. Under <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law, a person can be found innocent by reason of insanity if they are unaware of their actions or unable to distinguish between right and wrong at the time. Investigators have said <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> confessed shortly after his arrest. In the videotape of his interrogation, <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> acknowledged firing his guns, which he seaid he took to the shopping centers to make people stop talking about him. `` I just suppose I wanted to scare some people,'' he said. `` I hope I made an impression on them.'' Prosecutors say that after cooking dinner for his wife, <PERSON> Malahat </PERSON>, who suffers from Parkinson's disease, he left their modest home and fired on neighborhood children, wounding a teen-age boy playing basketball. As investigators later reconstructed the crime, the gunman then drove to the nearby <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> Shopping Center and opened fire, first with one weapon and then another, leaving the parking lot of a supermarket littered with bodies. Three shoppers were killed and others wounded in the first outburst. The gunman then drove across a busy highway to the <LOCATION> Sabal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> shopping center, left his car and killed the first police officer to arrive. He wounded a second policeman, reloaded his revolver and fatally shot that officer between the eyes. The gunman then moved to the another supermarket, blasted out the storefront glass and burst in, spraying the store with bullets as some 100 customers and employees ran from the store or hid. One customer was killed. He found a clerk hiding in a store restroom and took her hostage. Police closed in and tried to persuade him to surrender. After the clerk escaped, police fired tear gas and stormed the store. <PERSON> Cruse </PERSON> stumbled out and was captured as he tried to flee, authorities said.
