<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 To recapitulate: <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> ripped <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> in a memo which surfaced mysteriously while <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> was on vacation. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> was hurt; <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>, not mentioned in the memo, stood by stoically. On Monday, host <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> returned to <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show and joked about the controversy that had engulfed the nation's top-rated breakfast show in his absence Weatherman <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> was not there; he was starting his own one-week vacation. An attempt to ease tensions by telephoning <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> on the air foundered embarrassingly when the connection was lost, and <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> and co-host <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Pauley </PERSON> were forced to ad-lib through the show's final moments. `` A very unusual Monday _ in many ways best forgot,'' said <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON>. It all started last week, when someone leaked to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Newsday </LOCATION> a memo <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> had written to `` Today'' producer <PERSON> Marty </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>. In it, <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> criticized reviewer <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalit </PERSON>, consumer reporters <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Horowitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Furness </PERSON> and medical reporter Dr. <PERSON> Art </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulene </PERSON>. The harshest words were reserved for <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s hokey, homey shtick, including his endless recitations of centenarians' birthdays. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> at first made light of the memo, but later said <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON>'s comments were hurtful and hinted he might leave `` If it's not real, and if there is n't an honest, genuine reconciliation, I do n't think I belong there,'' <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> said. Exit <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shalit </PERSON>, on vacation. Enter <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON>. `` Good to be back after what should have been a quiet vacation,'' said <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> at the top of Monday's show. `` The fact that it was n't is something we'll get into a little bit later, but first things first. <PERSON> Pauley </PERSON> welcomed him back. `` You were never far from our thoughts,'' she said wryly. Later on, <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> thanked callers for expressions of support, saying `` <PERSON> Jane </PERSON>, <PERSON> Willard </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> and I are very grateful.'' `` We do appreciate your concern, and despite what you may have heard or read in recent days, we are together and hopefully we're going to be with you for many years to come,'' said <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> `` Now that may come as sad news for those who have tried to capitalize on our differences, but rest assured, that ` Today' family is intact and still smiling, albeit through some pain,'' he continued. `` ` We'll still be here long after the recent headlines are forgotten. Enough said.'' Of course, it is not possible to say enough about the `` Today'' imbroglio. Midway through the show, <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> managed a crack after a news story about secret government documents found in discarded safe. `` You've got to be careful where you put documents these days,'' said <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON>, to peals of laughter. Then, at the show's end, came the phone-call fiasco. <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> said he intended to talk with <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> `` about vacation plans and onto some other things.'' He said he had talked to Scott several times since Saturday and before the show. `` This was going to be our little surprise before going off,'' <PERSON> Gumbel </PERSON> said, and he wished <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> happy birthday. Tuesday is <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>'s birthday. His 55th, not his 100th.
