<HEAD>Partial Eclipse Tuesday in West</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The sun will be partly obscured Tuesday morning in an eclipse visible in the western portions of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory reports. The sun will be as much as 80 percent hidden for residents of western <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, while lesser amounts will be obscured in other areas. The eclipse will not be visible at all east of a line running from about <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rapids </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, through <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The eclipse will begin at 8:17 a.m. PST, will reach its greatest extent at 10:07 a.m. and end at 11:58 a.m., the Observatory reported. Astronomers cautioned that the eclipse must not be watched directly because of danger of burning the eyes. The event can be watched indirectly with a pinhole projector or through darkened film made specifically for solar viewing.
