<HEAD>Le Crocodile Rates Third Michelin Star</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Le </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Crocodile </LOCATION> restaurant in <LOCATION> Strasbourg </LOCATION> was promoted Monday to three-star status in the <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> guide, giving owner-chef <PERSON> Emile </PERSON> <PERSON> Jung </PERSON> the ultimate accolade in French gastronomy. His was the only restaurant to be raised to the highest level in the Michelin galaxy, which this year lists only 19 three-star restaurants in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The red <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION>, known to gourmets the world over as the `` bible of gastronomy,'' awards three stars only to those restaurants with `` exceptional cuisine, worth a special journey.'' Four two-star restaurants lost one or both stars this time, including the <LOCATION> Beau </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rivage </LOCATION> in Condrieu near <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION>, which went from two stars to one; the Chantecler at the <ORGANIZATION> Negresco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hotel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nice </ORGANIZATION>, which dropped a star; the Cote d'Or at <ORGANIZATION> Nuits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georges </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Burgundy </LOCATION> which lost both its stars and Point in <LOCATION> Vienne </LOCATION> which disappeared from the guidebook. Twelve famous <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> restaurants lost their sole star, including <ORGANIZATION> Chez </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> les </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anges </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Flamberge </PERSON> and Olympe. `` I was suprised and thrilled,'' said <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocodile </PERSON>'s 47-year-old chef in a telephone interview from his restaurant in <LOCATION> Alsace </LOCATION>. `` Of course, I've been aiming for the highest quality for years. I'm constantly giving myself grades, not always awfully high. `` His food is superbly creative, with a strong basis in the local produce and traditions,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON>. Outstanding dishes include fresh `` sandre,'' a kind of pike cooked with juniper berries, with a delicate stuffing of sauerkraut, an Alsatian specialty. The first course jellied consomme with foie gras dice, another Alsatian specialty, is presented in a crown shape with a puree of leeks and potatoes in the center. `` <PERSON> Jung </PERSON>'s cellar is fabulous, not only in Alsatian wines but in wines from all over <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and the whole world, which is very rare,'' said <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON>. Celebrating its 80th anniversary _ it did not publish for nine years during the two world wars _ the 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> guide is accompanied by a quaint facsimile of the original 1900 little red book. In those days, the book was aimed not at gastronomes but at pioneers whose `` tin lizzies'' were subject to frequent breakdowns. Today, the guide bases its choices on good food on the many visits by anonymous inspectors, and it is considered the most serious hotel and restaurant guide in a country obsessed with food and wine. Last year, 720,000 copies were snapped up by drivers and epicures. `` The little free booklet was offered to buyers of <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> tires and was aimed at helping drivers change a tire, repair their cars or find garages,'' said <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON>. There were no restaurants listed then, only hotels with restaurants in cities other than <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` The guide was aimed at drivers going from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to the provinces,'' said <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON>. The top grade of three stars signaled the most expensive hotels offering rooms with relative luxury, such as electricity, including all meals with wine. It also indicated the eventual presence of a doctor or pharmacy in every town, no matter how small. This information was vital in days when drivers needed more than a week to get from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to the south of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The legendary <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> stars, which look like rosettes, were first awarded for gastronomy in 1926. They now are the ultimate in prestige for restaurants, and the 1989 guide lists 619 starred establishments. Among this year's demotions, Olympe's fall from one-star grace is particularly disappointing to those who root for women chefs. Olympe's owner, <PERSON> Dominique </PERSON> <PERSON> Nahmias </PERSON>, is popular among gastronomes. She still retains her three `` toques'' and rating of 18 out of 20 in another popular guidebook, the Gault-Millau guide. `` We have nothing against professional women cooks,'' said <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON>, noting that several women have stars and the chef of the two-starred Le Restaurant in <LOCATION> Lille </LOCATION> is <PERSON> Ghislaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Arabian </PERSON>, wife of the owner, <PERSON> Jean-Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Arabian </PERSON>. <PERSON> Naegellen </PERSON> said that for the first time a special listing is provided for restaurants with menus of $ 25 or less. <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> has consistently enlarged its scope with the times, and now travelers can note which establishments do n't allow pets, honor credit cards, have views and beach facilities or offer terrace or garden dining. The guide still covers the driving essentials, including distance between towns, repair garages, dealers, and night breakdown facilities.
