<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda Monday joined other Soviets criticizing the ministry in charge of agriculture, reprinting citizen comment that it is ineffective and useless. Commonly known as `` Gosagroprom,'' the governmental committee that oversees the agencies that run the nation's state-owned and collective farms has recently been broadly criticized in the press. Rumors swept <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> last week that the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leadership is planning to abolish the committee, which was formed under Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in 1985 when five agricultural ministries and some other state agencies were merged. The party's policy-making <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will meet this month and is expected to make reforms in agriculture to remedy chronic food shortages. An article published in Pravda on Monday said the paperwork produced by <PERSON> Gosagroprom </PERSON> indicates the ministry is n't overlooking serious problems, but that a closer look reveals `` it's possible to say it did not solve any big problems.'' People attending a party conference in <LOCATION> Kharkov </LOCATION>, a Ukrainian city 400 miles south of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, wrote a letter to the Supreme Soviet parliament calling for the dismantling of `` this monopolistic, ineffective, bureaucratic organization'' that hinders effective forms of farming, the article said. Pravda said <PERSON> Gosagroprom </PERSON> has made certain the farmer's dream of living as well as non-farmers who work in food processing remains just a dream. The most common words to Gosagroprom from farmers are: `` Give us resourses, and do n't bother our work,'' Pravda said. The government daily <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> also printed an article Monday by a doctor of economic sciences, <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buzdalov </PERSON>, that indicated there is consensus at least on the need to drastically cut back the size of <LOCATION> Gosagroprom </LOCATION>, starting with the regional organizations responsible for agriculture, known to the Soviets by the Russian-language acronym of RAPOs. `` The judgment on whether <PERSON> Gosagroprom </PERSON>, starting with <ORGANIZATION> RAPO </ORGANIZATION>, is necessary in its present form is no longer subject to debate, it seems,'' the economist wrote. The Politburo published a report Saturday saying it supported the creation of various types of farms to help alleviate the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s food shortage. The 12-member ruling body made no direct reference to abolishing <PERSON> Gosagroprom </PERSON>, but said new forms and methods of management were needed in the country's agricultural management. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has announced it will hold a plenum March 15-16.
