ration aides and congressional sources said the president was mindful of the odds against the nomination. They said some Republicans in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been pressing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to give the job to his national security adviser, <PERSON> Brent </PERSON> <PERSON> Scowcroft </PERSON>. Others mentioned as possible successors have included Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Warner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Rumsfeld </PERSON>, former <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Drew </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, former Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Augustine </PERSON>, chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Martin-Marietta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>.
