<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 No elk showed up, but it was n't for lack of trying as 43 contestants growled, grunted, chirped and squealed through what was billed as the world elk-calling championship. The contestants each had one minute to give their best rendition of bull and cow elk calls, while a panel of seven judges listened intently behind a wooden partition at the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> State Convention and Trade Center. About 1,000 people attended Sunday's finals of the contest, officially called the <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wapiti </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Elk -RRB- Calling Championships. Many of the callers, or `` buglers,'' heaved their shoulders and gyrated as they blew through two-foot long sections of rubber pipe that directed their screeching calls to all parts of the room in the convention center. One bugler brought a small tree and an armful of brush that he ripped apart to simulate the sound of an animal tramping through the woods. All but two of the callers had small rubber diaphragms in their mouths that they blew on to create the wide range of noises an elk makes. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlton </PERSON>, who has 25 years experience calling everything from alligators to turkeys, said most of the people who call elk do it so they can hunt them, but others are photographers or those who want excitement, he said. `` Imagine standing by a tree or just being out in the woods and if you can imitate that, out walks a 700-800 pound bull elk looking for you to run you away,'' he said. `` The excitement builds up when you see the antlers walking through the trees at you.''
