<HEAD>Government May Help Pay for Efforts to Assist Its Workers to Quit
Smoking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal government is considering helping pay the costs of programs that assist government workers in their efforts to quit smoking, officials said Monday. If the rule takes effect, the government will be following in the footsteps of many businesses, which have combined anti-smoking programs with workplace rules banning tobacco, according to the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. The federal <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Personnel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> is circulating the proposal, which would allow agencies use available funds for such programs, officials announced. `` Smoking cessation programs, particularly for federal employees, are long overdue. This is a positive step,'' <ORGANIZATION> OPM </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> said in a statement. Ms. <PERSON> Horner </PERSON> is a former smoker. The plan would require that employees get advance approval for reimbursement in the anti-smoking programs. The regulation is being prepared in the wake of a ruling by the comptroller general that funding could be approved because smoking is a major contributing cause of illnesses such as cancer, heart disease and emphysema. The growth of both government and business rules banning smoking in many workplaces has spurred many companies to contribute to programs to help workers quit, said <PERSON> Joann </PERSON> <PERSON> Schellenbech </PERSON>, assistant vice president for media relations at the Cancer Society in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` We think it's an excellent idea. Our surveys show that most smokers want to quit and need something to help them do that. The incentive of having program paid for may make a difference,'' she said. Costs for the programs range widely, she said, from free clinics conducted by non-profit groups to $ 200 and more for more-structured systems. The expense of the anti-smoking efforts can be justified by the savings in insurance costs, cuts in sick time and reductions in lost productivity, she said. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said that organization would have no immediate comment on the proposal.
