<HEAD>Supreme Court to Decide Case of Man Held Without Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> agreed Monday to decide whether state officials can be sued for damages in federal court by people involuntarily held at state mental hospitals without hearings required by state law. The justices voted to review a ruling that would allow such a federal lawsuit by a man held in a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> state hospital for five months without a hearing that state law said he should have had within 48 hours. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> authorities contend the man should be limited to suing in state court. <PERSON> Darrell </PERSON> <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> was found wandering along a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> highway on Dec. 7, 1981. He was taken to a <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> community health services center where he was held for three days. During that time, <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> was hallucinating. He said he believed he was in heaven. After his stay at the center, <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> was transferred to the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, where he remained until May 7, 1982. Despite a state law that entitled him to a hearing within 48 hours to challenge his detention and treatment, <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> did not receive a hearing. His federal suit alleged that various officials and employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> acted `` with willful, wanton and reckless disregard of and indifference to'' his due-process rights. The suit invoked a much-used federal civil rights law. A federal judge threw out the suit, ruling that <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> was barred from filing it because he could win adequate relief _ including monetary damages _ by suing under personal-injury law in state court. A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the dismissal, but the entire appeals court voted 8-5 last March 18 to reinstate the suit. The trial judge and three-judge appellate panel had relied on a 1981 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision in which the justices limited federal civil rights lawsuits when certain state court remedies exist. But the full 11th Circuit court ruled that the 1981 decision `` does not apply to procedural due-process violations when the state is in the position to provide pre-deprivation process.'' Because <PERSON> Burch </PERSON> could have been given a hearing before his right to liberty was deprived, the appeals court said, `` post-deprivation remedies can not provide due process.'' The 1981 ruling also dealt with prison inmates who alleged they wrongly had been deprived of their property rights, not their right of liberty. The case is <PERSON> Zinmermon </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Burch </PERSON>, 87-1965.
