emphasize enough that this was a catch-up increment'' recommended by the panel `` to keep government pay abreast of inflation.'' <PERSON> Quello </PERSON>'s salary is $ 80,700 and he said that `` with a moderate lifestyle, I have no problem living well on my government salary. ... But the salary level simply does not reflect the complexity or importance of commission responsibilities.'' He said that killing the salary proposal did not serve the public interest `` because it doomed much-needed reforms on eliminating congressional honoraria, limiting outside income and changing campaign fund laws.'' On another issue, <PERSON> Quello </PERSON> also repeated his view that it is essential that free, over-the-air television survive in any future scenario in which telephone companies are allowed to carry TV signals on fiber-optic networks. `` Only broadcasting, not cable or phone fiber, has a government licensed obligation to provide TV service to the public,'' <PERSON> Quello </PERSON> said, adding that broadcasting is the `` principal source of local news and government affairs, of vital local services like traffic, road, weather, school closing reports and emergency bulletins. And only broadcasting has a program-issues public file requirement for license renewal and for public inspection.'' He said it may be necessary for the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to require telephone companies to provide a basic antenna service to transmit local broadcast signals at no charge. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> is considering proposing that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> lift cross-ownership restrictions that prevent telephone companies from competing with cable TV systems in the phone company service area.
