<SECOND>AM-India-Liquor,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bootleg Liquor Kills 130 in India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARODA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three people were arrested for supplying home-brewed liquor that killed at least 130 people and left 251 ill in the only Indian state that bans alcohol, authorities said Monday. Doctors said 151 of those 251 hospitalized were critically ill and probably would die. At least 25 people have been blinded by the lethal moonshine. In addition to the three arrested, several policemen have been suspended for failing to avert the tragedy in the city of <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION>, the local government said. Baroda is a major industrial center in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>, the only Indian state where alcohol is banned. The city 560 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> is home to 2.5 million people. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said the son of one supplier and the son of a prominent local politician are among those killed. The liquor normally is brewed from ethyl alcohol, alum and matured spirits. But this time, industrial methyl alcohol was mixed to the brew called `` lattha,'' which is sold in plastic sacks for 10 cents. Methyl alcohol paralyzes the central nervous system. Press Trust said many victims became dizzy and complained of nausea and stomach aches before losing consciousness. Most survivors were too ill to speak, but one told the <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency the only difference he noticed was the liquor was `` sweeter than normal.'' A doctor at state-run Sir <ORGANIZATION> Siyaji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> said groaning victims crowded against each other on the floor, on stretchers, and occasionally three to a bed. `` We do not have enough bottles of glucose to even administer first aid to the victims,'' the doctor said on condition of anonymity. <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION>'s chief minister, <PERSON> Amarsinh </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaudhary </PERSON>, ordered an investigation and promised action against the police officials who failed to avert the disaster, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported. It said most victims were poor laborers who bought the liquor Saturday morning after receiving their monthly wages. The first deaths were reported about midnight Saturday, it said. As news of the deaths emerged, police fanned out across <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION> with loudspeakers blaring warnings about the liquor. About 300 people have died in seven illicit liquor cases in <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> in the last decade, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said. Two previous cases occurred in <LOCATION> Baroda </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, meanwhile, a court arraigned two alleged moonshiners Monday after police raided the largest illegal still ever found in the country. Police discovered a modern facility capable of producing 1,000 liters of high-grade alcohol a day hidden in stalls on a horse farm in eastern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Small-scale bootlegging is not uncommon in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, where the government has imposed a high alcohol tax to discourage drinking. A fifth of the cheapest scotch costs $ 32 and gin $ 27.60 at state stores which have a monopoly on alcohol sales. The moonshine sells for about a third of the state price.
