<HEAD>Housing Affordability Measure Down in January</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An index measuring the ability of a typical American family to buy a home dropped in January, reflecting increases in housing prices and mortgage interest rates, a real estate trade group said Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realtors </ORGANIZATION> said its affordability index was at 108 in January, down from 111.2 in December. It was the largest month-to-month drop since a similar decline in January 1988. The new January number means that a family earning the median income of $ 32,207 annually had 8 percent more income than needed to qualify for a mortgage covering 80 percent of the purchase price of a median-priced home. The median price for an existing home in January was $ 91,500, meaning half the homes sold for more and half for less. January's median was up $ 2,800 from the previous month The mortgage rate used to calculate the index rose to 9.61 percent in January from 9.59 percent, representing a composite of fixed and adjustable rates. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuccillo </PERSON>, chief economist for the real estate group, said rising interest rates are likely to dampen home buying for much of the spring, particularly for first-time buyers. `` When rates are up, the first people shut out are borderline buyers,'' said the group's president, <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gribin </PERSON>. `` Having to spend even a few dollars more a month for mortgage payments can keep them out of the market altogether.'' The affordability index has been above 100 since June 1986.
