ON>'s G-2 intelligence section. He joined the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 and spent most of his career in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> working as an analyst of intercepted radio and telephone traffic and coded messages. Under the plea agreement, <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> waived his right to a grand jury-type hearing to determine if a court-martial was warranted. He also agreed to be tried by a single military judge, rather than a panel of officers. Hall also agreed to submit to `` unlimited debriefing'' and polygraph examination by government officials and to testify, if called, at grand jury proceedings against <PERSON> Huseyin </PERSON> <PERSON> Yildirim </PERSON>, a Turkish-born, naturalized citizen to whom <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> allegedly passed the classified information. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said through a military spokesman that the defense would have no comment on <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s motivation for passing classified information until after he has been questioned by <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON> during the closed part of the court-martial. The maximum punishment Hall could receive, since the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> agreed not to seek the death penalty, is life in prison, forefeiture of all pay and allowances, dishonorable discharge and a fine. The plea agreement, however, outlines the sentence that Hall will receive, unless the presiding judge, who is not permitted to see the sentencing agreement, imposes a lighter sentence. If the judge imposes a sentence that is harsher than the one in the agreement, the agreement will prevail. <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> will not `` comment at any time now or in the future'' on the espionage case or his involvement with classified materials while in the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. Part of the plea agreement requires that <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> sign away any profits that might accrue to him in the future from any publication based on his involvement in the espionage case. A statement of the facts in the espionage case, which <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> told <PERSON> Eggers </PERSON> was `` mostly written by myself,'' was included in the plea agreement, but it was not made public. <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> <PERSON> Sr. </PERSON>, his wife, and one of his children were in the military courtroom when the court-martial began. They are expected to testify later in the week in Hall's behalf `` His family was totally uninvolved and unaware of his activities,'' <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> said, `` and Hall will spend the remainder of his life working to prove that he eventually deserves to be reunited with his wife and children.''
