<HEAD>Court Extends Custody for Palme Suspect Despite Criticism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court extended the custody Monday for a man suspected of the 1986 murder of Prime Minister <PERSON> Olof </PERSON> <PERSON> Palme </PERSON> amid charges that his continued detention was aimed at winning a confession. It was the sixth time that <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>'s district court granted prosecutors' requests to hold <PERSON> Christer </PERSON> <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, who was arrested Dec. 14. <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>, 41, who has a history of violent crime and mental problems, is suspected of shooting the four-term prime minister in downtown <LOCATION> Stockholm </LOCATION>. Prosecutors have said they have circumstantial evidence against him but they need further evidence to file charges. <PERSON> Astrid </PERSON> <PERSON> Holgersson </PERSON>, an expert in witness psychology at <ORGANIZATION> Stockholm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, charged that <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s detention in solitary confinement for nearly three months was a `` psychological assault'' that could lead to a `` false confession.'' <PERSON> Holgersson </PERSON> wrote in the <ORGANIZATION> Dagens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nyheter </ORGANIZATION> newspaper that such treatment `` can after a few days lead to serious psychological disorders ... and a ` confession' aimed at getting out of a psychologically unbearable situation.'' She said it appeared to be an example of `` malpractice against an individual by the Swedish judicial system.'' <PERSON> Pettersson </PERSON>'s lawyer <PERSON> Arne </PERSON> <PERSON> Liljeros </PERSON>, who objected to previous detention orders, raised no protest against the latest court decision. `` The conditions for my client are OK,'' he told <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> TT </ORGANIZATION> news agency. `` He is not subjected to any psychological assault.'' `` We must accept that he is forced to be in jail for a while. After all, there are circumstances against him,'' <PERSON> Liljero