<HEAD>Two More Die in Avalanche in French Alps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRENOBLE, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An avalanche in the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alps </LOCATION> on Monday killed two men, including a ski instructor, who were skiing off the trail near the Val d'Isere resort, police said. The instructor, <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, and an unidentified companion were killed in the avalanche near <LOCATION> Tignes </LOCATION>, eight miles from the Val d'Isere ski resort, police in <LOCATION> Grenoble </LOCATION> said. A third man was hospitalized in critical condition, said the police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. A woman skiing with the group was found uninjured about 10 minutes after the avalanche by rescue workers who saw her ski sticking through the snow, police said. The group had been off trail and was ignoring elementary safety rules, police said. Seven avalanches reported over the weekend left two skiers dead and dozens injured. French authorities have advised skiers to stay on the alpine trails, especially during the warm afternoons.
