<HEAD>Government and Opposition Clash on Wage Indexation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government and opposition negotiators had a stormy session Monday over a Solidarity proposal to reduce 60 percent inflation by tying wages to the cost of living, opposition economists said. The `` round table'' talks on economic and political reform entered their fifth week with delegates from both sides under pressure from their leaders to reach agreement by late this month. <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, who founded Solidarity in 1980 and is trying to get the union made legal again, said he probably will have his second meeting with Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> in less than a week about problems in the talks. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and leaders of provincial party organizations convened to hear reports on progress. The meeting was called a `` consultation,'' not a formal party session, but was expected to produce advice for the government negotiators. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has said he expects new `` political decisions'' intended to move the talks forward. About the indexing question, opposition economist <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Wielowieyski </PERSON> said: `` We had the impression today the government side blocked itself. ... We are going to face a very difficult situation tomorrow. I think the situation is very difficult and very dangerous,'' <PERSON> Wielowieyski </PERSON>, a member of the working group on economic issues, said officials feared indexing would limit the authority of managers who control pay decisions. He said Solidarity leaders decided Sunday the government must agree to a form of indexation if it expects union agreement to a package of reforms that includes opposition membership in Parliament. `` Our demand for indexing is the indispensable condition,'' <PERSON> Wielowieyski </PERSON> said. Solidarity believes wages must be indexed to inflation, at least temporarily, to give workers some sense of security while economic reforms are introduced. Deputy Premier <PERSON> Ireneusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Sekula </PERSON> said on state television the government believes some indexing is needed, but `` it has to be introduced in a prudent manner so it does not disturb ... the motivating function of pay.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> by train Monday from <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where he works as a shipyard electrician, and he met with opposition delegates to the talks, said <PERSON> Piotr </PERSON> <PERSON> Konopka </PERSON>, a spokesman for the union leader. He would not give details. Working groups on trade union problems and youth issues also reported no progress Monday. Although the union has resolved the issue of how to legalize Solidarity and other unions, it is stalled on the mechanics of organizing. The youth subgroup had no problems with a proposal to make the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> legal again, but government negotiators said they want a broader agreement under which the opposition would endorse a statement on values in rearing children. `` Today's discussion of the youth table resembled a mental hospital rather than negotiations,'' said <PERSON> Andrzej </PERSON> <PERSON> Celinski </PERSON>, leader of the opposition team. <PERSON> Slawomir </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiatr </PERSON>, a government delegate, said it was possible no agreement would be reached in the youth talks, but added that the decision to legalize the student association might be made at a higher level. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has expressed optimism in recent days about the unprecedented talks between communist authorities and the opposition movement led by Solidarity. The talks are aimed at producing a compromise under which the government would legalize Solidarity and other banned groups in exchange for their help with a reform program. Solidarity, the first independent union movement in the Soviet bloc, was banned after martial law was imposed in December 1981.
