<HEAD>Channel One Pitches Jeans, Anti-Drug Message with News at High Schools</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Toi is cq in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Paid pitches for jeans, a candy bar and dandruff shampoo were mixed in with a fast-paced menu of current events Monday as Channel One, the televised news show for teen-agers, had its first school day. The paid advertising on the show, which is produced by Knoxville-based <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> LP </ORGANIZATION>, has enraged some education groups who want Big Business barred from making sales pitches to students inside the classroom. The fourth 30-second commercial was a public service announcement for the Partnership for a Drug-Free <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Students, teachers and parents who witnessed Channel One's debut at Central High expressed few reservations about the ads. ` It's fine with me,'' said <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> <PERSON> Bible </PERSON>, a 14-year-old freshman. ` You get more pressure from other students than you do from the commercials.'' <PERSON> Toi </PERSON> <PERSON> McCane </PERSON>, a 17-year-old senior, said the commercials `` are just the same thing you get on the news at night.'' The 12-minute program included two minutes of commercials. <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> is a media concern that has developed magazines and posters that can be used by advertisers to reach narrowly defined audiences, such as people in doctors' waiting rooms. Channel One is <ORGANIZATION> Whittle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>' first venture into television, and groups such as the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parent-Teacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secondary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Principals </ORGANIZATION> are opposing sending commercials into school along with the news show. ` They are trying to make it a part of every school day, and this medium has a much stronger impact than any other,'' said <PERSON> Tari </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshal </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the National PTA. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON>, the company's chairman, said schools ca n't afford the equipment and level of programming he is providing as part of the Channel One project The company has provided each of the six test schools with about $ 50,000 worth of television monitors, video recording equipment and a satellite dish on which they can receive the daily show. In addition to Central, the show debuted Monday at <ORGANIZATION> Billerica </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Billerica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mumford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Gahr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cerritos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Eisenhower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Middle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kan </PERSON>. The sixth test school, <ORGANIZATION> Withrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION>, was closed Monday by bad weather. If the test proves successful, Whittle hopes to expand it nationally to as many as 8,000 schools in the fall of 1990. In exchange for the equipment, the schools agree to run the news show once each school day. After the show began with flashy graphics, two youthful anchors read headlines illustrated with purchased film footage about the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strike, the battle over <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>'s nomination as secretary of defense and life as a Soviet teen-ager. The show's last segment dealt with the controversy over Channel One itself. In <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON>'s senior homeroom class, all 20 students appeared to follow the show intently, fidgeting only during the shampoo commercial. Whittle gave the show high marks for content, but said the broadcast's pacing needed some work and his anchors needed to `` loosen up a bit.'' He said the complaints had not deterred any advertisers who have signed up for the test run which will involve 25 shows over the next seven weeks. Eight advertisers have signed up, he said, and he is courting four more. No show will have more than two minutes of commercials, <PERSON> Whittle </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffmeister </PERSON>, superintendent of the <LOCATION> Knox </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> public school system, said he thinks the show's educational value was worth two minutes of paid ads. Besides, he said, `` kids do n't pay a lot of attention to commercials anyway.''
