<HEAD>Christian Troops Patrol Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Helicopter gunships and navy gunboats of the army's Christian command patrolled <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s territorial waters under Druze rocket fire Monday to prevent foreign merchant ships from using illegal port facilities operated by feuding militias. The move, aimed at choking off the main revenues of Christian and Moslem private armies, has triggered a political crisis in the Moslem camp. Police said neither of the army's two French-built Gazelle gunships was hit when militiamen of Druze warlord <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON> fired rocket launchers near the port of <LOCATION> Jiye </LOCATION>, 15 miles south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. To underscore Moslem objections to the Christian patrols, the Moslem army command ordered the closing of a Green Line crossing point linking the capital's <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> and Moslem sectors only one week after rival military forces reopened it. A communique issued by the command of Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Sami </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatib </PERSON>, who heads Moslem army units in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, said the decision to close the crossing at <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port was made on orders from Acting Prime Minister <PERSON> Salim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>' Moslem cabinet. The communique said the Christians' sea and air patrols were `` provocative acts.'' The makeshift harbor at <LOCATION> Jiye </LOCATION> has been the main sea outlet for the Druze community, a Moslem sect based mainly in the <LOCATION> Chouf </LOCATION> mountains, since they captured it from the Christians in 1985. A <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> communique said foreign ships heading for <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> have been warned not to enter any of the militia-controlled harbors along the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> country's 110-mile coastline. The ban was ordered Sunday by Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, who heads the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> military cabinet vying for power with <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON>' Syrian-backed government. It was part of <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s campaign to restore state authority, eroded by 14 years of civil war in which Christian and Moslem militias took over many government functions. The militias use the ports to bring in arms and supplies as well as imported goods sold in the areas they control, depriving the state treasury of an estimated $ 100 million a year in customs duties. `` We're not forcibly shutting militia harbors or blockading them. ... We are merely blocking foreign ships from going there,'' a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said on condition of anonymity. `` If a ship insists on violating the ban, it will be seized and forced to sail into <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> port to question its captain before beginning legal procedures,'' said the spokesman. He listed five legal ports _ <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tripoli </LOCATION> north of the capital and <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION> and Tyre to the south. To supervise the new ban, <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> revived a maritime authority made up of representatives from the public works ministry, the navy, air force, police and the customs department. <PERSON> Hoss </PERSON> said Monday that the ban could undermine `` the positive mood that has lately emerged about a possible end to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s plight.'' He was referring to mediation efforts by an <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> committee set up in January to help resolve a constitutional crisis that has left the country without a president for 162 days and threatens to formalize its de facto partition into Christian and Moslem cantons. President <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gemayel </PERSON> appointed <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> to head