<HEAD>Soviet Coal Miners End Five-Day Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100 coal miners ended a five-day strike Monday after the government agreed to correct their pay system, a dissident reported. <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON>, a Moscow-based journalist, said sources in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> reported that 115 miners had been striking while underground since Thursday and began a hunger strike two days ago. <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION>, with a population of 90,000, is 1,200 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. It is in the <LOCATION> Pechora </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION>, one of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s major coal mining regions that in 1985 produced 28 million metric tons of bituminous coal. Workers in the Northern Mine began the strike to protest increased work orders, to demand replacement of the facility's director and chief economist and a reduction of the management staff, according to <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> He said the strikers also demanded changes in the salary disbursement system. A group of supporters, who called their organization Solidarity after the independent union movement in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, pressed the miners' case with authorities while the strikers remained underground, according to <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> He said Soviet Coal Minister <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shchadov </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> Saturday, negotiated with the strikers and promised to partially meet their demands including paying them 158,000 rubles -LRB- $ 254,800 -RRB- to compensate for problems in the salary system. <PERSON> Grigoryants </PERSON> said the miners announced the end of the strike on Monday. The Soviet government has traditionally claimed that strikes are inconsistent with the Communist system that places priority on the interests of workers. But last year there were strikes of an unprecedented scale and length in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in the dispute over control of the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>.
