<HEAD>Metzenbaum Seeks Review of Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> urged the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to review the antitrust implication of the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger because he said cable television customers could be big losers in the merger between the media giants. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said there were `` strong indications'' that the $ 18 billion merger between <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> could substantially reduce competition and diversity in the communications and entertainment field, particularly in the cable television industry. `` Such a development is especially disturbing in light of a continuing trend toward further concentration and reduced possibilities for meaningful competition in cable television,'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said in a letter to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rule </PERSON>, the assistant attorney general in charge of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s antitrust division. `` I ... urge you to undertake a careful and thorough review of this proposal,'' said <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on antitrust, monopolies and business rights. <PERSON> Vickie </PERSON> <PERSON> Togans </PERSON>, a staff assistant in Rule's office, said the letter had not been received there Monday. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said the merger, which was announced Saturday, would link two of the world's leading media and entertainment conglomerates, creating a company worth $ 18 billion. Time publishes Time, People, Sports Illustrated and Fortune magazines, and owns <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest pay cable service, along with <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION>'s sister cable service, <PERSON> Cinemax </PERSON>. Time also owns <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's second largest cable system <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> owns the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> movie and television studios, <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, along with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, the fifth largest cable system in the nation. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said less than 1 percent of the 8,000 communities nationwide served by cable have more than one cable system. `` Cable is an unregulated monopoly throughout the entire country,'' he said. He said a <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger could extend the dominance of the larger multisystem cable operators over small cable companies. `` With the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> systems, there is an even greater incentive for Time to deny competing technologies its existing programming _ and the new programming which <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> is expected to create.'' `` It is this ability to control both the conduit for programming -LRB- the cable wire -RRB- and the content of the programming -LRB- through <ORGANIZATION> MSO </ORGANIZATION> equity interest in programming ventures -RRB- that poses the greatest threat to consumers,'' <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said. `` The absence of competition in the delivery of cable programming means that consumers have no protection against unrestrained rate hikes. The de facto editorial control which MSOs can exercise over new programming threatens diversity of information and entertainment sources available to cable viewers,'' he said.
