<HEAD>With AM-Tower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Heflin No Stranger To Partisan Battles Over Presidential Appointments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In becoming the first Democrat to support <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nominee for secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> followed the rule he always applies to presidential appointments. `` My general approach is that the president is entitled to have his appointments'' unless it can be proved `` that the person is flawed or that he would be a detriment to the country,'' <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> said last week after meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to discuss the Tower nomination. In the case of Tower, <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> said he was not convinced after reading the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> reports that the former <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator has a drinking problem that would disqualify him from serving in the nation's top defense post. Had Tower been nominated for a lifetime judgeship, <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> might well have voted against confirmation. But he said the fact that the secretary of defense serves at the pleasure of the president makes <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> responsible and accountable for Tower's conduct. `` It is the president's cabinet,'' <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> said, `` not <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' cabinet. Being at the center of a partisan battle over a presidential appointee is nothing new for <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, a 67-year-old ex-Marine and former <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> chief justice who was former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s most consistent Democratic support in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. As a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> frequently found himself holding the balance of power when controversial <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointments divided the panel along partisan lines. His vote in committee against <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s nomination of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 helped persuade other Southern Democrats to oppose <PERSON> Bork </PERSON>, who eventually was rejected by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> also cast the deciding vote on the only other <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> appointees rejected by the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the nomination of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Reynolds </PERSON> to the third-ranking post in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the nomination of Jefferson B. Sessions III to a federal judgeship in south <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> was widely criticized in his home state for opposing both <PERSON> Bork </PERSON> and Sessions, but his popularity does not appear to have waned in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> despite the increasingly tendency in recent years of the state's voters to support Republican candidates. During his first <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> campaign in 1978, <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> was so popular that then-Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> decided not to challenge him. <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON> carried all but five of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s 69 counties in the Democratic primary, and won move than 90 percent of the general election vote. He was re-elected in 1984 with 63 percent of the vote over a conservative <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> congressman. His only announced challenger in 1990 is state Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabiness </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Birmingham </LOCATION>, a businessman who chaired the state's delegation to the Republican convention that nominated <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for president.
