<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An Iranian trade fair has successfully introduced merchandise from the Islamic state to the Lebanese market, drawing 100,000 visitors and selling $ 60,000 worth of goods a day. `` Many deals have been struck between Iranian companies and <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> businessmen, both Christian and Moslem,'' said <PERSON> Abbas </PERSON> <PERSON> Zaferian </PERSON>, director of the `` Second Trade Exhibition of the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>.'' `` I can not give you a final figure, but I can assure you that the number is large,'' he added. <PERSON> Zaferian </PERSON> said 70 companies are participating in the fair that opened Feb. 20 at a hotel in a Syrian-controlled district of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. It ends Tuesday. He refused to say whether the fair had political motives, such as supporting the 1 million Shiite Moslems who make up <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s largest single sect `` I only answer questions related to the commercial aspect,'' <PERSON> Zaferian </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and its mainly Shiite Moslem population back the <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, militia which seeks to set up an Islamic state modeled on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> intermittently fought fierce battles from April until January against <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION>, its Syrian-backed rival. After 500 people were killed, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> brokered a truce that currently is holding. At the entrance to the fair, Iranian flags and huge portraits of revolutionary patriarch <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> contrast sharply with other events at the seaside hotel: a cheese and wine party and a Greek night. Cheap prices make the Iranian goods attractive not only to Shiites, but also to other low-income and middle-income groups. People flock to the exhibition, where an air conditioner is priced at $ 90, a gas stove at $ 39 and a pair of tennis shoes costs $ 2. The fair may mark a breakthrough for Iranian-made products in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, despite their mediocre quality. Nobody seemed to mind the long wait to park in the hotel's spacious grounds, or meticulous security checks `` It's worth it. I can not afford to pay $ 40 for a pair of jeans. Here, it's only $ 7,'' said a woman who identified herself as <PERSON> Soha </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem. `` The quality may not be the same as French designer ones, but we're living through hard days and jeans are jeans.'' A fair salesman said <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s first trade exhibition in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> last year provided an opportunity to assess the market. ` That was just an exhibition. People could not purchase any of the products. But it helped make this year's exhibition successful,'' said the salesman, who refused to give his name. Cars assembled in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> were popular, with prices ranging from $ 4,200 for a <ORGANIZATION> Renault </ORGANIZATION> 5 to $ 13,000 for a Range Rover. A government education stand was one of the fair's biggest, boasting a bookshop, a children's corner and a video room playing an Iranian film, `` The <ORGANIZATION> Eagles </ORGANIZATION>.'' The film showed Iranian jets mounting an attack against bases in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Jubilant crowds watching the movie shouted `` Allaho Akbar!'' -LRB- `` God is Great!'' -RRB- as the jets unleashed their bombs. Wealthier people also attended the fair, but for different goods. `` I came here to look at the silk carpets and buy some caviar and pistachio nuts,'' said a woman whose hand glittered with diamond rings. These luxuries are the only Iranian goods imported to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> regularly, although the trade is minimal. A silk carpet runner measuring a bit more than 5 feet by 3 feet cost $ 1,827, and two pounds of caviar sold for $ 200. `` The caviar shelves were wiped -LRB- clean -RRB- during the first few days,'' said <PERSON> Zaferian </PERSON>. `` People would buy it here for $ 200 and sell it outside for at least double the price.''
