<HEAD>Extradition Approved of Argentines Accused of Stealing Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> issued extradition orders Monday for two Argentine couples accused of taking four children from parents who were arrested and presumed executed by security forces a decade ago. During nearly two years of house arrest in <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, the couples appealed lower court rulings and argued they were victims of persecution by the Argentine government of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. The court ruling said: `` It was not proven that both couples are persecuted politically, and in accordance with the extradition treaty signed by <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> in 1889 in <LOCATION> Montevideo </LOCATION>, the appeals are rejected.'' `` After two years, this is very good news,'' said <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Quijano </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s ambassador. In a domestic political development, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s main opposition party filed documents Monday seeking recognition that would allow it to enter national elections set for May 1. <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Authentic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, indicated it still might boycott the elections unless the provisional government of Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> changes voting laws and procedures. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> overthrew President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, a general who had ruled since 1954, in a coup Feb. 3. The kidnapping case strained relations between the neighboring <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> countries. Ambassador <PERSON> Quijano </PERSON> was recalled for for several months last year after Attorney General <PERSON> Clotildo </PERSON> <PERSON> Jimenez </PERSON> <PERSON> Benitez </PER