CATION> Argentina </LOCATION> they will be able to put things right,'' <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> said. Grandmothers of the Plaza de Mayo, an Argentine human rights group, claims <PERSON> Miara </PERSON>'s 11-year-old twin sons <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matias </PERSON> <PERSON> Angel </PERSON> are <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosetti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, whose parents were arrested during the `` dirty war.'' Their mother was never seen again but the father, <PERSON> Gustavo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosetti </PERSON>, survived, was released and now is a lawyer in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. No one answered the telephone Monday at the office of <PERSON> Miara </PERSON>'s lawyer Asked for comment Monday, a spokeswoman for the Grandmothers said they expected the decision but had no formal notification of it. She would not identify the supposed biological parents of the <PERSON> Bianco </PERSON> children. The group was set up in 1977 to trace the children who disappeared and were presumed killed in the anti-leftist campaign. Investigators for <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s civilian government say at least 8,960 people were killed but human rights groups put the toll nearer 30,000. According to the Grandmothers, about 300 babies were born in captivity or taken with their mothers to clandestine detention centers. The group has helped reunite about 50 children with their biological families since <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> took office in December 1983.
