<HEAD>Milan Eases Its Way Into The 1990s</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MIL12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mood in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> is relaxed as Italian fashion enters the 1990s. Milanese designers presenting ready-to-wear collections for fall-winter 1989-1990 this week are not forcing outlandish ideas on a reluctant public for the sake of creativity. Rather, they are content to tailor beautiful clothes in colors and styles which are attuned to the needs of the modern woman. <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s most flamboyant designer, <PERSON> Gianni </PERSON> <PERSON> Versace </PERSON>, said that as fashion embarks on a new decade there is a need for `` looks more in keeping with the times.'' He thinks women should be free to choose between skirts and pants and to decide for themselves the length of a hemline, `` provided the fit is easy, truly comfortable, practically a home away from home.'' For the most part, the collections seen thus far on the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> runway are helping women to do just that. Styles are mainly soft and sporty, with pants overshadowing skirts, cozy sweaters replacing fussy blouses, and myriads of generously cut jackets, big comfortable coats, and flattering capes to face up to the rigors of the winter season. Hemlines play to the needs and tastes of all, from a few short versions to the all-purpose knee length, to the calf length championed by the young. When it comes to skirts, <PERSON> Versace </PERSON>, who presented his new collection Sunday night, does not practice what he preaches. His new skirt in clinging jersey is so short and tight that anyone wearing it risks being arrested for indecent exposure. For nighttime the skirt demurely descends to the ankle in black chiffon, only to be ripped up the side straight to the hip bone. <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> has always felt most at home with sombre shades of black gray and brown in keeping with the grim, smoggy skies of this northern industrial city. But no Italian can live without color, and designers have always perked up their collections with bright shades. This season is particularly vivid with the favorite palette a fall scheme of pumpkin and tangerine, plum and grape, crimson and fuchsia, apple and moss green. A wide variety of yellows and blues also turn up, as well as gaily colored prints. Never one to go along with the pack, <ORGANIZATION> Krizia </ORGANIZATION>, who usually favors glitzy clothes in shimmery fabrics, showed the most somber collection seen thus far on the runway. Not only were the colors almost exclusively in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> fog shades, but the style was uncharacteristically puritanical with long wool jersey dresses or mohair skirts worn under straight three-quarter length jackets by day, and demure gray evening gowns with lace bodice and bunched tafetta skirt. In general there is much more wool than silk in next winter's fashion, another concession to a sporty practical wardrobe Best at this woolly look was queen of cashmere <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Biagiotti </PERSON>, who had her show late Sunday. For the past decade, <PERSON> Biagiotti </PERSON> has been holding the working woman's banner high with soft and elegant cashmere fashion, easy to wear and easy to pack. The novelty of her collection this season is in the intricate ruffled workmanship in capes, sweaters and gowns to look like flower arrangements. Her favorite shades are rose and fuchsia, as well as her trademark white. The new casual look was no trouble for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Varty </PERSON>, the designer behind the Byblos label, popular for its young sporty style. <PERSON> Varty </PERSON> also showed Monday, the second day of the five-day <ORGANIZATION> Milan </ORGANIZATION> ready-to-wear collections. Next winter the Byblos woman will wear cozy jackets in bright shades of purple, blue and chartreuse, with shawl collar and extra-wide sleeves in warm shearling or bulky wool, gaily printed dirndl skirts, and heavy-knit sweaters with cheery floral motifs.
</TEXT>
