<FIRST>r a AM-AIDS-Drugs     03-06 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS-Drugs,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group To Import Drugs For AIDS Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug buyers club announced plans Monday to provide American AIDS patients with prescription drugs from abroad that have not been approved for use in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The People with <ORGANIZATION> AIDS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> said it would rely on foreign doctors to obtain the prescription drugs, then pass them along at cost to AIDS patients. To get a three-month supply of a drug, an AIDS patient must present a physician's prescription or note, group officials said at a news conference. Although they described the plan as unprecedented, they said it would not violate Food and Drug Administration rules. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said it would allow people with life-threatening illnesses to import personal supplies of unapproved drugs. But until now the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> group and other buyers clubs have only imported drugs that do nt require a prescription in the foreign country. Anyone wishing to legally obtain such drugs had to travel abroad and get a prescription from a physician there. `` We're saving people the trip and the importation expenses,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Callen </PERSON>, a founder of the group. Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, has declined to say if his agency would try to stop the drug importation effort, but said any action probably would depend on what drugs the group imports and how it does so. One will be fluconazole, which has been approved by several European nations as an anti-fungal medication for use against meningitis and AIDS. It is seen by some physicians and AIDS patients as an effective yet mild alternative to amphotericin B, a drug which must be taken intravenously once a week and whose harsh side effects include shakes and fever. Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> there have been 49,976 deaths from AIDS since June 1981. <PERSON> Callen </PERSON> said his group would decide which other drugs to import based on criteria such as toxicity, cost, effectiveness and availability. It is unclear how many patients might use the service, he said. Although <PERSON> Callen </PERSON> said the group would try to keep drug costs as low as possible, some AIDS remedies are relatively expensive. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutchnik </PERSON>, an AIDS patient whom the group supplied with fluconazole, said a daily dosage cost about $ 23, and was not covered by insurance because it was not FDA-approved. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on Monday quoted group officials as saying they would obtain the drugs through foreign doctors. But <PERSON> Callen </PERSON> said at the news conference that they had decided `` not to be fully forthcoming about our precise means'' of importation. One possibility, he said, would be to put a patient directly in touch with a foreign physician who would send the drug. AIDS patient advocates have criticized the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> for being overly cautious about approving AIDS drugs, arguing that they do not have time to wait for more tests on drugs deemed controversial by the agency. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> says it has a responsibility to protect Americans from drugs that could be useless or harmful, but `` something is wrong when doctors feel compelled to send patients overseas'' to obtain drugs, said Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Seitzman </PERSON>, a physician with a large AIDS practice. He said several of his patients have gone to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to obtain fluconazole. The People with <ORGANIZATION> AIDS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> has been supplying about 2,000 AIDS patients with non-prescription drugs from abroad which have not been approved for use in this country.
