<HEAD>Scientists Join Call For Amnesty, Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 40 prominent scientists have joined the movement among Chinese intellectuals for greater democracy and the release of political prisoners, a spokesman for the group said Monday. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Liangying </PERSON>, a scientific historian at the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, said 42 people signed a letter urging <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s top leaders to guarantee freedom of speech, publication and information. `` This is the only reliable guarantee of unity and stability,'' the letter said, referring to government fears that democracy could bring instability. `` World history and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s experience shows that political democratization, including a legal system, is necessary to guarantee economic reform and the whole modernization -LRB- program -RRB-,'' the scientists said. <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> said he mailed copies last week to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and the heads of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consultative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, an advisory body of intellectuals It was the third letter of its kind sent to the leadership this year. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s best-known dissident, astrophysicist <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, first proposed amnesty in a letter to senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> in January. Thirty-three intellectuals, including some of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most famous writers and philosphers, signed a letter with the same message in February. Hundreds of people in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, as well as Chinese living in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have signed petitions and letters of support for an amnesty. Specific requests were made in the first two letters for the release of <PERSON> Wei </PERSON> <PERSON> Jingsheng </PERSON>, who was convicted of counterrevolutionary activities in 1979 and is said to have become mentally ill. No names were mentioned in the scientists' letter, which appealed for the release of `` all young people who were convicted and sentenced to labor reform because of ideological problems. It said that would `` open a new era in the political history of our country.'' <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> said he helped write the letter and the signers believed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` should n't arrest people because they have different political views.'' Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said calls for amnesty amounted to `` interfering in the administration of justice.'' No other direct government response has been forthcoming, but Monday's <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Daily defended the imprisonment of <LOCATION> Wei </LOCATION>. `` Freedom of speech in any country can not be held to be above the country's basic interests,'' it declared. `` People have the freedom of speech but not the freedom of agitating for counterrevolution by taking advantage of socialist democracy.'' Among signers of the latest letter were <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganchang </PERSON>, a former vice minister of nuclear industry, and physicist <PERSON> Qian </PERSON> <PERSON> Lingjiao </PERSON>. Many intellectuals have learned caution from four decades of alternating thaws and freezes on freedom of expression, but increasing numbers now are speaking out on political and economic issues. They say they are disillusioned by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s continued backwardness and poverty and believe a free exchange of ideas is necessary to modernizaton. <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, who last week was barred from a dinner given by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has encouraged intellectuals to press for democratic reform. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s leaders say their priority is stability. Party chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during his two-day visit that multi-party democracy is not suitable for <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and efforts to promote it will endanger economic reform.
