<HEAD>Arkansas Youth Wins $20,000 Westinghouse Science Talent Search</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high school student from <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark </LOCATION>. who analyzed a 1,500-year-old mathematical equation was named the winner Monday of the national <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> Science Talent Search. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> McLean </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, 16, a student at <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, was the top award winner in the 48th annual Westinghouse contest. He won over 1,461 other entrants and will receive a $ 20,000, unrestricted science scholarship. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>'s winning project was an analysis of a math equation named for Diophantus, a fourth century mathematician. The second place winner in the <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> competition was <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellenberg </PERSON>, 17, of <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, who also entered a math project. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, 15, of <LOCATION> Penfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> won third place for a project on the nervous and immune systems. Both <PERSON> Ellenberg </PERSON> and <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> will receive $ 15,000 scholarships. The three were selected top winners from among 40 finalists in the national contest. The finalists came to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week for a judging that involved displaying their projects and then undergoing interviews by a panel of eight scientists who evaluated the creativity and potential of each entrant. Other winners and their scholarship awards are: 4. <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON>, 16, <LOCATION> Cambria </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, $ 10,000. 5. <PERSON