<SECOND>AM-Europe-Space,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ariane Launches Two Satellites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s 29th Ariane rocket lifted off successfully Monday from this South American launch center and put a Japanese and a European satellite into orbit. The launch had been scheduled for Feb. 28 but was postponed because of a strike by technicians. It was rescheduled for Saturday but delayed again when high winds caused two `` umbilical cables'' to disconnect as the gantry was being pulled away. Seventeen minutes, 41 seconds after liftoff at 8:29 p.m., the Ariane 4 attained orbit, and after seven more minutes it had released the two satellites. Ariane 4 is the most powerful launcher in the Ariane series. Put into orbit were JCSAT-1, a Japanese commercial communication satellite, and MOP-1, a European meteorological satellite. The JDSAT-1, built by <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communication </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Satellite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s first commercial communication satellite. MOP-1 is the fourth weather satellite for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. It will send weather pictures every half hour to stations on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. It was the agency's second launch this year and the 11th straight successful operation. The first Ariane rocket, an Ariane 1, was launched a decade ago. The agency has had four failed flights since its rocket became operational. The last failure was in 1986 and resulted in a delay in the program of more than a year. Launches resumed in September
</TEXT>
