<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Pilots Rules,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Given Two Safe Choices: Take The Slowest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Plans by pilots for nearly all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines to strictly fly by the rule book starting Tuesday could cause lengthy flight delays, especially where there is heavy traffic and bad weather, according to aviation experts and pilots. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> announced the action by its 40,000 members as a show of support for 8,500 striking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union members and the <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots and flight stewardesses who have refused to cross the picket lines. Pilots, in announcing the action, said it would not amount to a `` slowdown,'' because they would simply be following procedures, taking the longer option when there are two or more safe options available. The primary impact could come if pilots rely on instrument landing procedures when they could use visual procedures, said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON> said it was impossible to tell how much the pilots' action would affect overall air travel He said in some instances, the impact might be minimal and in areas where weather is bad and traffic heavy, it could be greater. Pilot <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON>, who has been flying for Eastern for 19 years, said he viewed the action as `` a morale booster'' from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots who are honoring the pickets but doubted it would cause significant tie ups. <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON>, spokesman for picketing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots at <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, said the action could enhance safety in a time when several airlines have beefed up routes normally flown by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, using pilots unfamiliar with the routes. `` What you want to do is be sure the public is protected. We want to be sure the crews know where they're going ... so the approaches are made safely,'' said <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON>. One thing pilots might do is require air traffic controllers to read back flight plans for verification, rather than simply giving an acknowledgement that they have heard the pilot's intentions. `` They'll make sure every ` t' is crossed and every ` i' dotted,'' said a government official who is a pilot. The official, who asked not to be identified, said pilots likely would be taking the `` most conservative and time-consuming way'' whenever possible. The official said this might not necessarily enhance safety, because tie-ups at crowded airports could lead to increased frustration. `` It's a matter of a few seconds here and a few seconds there, and it could really cascade,'' the official said.
</TEXT>
