<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKEWOOD, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police on Monday denied allegations that they beat a diabetic man who went into insulin shock while driving his car and was arrested for drunken driving. `` The police probably should have checked a little closer,'' Police Chief <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said. `` But they had a lot of other concerns at the time, mainly that this guy did n't fall down and hurt himself.'' <PERSON> Phillip </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, 63, sustained bruises to his face, hip and arms. He said he does n't remember much of what happened in the incident Friday because of his condition, but remembers being `` roughed up pretty good'' and telling police he needed insulin. He said police should have diagnosed his problem sooner and that they mistreated him by handcuffing him and putting him in a holding cell. At a news conference, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> defended his officers' actions and said a preliminary investigation showed no evidence of brutality or excessive force. He said the bruises to <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>'s arms and wrists were caused when officers tried to handcuff him. He added that <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> bruises easily because of medication he takes for a heart condition. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> may have contributed to discoloration around his eyes by rubbing them a lot, but added that he also fell and hit his eye on a file cabinet in the police station. The incident began when <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> allegedly made an improper turn at an intersection and his pickup was hit by a car. He drove away, and police were notified of a hit-and-run accident. Officers later found <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> and his car in a stranger's driveway. Police said they did not notice a necklace <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> wore under his shirt identifying him as a diabetic or a similar identification card in his wallet. They noticed a medical bracelet he wore which said he suffered from a heart ailment but mentioned nothing about diabetes. <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> refused to take a sobriety test, but later tests showed he had no alcohol in his blood. Officers said they asked <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> on the way to the station if he needed medical attention and he said no. Police reports say <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> was uncooperative at the police station, exhibited mood swings and was handcuffed to a bench in a holding cell. An officer found him unconscious in that cell some 80 minutes later and he was rushed to a hospital, where glucose injections revived him. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> probably would not be charged in the traffic accident because he was unaware of what he was doing at the time.
