<HEAD>General Strike in Trinidad Protests IMF Conditions for Debt Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT OF SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of workers throughout <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> struck on Monday to protest an economic austerity program and wage cuts imposed to meet <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> requirements for debt relief. Oil fields, factories and schools shut down. The trade union movement called it a `` Day of Resistance'' to protest the government's 10 percent cut in the salaries of 65,000 public workers, part of the belt-tightening measures brought on by the conditions of an <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> standby loan agreement. `` The strike has affected us, but it is much better than going the way of the riots in <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>,'' said one businessman, who spoke on condition of not being identified. He was referring to the bloody riots that rocked <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> last week after the government there imposed similar measures. No violence was reported in the English-speaking nation of <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> and </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tobago </LOCATION>, a former British colony of 1.2 million people and the southernmost of the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> islands, lying seven miles off <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. National Security Minister <PERSON> Selwyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said 50 to 65 percent of the estimated 400,000 workers in the private and public sectors showed up for work. President <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> McCleod </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Oilfields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> said 80 percent of the union members stayed off the job. He said the only exception was at the refinery, `` where we did not want to interrupt the complex operations there.'' Workers also struck the country's major sugar factory. The turnout at government offices and several ministries was reported at 50 percent, but at the post office and other key operations, only a 2 to 3 percent turnout was reported. Throughout the country, schools closed as teachers and students stayed home. In Port of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, plainclothes army personnel drove the buses. There were no taxis as cab drivers honored the walkout. In <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fernando </LOCATION>, the second largest city, there was no transportation and hardly any commercial activity. Workers earn a minimum wage of $ 500 a month. Midlevel professionals make about $ 900 monthly. Inflation has averaged 10 percent a year, but Trinidadians complain most about taxes and about high prices for many consumer items. <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tobago </LOCATION>'s foreign debt runs to nearly $ 1.8 billion. The government of Prime Minister H.N.R. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> received a $ 128 million standby loan from the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> in January to be parceled out in three payments, conditional on expenditures being cut in the public sector and other measures. The country made nearly 75 percent of its payments on the principal and interests in 1988, or about $ 350 million dollars to creditors. Payments for 1989 have not come due yet. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> says commercial creditors would only reschedule the debt repayments within the context of an <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> program. The country's economy has been hit by the world decline in oil prices.
