<HEAD>Assembly Approves Death Penalty Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The state <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation Monday to restore the death penalty in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as the bill's chief sponsor predicted the chamber would for the first time override a promised veto by Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>. A successful override later this year in the Democratic-controlled Assembly would clear the way for the electric chair to be put back into use in the nation's second largest state. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> already has the death penalty. The Assembly approved the death-penalty measure 97-48 after an emotionally charged debate lasting more than five hours. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, which passed the legislation last month, is expected to override the veto, as it has several times in the past. A successful override in the Assembly would restore the death penalty. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s electric chair, last used in 1963, has been sitting unused at <LOCATION> Greenhaven </LOCATION> state prison in <LOCATION> Stormville </LOCATION> since capital punishment in the state was eliminated by a series of court rulings. The chair, the first in the world, has already been used to execute 695 people since its introduction in 1890. Two death penalty supporters were absent from the Assembly on Monday. Had they been present, there would have been 99 `` yes'' votes in the 150-member Assembly. A veto override requires 100 votes. <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> has promised to veto the bill, making it the seventh year in a row the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> governor has quashed capital punishment legislation. <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Graber </PERSON>, the bill's chief Assembly sponsor, predicted he would have the extra vote required by the time the override attempt comes later this year. State lawmakers have approved death penalty legislation in the last 12 years, but <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> and former Gov. <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> repeatedly vetoed it. <PERSON> Graber </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> area Democrat, closed in on the 100-vote override margin when longtime death penalty opponent <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, also a Democrat, announced he would vote for <PERSON> Graber </PERSON>'s bill. <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>, citing the highly publicized assassination last year in his district of Police Officer <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryne </PERSON> by associates of a drug dealer, said a poll of his constituents found that 73 percent supported the death penalty. The vote came less than a week after a federal narcotics agent and a city policeman were shot to death in separate incidents in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Before the debate, about 150 anti-death penalty demonstrators, many from a Hutterite religious community near <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, gathered outside the Assembly chamber and sang such traditional protest songs as `` We Shall Overcome.'' `` No person is allowed to take the life of another person, for whatever reason,'' said <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldner </PERSON>, a member of the Hutterite community in <LOCATION> Rifton </LOCATION>. `` Only God can do that. We feel God should be the judge.'' During the debate, <PERSON> Graber </PERSON> noted that the number of murders in the state last year rose to 2,225, an increase of 213 from 1987. Pointing out that most of the 1988 killings occurred in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, he read off a list of the 20 most dangerous Assembly district in the state, including <PERSON> Abramson </PERSON>'s. All were in the city and all but one were represented by legislators who had voted against the death penalty bill previously. Under the bill, the most cold-blooded murderers _ paid hit-men, killers of police officers, those murdering witnesses and the like _ would be subject to the death penalty. Once a murder verdict was delivered, a second jury would be asked to decide whether the death penalty should be imposed.
