<HEAD>Founder of Doyle Dane Bernbach Advertising Agency Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, a co-founder of <ORGANIZATION> Doyle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bernbach </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the nation's largest advertising agencies, died Sunday at his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> home, the agency announced Monday. He was 86. The announcement did not give the cause of <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>'s death. When the agency was formed in 1949, <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> was named executive vice president in charge of account services. He became chairman of its executive committee in 1967, when the company had grown to become the nation's eighth largest advertising firm. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> remained on the agency's board of directors after his retirement in 1969. In 1986, <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> Dane </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernbach </PERSON> merged with two other large agencies, <ORGANIZATION> BBDO </ORGANIZATION> Worldwide and <ORGANIZATION> Needham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worldwide </ORGANIZATION>, to form <ORGANIZATION> Omnicom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, one of the world's largest advertising corporations. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>'s blunt comments to co-workers and clients led many in the advertising field to refer to him as the `` man with the sandpaper charm.'' One DDB employee once said of <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON>, `` He is the roughest, toughest, softest man I know _ and I suspect the first two are put-ons.'' <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> got his first taste of the advertising world as a magazine space salesman, a job he held while attending <ORGANIZATION> Fordham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> at night. Although he passed his bar examination, he never practiced law. `` In those days, after you passed the bar, you went to work in a law office for $ 10 a week. I was making $ 75 a week selling space. I could n't afford to quit,'' he explained. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> served as western and eastern manager for Cosmopolitan magazine in the 1930s, and in 1936 he became the first advertising manager for a new magazine _ Look. Just before World War II, he went to work for Good Housekeeping magazine. After the Japanese attacked <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, he tried to enlist in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Marines but was rejected because he was too old for voluntary military service. He was 39 at the time. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> persisted and enlisted in 1942. Because of his Good Housekeeping background, the <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> appointed him a mess officer. He protested and, within three weeks was reassigned and became an intelligence officer serving in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> as a captain. After the war, he joined Grey Advertising and in 1949 he and <PERSON> Grey </PERSON>'s creative director, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernbach </PERSON>, decided to create their own agency along with <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> <PERSON> Dane </PERSON>, who was running his own small ad agency. The result was DDB. <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> is survived by three children and four grandchildren.
