to conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first federal desegregation lawsuit ever filed against an entire state university system heads back into court Tuesday, 15 years after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> first sued <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. A special master appointed by a panel of federal judges is convening hearings on desegregation plans proposed by the state, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Grambling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alumni </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The panel of federal judges ruled in December that a 1981 consent decree aimed at improving Southern and <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> in order to bring more whites to them had failed miserably. Settlement talks were held Monday, but the hearings will go ahead, said the state's attorney. `` Some progress was made. There has not been total consensus in the form of a settlement,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, attorney for Gov. <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON>. `` And as a practical matter, even if everyone agreed on everything, we could n't get it all drawn up and written out in time to stop the hearings.'' Alumni from Southern, the nation's largest predominantly black university system, and <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION>, also mostly black, are fighting to keep their schools distinct from other state universities while making them equal. `` Separate but equal has another connotation, so I would n't describe it in those words,'' said <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Spikes </PERSON>, president of Southern `` I think what Southern is asking for is the same thing that the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is asking for _ a desegregated system, but one that still allows for access and a chance for reasonable success for minority students, poor students, and disadvantaged students,'' she said. `` That's part of the mission of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>; we're asking that remain intact. The problem that must be corrected, supporters say, is that Southern and <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> never got the money and programs needed to catch up academically to other schools. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Verkuil </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mary </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, was appointed special master in the case to draw up a desegregation plan because attorneys for 13 universities, four governing boards, the state and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> were unable to agree on one. The first day of hearings comes one week before the suit's 15th anniversary; <PERSON> Verkuil </PERSON> has said they must end by March 15, the day after that anniversary. <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> campuses of the <ORGANIZATION> LSU </ORGANIZATION> system remain almost all white, while Southern's campuses in those cities remain nearly all black The same is true of <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION>, about eight miles down Interstate 20. Southern contends that <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, not the agreement, failed miserably. The state says it spent more than $ 200 million to upgrade the black schools. Southern contends the total spent on black schools was closer to $ 75 million. <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> and Tech are among nine schools run by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trustees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Colleges </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universities </ORGANIZATION>, and the state's proposal includes <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> However, the <ORGANIZATION> Grambling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alumni </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has proposed its own plan. Although the <ORGANIZATION> LSU </ORGANIZATION>, Southern and trustees systems all are controlled by the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regents </ORGANIZATION>, they often fight over the limited money in a state budget hit hard by the oil industry bust. <PERSON> Roemer </PERSON> wants to scrap the current four-board system and set up one board to run all of the schools and end the turf wars. Southern, which lost $ 5.6 million when $ 11 million in state money was cut from all colleges, would probably lose even more if this happens, supporters say. Just as important, they say, thousands of blacks left unprepared by <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s woeful public schools might lose their chance at a college education. Plans submitted by Southern and by the <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> alumni depend heavily on moving programs from predominantly white schools to the black schools to make them more attractive to whites. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plan also leans heavily on transferring programs to Southern and <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION>, and calls for Southern to open new graduate schools in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>. The state's proposal calls for varying admission standards for seven of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s 13 four-year universities, for cooperation among schools in the same part of the state and for a separate system of community colleges to take over the most basic courses. <PERSON> Verkuil </PERSON> already has statements from all the witnesses, plus depositions they gave to opposing lawyers. Rather than listen to arguments he's already read, he plans to jump directly from an introductory statement by state attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> into cross-examination of the state's 32 witnesses. Attorneys for the Justice, Southern and the <LOCATION> Grambling </LOCATION> alumni association each may question each state witness. After that, each must defend its own alternative to the state plan.
