<TEXT>
 Sixteen members of the Christian Knights of the <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> chanted `` White power for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' as they marched Sunday afternoon through the town portrayed in the movie `` Mississippi Burning.'' About 100 people lined the streets of the north-central <LOCATION> Mississipi </LOCATION> town of 7,500 to watch the Klan demonstration. Only a handful of hecklers, some of them white, shouted at the white supremacists. About 20 Klansmen marched later in the day in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION> about 40 miles to the east. About 10 counterdemonstrators and 100 spectators turned out. <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> was chosen for what was billed as a Klan recruitment rally because of its portrayal in `` Mississippi Burning,'' said the Grand Dragon for <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gollub </PERSON> of Picayune. The fictional movie, which received seven Oscar nominations, is loosely based on the 1964 slayings of three civil rights workers whose bodies were found in an earthen dam near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, 21, who was black, and <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, 20, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, 24, who were white, were shot to death. The federal government eventually convicted eight people of violating the civil rights of the three men, but no one was ever charged with murder. The Klan group that rallied Sunday included men and women, with 10 wearing robes. <PERSON> Gollub </PERSON>'s group has marched in several <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> towns in the past few months, with <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>'s crowd drawing by far the largest number of spectators. The Klan planned another rally later Sunday in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>. Several black leaders had asked opponents of the Klan to sta