<SECOND>AM-Italy-Fashion,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Youthful Armani And Moschino Kick Off Milan Fashion Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIELA PETROFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Italian ready-to-wear collections for fall and winter got off to a lively start Sunday with fashion darling <PERSON> Giorgio </PERSON> <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>'s sporty <ORGANIZATION> Emporio </ORGANIZATION> line and spoof specialist <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON>'s gag-filled winter wardrobe. Pants, in all shapes and sizes prevailed in both collections, with only a spattering of skirts. In the early 1980's, <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>, the leader in Italian ready-to-wear, decided to court the younger set by creating a fresh sporty line at more accessible prices. He started with designer jeans, but the label dubbed Emporio soon was manufacturing <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>'s trade mark blazer, suits, coats and even evening wear. Today Emporio shops designed to appeal to the young with their bright lights, trendy posters and hip music are scattered throughout <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the rest of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. An Emporio Armani shop is due to open in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> later this month. For this year's chillier season, <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>, who showed his collection Sunday morning in the modern theater of his downtown Milan headquarters, plays heavily on casual, with a series of wool knit sweat pants worn under tweed blazers or matching jackets. Other trousers are super wide and cropped at the ankle, with or without cuff. <PERSON> Armani </PERSON>'s new winter jacket is cut off above the waist. At times it has a long loose back, at others it is trimmed in demure pie-crust ruffles. His blazer is single breasted with huge breast and side pockets, a look he introduced in his more exclusive Armani label several seasons ago. There are plenty of beautiful coats to pick from for next winter, from the classic polo, to cape coats and fun furs. <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> who has joined the chorus of voices calling for a ban on the use of real skins in fashion, introduced fake sables, minks and bear. To prove his point he even dotted his leather wear from shoes to purses with precious leopard spots. Evening at <LOCATION> Emporio </LOCATION> is very 1930-ish with long clinging black jersey velvet dresses, enhanced by small velvet hats complete with feather, and feather cuffed gloves. He also favors the tuxedo look from silk lapel to studs and black tie. <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> has never been a bright light on the <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION> runway where color is concerned and his new <ORGANIZATION> Emporio </ORGANIZATION> collection is no exception. Browns grays and blacks, plus the traditional fall shades are his favorite palette, with a spatter of bright red and green for future Christmas cheer. <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON>, who also showed Sunday, was putting everything but the kitchen sink on hats, as a joke, before <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> LaCroix </PERSON> turned potpourri hats into a multi-million dollar business. For the winter season he gets his biggest laugh out of the label racket, by flaunting labels and price tags throughout the collection. Thus a simple striped silk stole has a super visible huge white label with the designers name and the word ` couture' written on it A jacket bears the inscription embroidered in gold, `` this is very expensive,'' and a blouse states its price, also in gold. Other fashion gags at Moschino include tape measure belts, dinner jackets decorated with real forks, knives and spoons, and an Irish knit sweater with a ball of yarn and knitting needles still attached around the collar. But do n't be fooled by <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON>'s sense of humor. Behind the chuckles is a very serious designer with lots of superbly designed clothes. For next season <PERSON> Moschino </PERSON> prefers pants, with wide bell bottoms to skirts, and favors long jackets with large cloth buttons. Like <PERSON> Armani </PERSON> he prefers to let the animals keep their skins opting for opulent fuzzy coats and stoles in harmless synthetic fabric.
