<HEAD>Iraqi Leader Seeks Dominant Role in Arab World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, who has proclaimed <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> the victor in the war with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, now seeks a dominant role for himself in the Arab world. But <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON>, the name he goes by in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, faces growing resentment at home because promised economic good times are slow in coming after eight years of wartime hardship and sacrifice by his 16 million people. Salaries are low and prices are high. `` I want to get married, but I need 10,000 dinars -LRB- $ 30,000 -RRB- for an apartment, furniture, gold,'' said <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, a 27-year-old soldier, referring to the three items required of any perspective Middle Eastern groom. He earns just 100 dinars -LRB- $ 300 -RRB- a month in the army. `` I want to open an auto supply store, but I have to get out of the army first,'' he said. Nevertheless, Iraqis still regard <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> as a hero and, according to diplomats in <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>, visiting <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> leaders praise his strategies that led <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to sue for peace last summer. A Western military analyst said <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON>'s well-equipped, 1-million-man army has made <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> `` a major player'' in the region. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s new economic alliance with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> _ all of whom lent men and materiel to <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION>'s war effort _ may prove the first indication of how <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> will fare as a pan-Arab leader. Other Arab countries will also be watching the extent of political and social reforms inside <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Iraqis accepted many economic and political limitations as a necessary price for the war, but now that it's over, the restrictions chafe. `` Wherever you go you feel that the secret police are on your back,'' said <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, 51, who works for a retail company. `` Even the traffic police can beat you. There's no personal freedom here.'' Said another Iraqi: `` There is some personal freedom, but not as much as people want.'' Restrictions like banning foreign travel, limiting imports of videos and barring foreign publications are widely resented, he said. Iraqis are forbidden to allow foreigners into their homes and even talking to them is viewed with suspicion. So Iraqis interviewed by visiting reporters usually give their first names or none at all. Certain subjects, like the <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, are taboo. <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> government officials say many of the restrictions were necessary because of the war and will be lifted gradually. `` The trend has been approved that there be more openness in the political system, including this matter of elections and other steps to improve the political and social system,'' said Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nizar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamdoon </PERSON>. `` People should expect lots of changes over the next few months.'' Elections postponed since August are now set for April, with the delay attributed to the governing <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> working out laws for new political parties <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> is permitting to operate. But Iraqi officials said the plans date back to the 1968 revolution that brought the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to power. They can now be implemented because <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> came out of the war a more cohesive nation. `` Difficult conditions existed even before the war,'' said <PERSON> Salah </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukhtar </PERSON>, director general of the <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. `` But any citizen who lived through the war is qualified to practice freedom in political life. No one who went through the war is a threat to our government. Why should we exclude them?'' The strongest opposition groups _ the Communists, the fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Call </ORGANIZATION> and separatist Kurdish factions _ are excluded. All were driven underground in bloody purges. Information Minister <PERSON> Latif </PERSON> <PERSON> Nayyif </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasim </PERSON> said all were `` treacherous and treasonous'' for aiding <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> during the war. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s image was tarnished by its alleged use of chemical weapons against the Kurdish rebels last fall in a major offensive to crush the guerrillas' campaign for an autonomous homeland. <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> has declared an amnesty for many prisoners and dissidents, but Kurdish officials described it as little more than cosmetic. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> recently singled out <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> for its `` abysmal human rights record,'' mainly because of the assault on the Kurds in the northern mountains. Diplomats said easing restrictions on personal freedom will help <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> deflect the heat from economic problems expected to last at least five years. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has an estimated $ 60 billion to $ 70 billion in war debts and moves to expand the private business sector and secure Arab investment have yet to make headway. Prices skyrocketed as private firms took over agriculture and importing consumer goods, leaving Iraqis feeling empty handed despite promises of postwar prosperity. Long lines form outside government meat stores when the monthly ration is distributed. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> Passat cars imported from <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> are the only autos widely available. One boutique owner said she spent hours scouring the market for decent buttons. `` Anything electric is very expensive. I ca n't afford them,'' said <PERSON> Abdel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamid </PERSON>, 34, a veteran who was wounded seven times and lost a kidney. Blistering attacks have appeared in the press. Economist Human al-Shuma' a wrote in <ORGANIZATION> Al-Qadissiya </ORGANIZATION> that the private sector was `` soaking the sweat of the people and grabbing their daily bread.''
