<FIRST>a i AM-Germany-BlackMarket Adv14   03-06 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Black Market, Adv 14,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tue AMs, March 14, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poles Make Deals on Black Market in West Berlin</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a muddy field near the Berlin Wall, a young Pole looks furtively about and pulls a bottle of vodka out of a plastic bag. `` Five marks, you can have,'' he says. He motions to a fox fur coat on a hanger clipped to button on his shirt. A bargain for 30 marks -LRB- $ 17 -RRB-, he says. If he sells four bottles of vodka at five marks -LRB- $ 2.70 -RRB- each, or the fur coat, he will have earned himself the equivalent of about a month's salary in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Across town, in the fashionable <LOCATION> Zehlendorf </LOCATION> district, three Poles are painting the interior of a handsome turn-of-the-century villa for the unbeatable price of 400 marks -LRB- $ 220 -RRB-. `` You could n't get a union painter to even look at the place for that price,'' said the homeowner, speaking only on condition of anonymity. City officials estimate that as many as 4,000 Poles sell goods or their labor illegally in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> now that entry into the city has been eased for them. Many advertize in the city's newspapers offering to do home repair work and odd jobs at prices many West Berliners find hard to resist. Thousands of Poles are also turning up on weekends at a flea-market to sell everything from baby clothes to superbly crafted amber necklaces for hard currency, such as marks and dollars. With the Polish economy in shambles, the vendors say, hard currency has become the only means to acquire quality goods and food items in short supply. It also offers the opportunity for staggering profits on the black market currency exchange at home. `` Without hard currency you ca n't get anything that's any good,'' said a 30-year-old man from <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, who drove through the night to be at the market when it opened at 5 a.m. He was among a record 8,000 Poles who jammed a field in the <LOCATION> Kreuzberg </LOCATION> district of the city on a recent weekend. Thousands of West Berliners jostled through the mud to inspect shoes, clothing, household goods and food. The grocery goods, displayed in open suitcases and car trunks, ranged from heaps of Polish sausage to tins of Russian caviar at dumping prices. Many Poles at the market earn enough West German marks in a weekend to support them for several months. `` Ten marks on the black market in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> will get you up to 20,000 zloty, or almost as much as a pension,'' said a middle-aged man from <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> who was selling crystal goblets from the trunk of his car. A companion, who said he came from <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, added: `` I buy goods in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for 1,000 zloty that I can sell here for 200 marks. With those 200 marks, I can get 400,000 zloty on the black market in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. We can live for six months on that.'' A Polish house painter, who asked not to be named, said he could earn a year's wages from three months' work in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. Under new regulations that went into effect Jan. 1, Poles do not need visas to enter <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> and are allowed to stay as long as three months. However, they come as tourists and are prohibited from engaging in commercial enterprises. So far, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police have cracked down only on vendors illegally selling heavily taxed items such as cigarettes, furs, jewelry and alcohol. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> police said that on one day alone, authorities seized 11 liters of vodka, 28,000 cigarettes, 360 grams -LRB- about 12 ounces -RRB- of caviar and two fur coats. Fourteen Polish vendors were charged with violations of import tax laws. Six Poles were arrested in February and expelled after they were caught working illegally in the city. Customs checks have also been stepped up and the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has ordered that Poles caught smuggling goods be immediately expelled and the offense noted in their passports. But customs officials say tourists are allowed to bring in goods worth up to 100 marks -LRB- $ 54 -RRB- for personal use and it is often impossible to prove that the goods are intended for sale. `` There are too many of them and too few of us,'' said an exasperated customs officer as as he made his way down a row of sputtering Polish Fiats and vans at Checkpoint <PERSON> Charley </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall. Around the corner, where 45 cars packed to the roofs with goods waited for custom inspectection, deals were already flourishing. A West <PERSON> Berliner </PERSON> walked away with a porcelain tea set for 50 marks -LRB- $ 27 -RRB-, three times less than the department store price.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, March 14</NOTE>
