<FIRST>a i AM-LiberalCapeTown Adv15   03-06 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liberal Cape Town, Adv 15,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, March 15, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cape Town Wants to be South Africa's First Desegregated City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s oldest city, wants to be the country's first completely desegregated municipality. `` We are striving toward prize No. 1, that the whole city is a free settlement area. But the government is hardly likely to do that,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>. He meant the national government. National apartheid laws allow municipalities to decide whether to open public amenities such as parks, beaches and buses. <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> is the only major city with no segregated public facilities. But the national government holds the power to segregate residential areas, schools and hospitals. The <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Council </LOCATION> has petitioned repeatedly for the right to declare its whole area, or sections of it, open to free settlement. The law prohibited multiracial neighborhoods, although parts of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> and other cities are mixed, with non-whites living illegally in designated white areas. On March 2, a new law took effect that will allow multiracial neighborhoods on a limited basis. <PERSON> Muller </PERSON> believes that a section of <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> will be the first area where all races can live together legally since the governing <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> legislated residential segregation in 1950. `` It's common cause that District Six will be the first free settlement area,'' said <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>. He referred to a hillside near the center of town where a squalid but lively multiracial neighborhood was bulldozed in the 1960s and declared `` whites only.'' District Six is now bordered by all-white apartment blocks and a white technical school. But grass-covered lots, intersected by empty streets and dotted with mosques and churches, lie vacant because most Capetonians felt the demolition had stigmatized the area. `` Nobody with any kind of sensitivity would have taken it upon themselves to in any way develop District Six,'' said <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>. Before cities were granted the right to open public amenities to all races, the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Council </LOCATION> refused to enforce the Separate Amenities Act. Instead of signs demarcating swimming pools and toilets for `` whites'' or `` non-whites,'' <PERSON> Muller </PERSON> said, the council put up notices warning `` disallowed people'' that they could be prosecuted if they broke the law. `` But we did n't prosecute,'' he said. `` Right through the 1960s we fought the removal of the colored -LRB- mixed-race -RRB- people from the voters' roll and as representatives on the Council,'' recalled the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s executive committee chairman, <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedlander </PERSON>. He was mayor in 1972 when national law forced the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to become all-white. `` We held protest meetings, we passed resolutions, we did all we could,'' <PERSON> Friedlander </PERSON> said. `` Six of the 34 councilors were legislated out of office.'' `` Some of the colored councilors were elected from predominantly white areas, and vice-versa,'' <PERSON> Muller </PERSON> said. `` We had gotten away from racial stigma.'' The people of mixed-race, <LOCATION> Indonesian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysian </LOCATION> or Indian ancestry whose religions, customs, language and architecture contributed to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>'s historic and cultural attraction now have no direct voice in how the city is run. They can elect neighborhood management committees, which appoint delegates to a regional council. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> sits in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, the legislative capital. The first whites to settle in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> were merchants from the Dutch <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> who established a trading post in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> in 1652. The 1985 census put the population of greater <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, including suburbs, at 1.54 million _ 433,000 whites, 839,000 coloreds, 18,000 Asiatics and 254,000 blacks. City spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Doman </PERSON> said the blacks are grossly undercounted. Officially, no blacks live in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>. The adjacent townships of <PERSON> Langa </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nyanga </LOCATION> and Crossroads were taken from the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s control, although the city provides most of the water, sewerage and fire protection services that exist in those areas `` We feel a moral, if not a strategic, obligation to make sure those places have the highest quality of life they can expect, bearing in mind the shanty type of existence there,'' said <PERSON> Muller </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
