<HEAD>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&amp;w photo.)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> oversees a most unusual performance in a most unlikely setting. He's been doing it for 48 years, and spectators still wonder why they find it so amusing. He knows why.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By JULES LOH</NOTE>
<NOTE>AP Special Correspondent</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A few days before his 9th birthday, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> dared to try every boy's ultimate adventure. He ran away and joined the circus. His purpose, he says, was to escape violin lessons, not to become a performer. Yet today, a few days before his 80th birthday on March 22, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> is still going strong as the raucous ringmaster of the oldest established permanent floating animal act in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, perhaps in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and certainly one of the most charming. He's the Peabody duck man. `` I swear,'' he was saying the other day, scratching his gray head, `` I still do n't understand why people like it so much. `` You saw'em, saw how they behave. They laugh and clap and cheer and take pictures. They've been doing that for the 48 years since I've been here and were doing it before that, so I'm told. I do n't understand it, I just do it Twice a day.'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> understands more than he lets on. The applause recognizes the unlikely setting for the performance, and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON>'s sense of showmanship makes the most of it. Picture this: At midmorning the grand and gilded lobby of the Peabody Hotel begins to fill. The bar opens and the tinkle of ice in thin glasses mingles with the chatter of expectant guests. At 10:45 a.m. the bell captain rolls a red carpet from the elevator's brass door 50 feet to the base of the fountain in the center of the lobby beneath hand-painted beams and wrought-iron chandeliers. He places a three-step red-carpeted staircase up to the lip of the fountain. The fountain is of carved travertine marble. Four marble cherubs support a huge marble bowl of fresh water overflowing into an octagonal marble pool. Above the bowl a marble pot overflows with fresh flowers. When it comes to gilt and grandeur, the Peabody is not known to stint. At the stroke of 11 a loudspeaker announces solemnly, `` Your attention please. Ladies and gentlemen, the Peabody ducks.'' Spectators crowd into position along both sides of the red carpet. The loudspeaker strikes up `` Stars and Stripes Forever.'' All eyes turn to the polished brass elevator doors. They open with a flourish and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON>, in a voice like a trumpet, cries, `` Let's go, ducks!'' Out they come, a mallard drake leading a four-hen harem. <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> swaggers behind them in a burgundy and black uniform, carrying a stick, like a field marshal. Down the red carpet they waddle, up the red stairs, over the marble ledge, flapping and quacking into their elegant pond. Cheers. Laughter. Flashbulbs. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> has devoted more than half his long life to this twice-daily task _ the duck parade will be repeated, in reverse, precisely at 5 p.m. when they return to their penthouse palace _ and he appears more than content in his role. `` I've done lots of other things in my life,'' he said. `` Some I'll tell you about, some I wo n't. But the ducks are important to the Peabody and I'm proud to be the one to see after them. I never saw any reason to change jobs.'' Indeed, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> has done other things. Chatting with him, you get the impression that the ones he wo n't tell you about outnumber the ones he will. When he fled his home in Reading, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION> in 1918 and the circus people adopted him, they gave him a job delivering the mail for $ 4.28 a week. `` That way I got to know all of them. About half of them could n't read or write, both black and white people I did that for them. Sometimes we'd get a notice that a sheriff was waiting for one of them in the next town, so of course I'd warn them about that. I never turned in anybody.''
</TEXT>
