<SECOND>BC-APN--Duck Man, Adv 19-1st Add,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sun., March 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>Repeat for all needing</HEAD>
<HEAD>MEMPHIS, Tenn.: in anybody.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 He stayed with the circus 13 years, until he was 22, moving on to more responsible jobs of every sort, including animal handling. Ducks would prove to be a pushover. `` I left the circus because the train was in a wreck coming out of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. I was hurt pretty bad, and had to stay behind.'' When he recovered, <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> found jobs where he could, a period in his life he recalls with a grin but few specifics. By inclination he drifted toward the company of entertainers. In <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, he drove the bus for the Count Basie band. In <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, he palled around with blues man W.C. Handy and other Beale Street denizens and in 1940 landed a job at the Peabody, two blocks off <PERSON> Beale </PERSON>, as bell captain. The Peabody, with various face lifts over the years, has been a Southern institution since 1869 and is listed on the national register of historic places. The saying is that the <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> begins in the lobby of the Peabody Hotel and ends on Catfish Row in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>, Miss. By the time <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> arrived the ducks were an established Peabody trademark. The story is that back in 1932 the hotel's general manager returned from a duck hunting trip with three live decoys, which were legal then. As a prank, he put them in the fountain. They've been there ever since. Now duck imprints show up on everything imprintable _ the hotel's soap, ash urns, swizzle sticks, chocolates that appear on turned-down beds One of its dining rooms is named `` <PERSON> Dux </PERSON>,'' another `` Mallards.'' The only place ducks do not appear is on the menu. That's forbidden. `` The ducks were here when I came,'' <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON> recalls, `` but they did n't do the march then. That started with me. The duck palace is new, too.'' That's where the ducks live in regal splendor on the roof, where people party and dance in the summertime. The palace is a large carpeted cage with a `` bed chamber'' painted purple and gold. Trays of cracked corn are handy. So is a 6-foot-wide pool sweetened daily with fresh lettuce from the kitchen, a flower garden, a 24-foot mural of trees and waterfowl, and a magnificent view of the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. It is a duck Camelot and must look inviting to less privileged ducks migrating along the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> flyway. `` Oh it does,'' says <PERSON> Pembroke </PERSON>. `` Every spring and fall some of them land on the roof. I shoo'em off.'' He also shoos off the Peabody ducks every four months. `` All that high living makes them so fat they wobble. Not waddle, wobble. So we replace them. They do n't get much exercise swimming around in the fountain, and they ca n't fly.'' They ca n't? `` I clip one wing. Otherwise they'd be flying all around the lobby.'' How long does it take to train a new batch to march down the red carpet? `` One day. People are all lined up along the carpet. Their legs are like fence posts. The ducks have n't got anyplace else to go except to the fountain and back to the elevator. `` They might be a little confused on the first day. After that they do just what I want them to do. `` They get to know my voice. They know I'm the one who feeds them. They also know I'm the one with the stick.''
</TEXT>
