<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Changes in federal tax laws have put a chill on the rehabilitation of historic buildings. Investment in such projects dropped from $ 2.4 billion in fiscal 1985 to $ 866 million in fiscal 1988, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which must certify properties as historic for tax purposes. Here's a look at one giant renovating firm that has fallen on hard times as a result.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By TED DUNCOMBE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A developer with a reputation for saving historic buildings threw a party last April to celebrate completion of its most ambitious project, a $ 40 million refurbishing of a 19th-century railroad station in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>. `` We believe it will be a grand slam home run,'' <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dranoff </PERSON>, then-president and chief executive officer of Historic Landmarks for Living, said as the station reopened with 242 luxury apartments, a restaurant and office space. Less than a year later, he's in trouble, hitting just one more long fly since the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> opening, a 105-unit apartment building in a former cosmetics factory in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis </LOCATION>. The Philadelphia-based company is struggling to save itself, largely because of an inability to recover from the tax-law changes that have slashed the nation's investment in historic rehabilitation by two-thirds in the past three years. Preservationists say the company's predicament symbolizes their concern about the future of efforts to recycle old factories, warehouses, hospitals and other threads of the nation's urban fabric. `` There already is a chill,'' says <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Spatz </PERSON> of the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION>. `` That's not speculative The numbers are very clear. The interest in renovating historical buildings has crashed since the Tax Reform Act of 1986.'' Word of Historic Landmarks' troubles surfaced when <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fidelity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorp </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said in mid-December that it expected heavy fourth-quarter losses in part because of troubled real-estate loans. Historic Landmarks, which had completed or planned 66 renovations in 15 cities, soon announced the resignation of <PERSON> Dranoff </PERSON> and the suspension of projects in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Providence </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ellicott </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. Company officials, trying to renegotiate a $ 46-million line of credit and $ 40 million in construction loans with the bank, agreed to an interview but then backed out. On Jan. 31, the company filed for bankruptcy court protection on three partnerships set up to renovate buildings in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lancaster </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Marietta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and warned in a statement the protection may be sought for other partnerships. Analysts say Historic Landmarks' problems were exacerbated by softening demand for apartment rentals in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where the company has its greatest concentration of buildings. In addition, the company was stymied in an effort to go public in 1987 and its projects have been under scrutiny by the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dranoff </PERSON> has said a city condominium-conversion tax added to the anticipated costs of selling apartment buildings after tax credits expired. Historic Landmarks was one of a number of companies that sprouted after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1976 authorized major tax incentives for preserving historically certified, income-producing properties. Before that, `` our tax laws favored destruction of existing building stock, because they reimbursed the developer the cost of the demolition and then gave him preferential depreciation rates on his new building,'' says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtaugh </PERSON>, the first keeper of the National Register of Historic Places. In his 1988 book, `` Keeping Time: The History and Theory of Preservation in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Murtaugh </PERSON> said the public and private sector were forced to act together on preservation after World War II because of the impact of interstate highways and urban renewal programs. `` These well-funded government programs were causing major social displacement and widespread obliteration of visual landmarks in most parts of the country, especially in cities,'' he wrote. Developers took even greater interest in preservation after the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981 allowed investors a 25 percent tax credit on certified historic rehabilitations. But the 1986 tax law cut the historic-rehab credit to 20 percent, limited it to $ 7,000 for most taxpayers and eliminated it for people with more than $ 250,000 in income. Similar cuts were exacted on low-income housing credits and non-historic restorations. Thus, instead of being able to raise millions of dollars from a few wealthy investors, developers had to raise money in smaller parcels from people with relatively moderate income. While some companies successfully set up partnerships that put investors' money in a portfolio of renovations, many just switched to other types of development. Investment in historic rehabilitation nationwide fell 64 percent to $ 866 million in fiscal 1988 from $ 2.4 billion in fiscal 1985, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which must certify properties as historic for tax purposes.
</TEXT>
