<HEAD>PHILADELPHIA: tax purposes.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` I did n't go out and restore 300 historic buildings because I'm a frustrated curator,'' said <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Mistick </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Tom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mistick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons, a <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> firm that has worked on three projects for Historic Landmarks `` I did it because there were incentives in the tax code to work in historic districts. And it was fun, too.'' Other companies say they are still making a good profit by limiting their involvement to raising the money and hiring out the work. `` We generally do n't act as developer unless we have to,'' says <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Dover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` The people here are bankers and lawyers first.'' Historic Landmarks not only has raised the money, but acted as developer, managed the buildings after restoration and set up a realty subsidiary to sell the buildings as condominiums. `` They took the approach of doing large, single projects as opposed to a portfolio of projects,'' says <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Banwart </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> company whose portfolio includes eight properties this year. `` I do n't want to knock them. Both approaches can be successful, but there's a big difference.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solms </PERSON>, chairman and co-founder of Historic Landmarks, told The <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inquirer </ORGANIZATION> in a 1983 interview he got into preservation because he abhorred modern high-rise apartments and look-alike developments. `` They're nothing but concrete boxes,'' he said. `` Every apartment looks just like the one next door to it.'' He also said he found satisfaction in converting old buildings into housing that could attract well-paid professionals as renters without displacing low-income residents. `` I buy run-down, abandoned industrial properties,'' he said. `` We're not supplanting the poor. We go into neighborhoods or areas of the city that are languishing.'' For years, Historic Landmarks seemed to have the <LOCATION> Midas </LOCATION> touch, turning buildings covered with pigeon droppings into gleaming, desirable apartments, complete with concierges and limo service. Not that everything always went smoothly with the company. In November 1986, 45,000 demonstrators _ by police estimate _ marched in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> against conversion of the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Railroad Station, because <PERSON> Mistick </PERSON>, acting as contractor, was using non-union labor. Some 1,500 union demonstrators kept Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> and other dignitaries away from the $ 40 million project's coming-out party last May. `` This demonstration is an embarrassment to everyone,'' <PERSON> Dranoff </PERSON> said, contending one-third to one-half the project was done by union workers. `` It was an open shop with bids from union and non-union,'' he said. The labor troubles were nothing compared to the firestorm that greeted Historic Landmarks' plan in mid-1987 to sell up to $ 25 million of common stock and $ 50 million in debt certificates in a subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Landmarks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Living </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> investment firm, filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, alleging <PERSON> Solms </PERSON> and his partners were trying to defraud him of his share in several Historic Landmarks projects Butcher's attorneys argued that <PERSON> Solms </PERSON> and his partners `` are transplanting the heart and brain of the organization which has taken years to build and are leaving Butcher with a lifeless corpse, without any compensation whatsoever.'' <PERSON> Solms </PERSON>' attorneys contended Butcher and a company he formed, <ORGANIZATION> Deilwydd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Properties </ORGANIZATION>, had bargained away their interest in the future of Historic Landmarks or its subsidiaries. Although Butcher never tried to stop the stock offering, just to share in the proceeds, it was never completed. An unidentified spokesman for Historic Landmarks told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> in December the plan was halted by the 1987 stock market crash, not Butcher's lawsuit. For preservationists, the work Historic Landmarks and similar companies have done is ample testimony for the need to restore some aspects of the tax credits taken away in 1986. `` I think the whole purpose of the tax incentive program was to connect the historic buildings to investors,'' said <PERSON> Spatz </PERSON> of the National Trust. `` In 1986, that connection was broken.'' A bill introduced on Feb. 2 by Reps. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennelly </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulze </PERSON>, R-Pa., and by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo., and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, would raise the historic-rehab credit to the first $ 20,000 of a taxpayer's net liability, plus 20 percent of anything over $ 20,000 It also removes the credits from rules restricting the type of income against which they can be applied and contains safeguards to prevent abuse of the credits by people trying to avoid any tax. `` The tax code has always been a tool of social policy,'' said <PERSON> Mistick </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> developer. `` So we can say, look, we need the urban investment and we can direct that investment through the tax code, or we can address the problem head on and provide hard money for such investment.''
