<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 12, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Economy Looking Up, But Scottish Resentment Still Smoulders</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PLanned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Still looming over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s capital city today is <LOCATION> Edinburgh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castle </LOCATION>, a turreted, ancient fortress on a hill that has succumbed to English invasions since the 7th century. It's symbolic of how <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, nearly 300 years after its union with <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, feels dominated by its southern neighbor, which sets the direction for its economy _ not always, many Scots feel, the most desirable one. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s lack of control over its own economic affairs is a big issue north of the border, particularly now that a sharp rise in interest rates is threatening a slow, belated recovery in the Scottish economy. The feeling that <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has fallen behind <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, that its economy has been battered by nearly a decade of Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s policies, makes for some potent anti-government, and anti-English sentiment, in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has pushed interest rates up 5.5 percentage points to 13 percent in five months to curb inflation, which has accelerated to a 7.5-percent annual rate. This, among other things, could raise the value of the British pound and hurt exports, on which the country depends heavily. `` The harmful effects of dampening could be worse on the Scottish economy, just because you're cutting the recovery off just at the point where it should continue to be growing,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, an economist at the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. The backlash, also fueled by strong opposition to the government's property tax reform, has revived Scottish nationalist sentiment, and a heated debate over whether <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> should keep the status quo or seek self-government. The tax reform, known as the poll tax, takes effect in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> in April and is based on the number of people in a home rather than the value of the property. Property values tend to be lower in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` There is a great struggle of minds in the people of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sillars </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member, who won a stunning election victory in <PERSON> Govan </PERSON> in November, ousting a <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member and reviving his party's fortunes. Opinion polls consistently find 80 percent of Scots would prefer a moderate degree of self-government. But the <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s call for outright independence attracts only minority support. Now the nationalists have come up with a new formula, `` Independence within <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' whereby <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> would become independent but retain an association with <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> by joining the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. A recent opinion poll put support for the <ORGANIZATION> Scottish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> at 28 percent, double its strength in the June 1987 general election. It stands in second place after the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which has a 41-percent approval rating. Conservatives are third at 20 percent. Of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s 72 seats in the 650-member House of Commons in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, 49 are Labor, 10 are Conservative, four are nationalist, and the rest are held by centrist parties. A referendum in 1979 failed to win the necessary majority for devolution, or self-government within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> has always had its own church -LRB- Presbyterian as opposed to Anglican in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> -RRB-, its own currency and its own legal and educational systems, but critical decisions such as interest rate increases are usually taken in <ORGANIZATION> Whitehall </ORGANIZATION>, the seat of government in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, 400 miles south. Most Scots are staunch socialists. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, a fervent capitalist, has been fighting to eradicate socialism from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. She is also a firm believer in maintaining the union between <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` This government remains committed to the union, as committed as ever,'' she said in a recent speech in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. `` And it is in the union that we have flourished and found strength.'' Nationalists have long accused the English of fostering <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>'s kilt-and-bagpipe identity as a diversion from the real issues of nationhood. Now they talk of <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> being `` Englished'' as more and more positions of power in the Scottish cultural bureaucracy fall to English appointees. The government's Scottish secretary, <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Rifkind </PERSON>, says <ORGANIZATION> Scots </ORGANIZATION> have benefited greatly from the government, which spent 2,676 pounds -LRB- $ 4,683 -RRB- per capita in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, compared with 2,162 pounds -LRB- $ 3,784 -RRB- overall in the last fiscal year. Scottish-born <PERSON> Rifkind </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> minister, says government policy is not to `` put more pounds into people's pockets'' but to make them take the initiative. In a speech, he urged Scots: `` Search out the opportunities. Do not just respond to those put on the plate before you.''
