<HEAD>Soviet Election Campaign is Firing up Passions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, note elections are March 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MURMANSK, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democracy, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> style, went to work aboard a Soviet fishing vessel off <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Its 50 officers and sailors met during a storm to nominate a candidate for a new national assembly back home. Slicing through 40-foot foam-flecked waves, the 18,000-ton <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> covered 400 nautical miles before its crew could agree on who they thought should represent them in the halls of power in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said first mate <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atroshnikov </PERSON>. Democracy, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> style, pre-empted the movie `` King Kong'' in the palace of culture of this port city 1,000 miles north of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, famed as the destination of the World War II Allied convoys carrying guns and Spam to the embattled Soviets. In snow-coated Kirov Palace, where on other days the great ape had roared on the screen, more than 700 delegates from city workplaces and neighborhoods gathered to whittle down the list of candidates to be proposed to voters. It took them nine hours to pare the list of six names to three. With passion and skepticism, a modest measure of ballyhoo and a big dose of confusion, this city of 440,000 and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> at large are experiencing their first nationwide election campaign where voters will be allowed a choice, instead of having a single candidate put up by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm running because the law now gives me that right, and I want to state my positions,'' said one <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> candidate, <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON>, an engineer who has worked on nuclear-powered icebreakers. `` That's my only goal.'' Said the chief of <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> apparatus, <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khachenko </PERSON>: `` In the past, we used to gather in committee and say: ` How many women candidates do we need here, or how many workers there?' This time not a single candidate has been endorsed by the city -LRB- party -RRB- committee.'' President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who championed the multi-candidate elections, calls the exercise a `` school of democracy.'' He says Soviet political life must be opened to greater citizen participation if his program for `` perestroika'' -LRB- social and economic change -RRB- is to succeed. That's the theory. In practice, there are clear signs of pressure from the party in some sections of the country, like the conservative <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, to have a party-backed candidate become the voter's sole option in the elections March 26 for the newly created <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deputies </ORGANIZATION> The electoral changes, approved in December by the Soviet parliament, also create what some Soviets call `` filters'' at several levels to block candidates who ca n't garner majority support on nominating panels. One famous victim of the `` filters'' was <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the dissident and Nobel Peace Prize laureate, whose candidacy was not backed by the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>. The choice of the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>'s crew, the captain of another fishing boat, never made it through a subsequent nominating meeting held by representatives of <LOCATION> Sevriba </LOCATION>, the enterprise that runs the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and more than 70 other Murmansk-based fishing vessels As a result of the meeting in late February at the culture palace, voters in <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>'s Territorial Election District No. 224 will choose on March 26 from among a doctor, the chief of a fishing trawler fleet, and the 37-year-old <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON>. What's emerging in their fledgling campaigns is a pronounced accent on local issues, such as the lack of housing that's keeping 50,000 <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> residents waiting for better apartments; the rationing of sugar, sausage and other staples; the lack of polyclinics in new neighborhoods, and the fouling of the environment by industry in this once pristine region north of the <LOCATION> Arctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Circle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON>'s nine-minute speech at the Kirov Palace never mentioned <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> but detailed the problems of his fellow city dwellers and had a distinct `` let's send a message to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'' tone. `` When you're talking about people's lives, you must make demands,'' he declared. According to <PERSON> Khachenko </PERSON>, there's little if any difference in the candidates' platforms: `` What people want is a deputy with courage who will fight for what he believes in.'' What's also becoming apparent in <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> is a clannishness, or splitting along professional lines. `` The city's doctors are campaigning for the doctor and are in the street passing out leaflets,'' <PERSON> Khachenko </PERSON> said. The captain, meanwhile, has surrounded himself with other captains. A local editor, <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Prostikhin </PERSON>, is trying to shake off attempts by <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>'s electoral commission to force his <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> newspaper, run by the <ORGANIZATION> Murmansk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, to give equal space to other candidates besides <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON>, a shipping company employee. `` That's pressure on the press,'' Prostikhin maintained. If <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s new electoral system is a school, <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON> is a budding star pupil. The lanky <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION> native with gray-streaked black hair wears a burgandy tie and light blue shirt, because allies advised him to. However, the engineer drew the line at loosening his collar and tie while campaigning, as his advisers suggested. `` Somebody told me that's what <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> senators do, but it would n't look proper here,'' <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON> said in an interview, between puffs on an imported Pall Mall cigarette. Before the Kirov Palace meeting, <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON> bought time on an electric sign that shines down on <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>'s main square. `` VOTE FOR ANDREI <LOCATION> ALEKSEYEICH </LOCATION> <LOCATION> ZOLOTKOV </LOCATION>,'' it said. He wanted to rent a sound truck but relented when told that the move might offend other candidates. His character became a campaign issue when one participant in the Kirov Palace meeting asked him if he would have the courage to publicly oppose a decision by <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. `` Yes,'' he responded. `` I already have disagreements with the election law,'' <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON> said. `` Why should a member of the -LRB- party -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> have more votes than I do?'' The Gorbachev-backed law gives the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> the right to directly fill 100 of the assembly's 2,250 seats. Whether a candidate like <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON> can win March 26 is a subject of keen debate in <LOCATION> Murmansk </LOCATION>. `` Perestroika so far here is more slogans that deeds,'' said <PERSON> Yura </PERSON> <PERSON> Verbitsk </PERSON>, 24, who works at a plant that burns garbage to generate electricity. `` There are a lot of people still around from the era of -LRB- Leonid I. -RRB- <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>,'' the late Soviet president. But the fact Zolotkov even made it to the ballot is a sign of changing times. To become the candidate proposed by the <ORGANIZATION> Murmansk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipping </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, he beat out a man who would have been an easy winner in past elections, an icebreaker captain awarded the coveted title of Hero of Socialist Labor. <PERSON> Zolotkov </PERSON>, a candidate for membership in the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, says he is no expert on economics or legal matters but wants to go to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to make <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s vision of Soviet democracy work. `` If one party is directing things, that's exactly why we need a stronger legislature,'' he said. `` By my activities, I want to demonstrate that there can be controls on power.''
