<HEAD>At the Movies: ``True Believer''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The American judicial system, that great theater of the absurd, seems to inspire more movies than any subject except love. The newest addition to the pantheon is `` True Believer,'' the saga of one burned-out lawyer and the murder case which offers him redemption. In the capable hands of director <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruben </PERSON> and actor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>, the imaginative story of lawyer <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> becomes a genuine edge-of-your-seat thriller with an ending that, for once, is not telegraphed in advance. Believable? Well, one ca n't ask for everything. Suspension of disblief is the name of the game in <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> <PERSON> Strick </PERSON>'s cleverly crafted script. We meet <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> at the nadir of his brilliant legal career. Once a champion of the underdog, a fighter for unpopular causes, this aging radical with the graying pony tail, has been reduced to defending drug dealers. He says he's fighting for the constitution, but neither he nor we believe that. With the arrival of his fresh-faced, hero worshipping new law clerk -LRB- <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> -RRB-, <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> is reminded of his past glories but gives the apprentice defense lawyer his most cynical assessment of the accused: `` They're all guilty.'' That pronouncement quickly is followed by the arrival at <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s office of a tearful mother seeking help for her imprisoned son She claims the son, a Korean-American, was wrongly convicted of a <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION> murder. <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> takes the case, and with that begins piecing together a puzzle so complicated we are n't quite sure where it leads. When the revelations pile up toward the end, they are stunning. The pace of `` True Believer'' is so fast that we have little time to question its real-world underpinnings. It will be hours before we begin to wonder why <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, hated by law enforcement, would tempt fate by openly smoking pot in his law office. Or why the most simple fact involving the location of the coroner's office eludes everyone on this case for years. But the plot is complex enough to distract us from such concerns. And the peformances _ particularly <PERSON> Woods </PERSON>' _ make it all seem plausible. <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> is appealing as the wide-eyed young law clerk who helps crack the case. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hallahan </PERSON> is memorable as the key prosecution witness and <PERSON> Kurtwood </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> gives a cool malevolence to the district attorney. <PERSON> Yuji </PERSON> <PERSON> Okumoto </PERSON> as the accused murderer and <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> as one of several villains, give strong supporting performances. Production designer <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> adds insight into <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s character with his cluttered office and the lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> world he inhabits. <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> puts his stamp so strongly on <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> that it's hard to imagine anyone else playing this off-beat character. With such successful casting, could there be a sequel in the works? `` True Believer'' is rated R for violence.
