 `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' -LRB- Sire -RRB- _ <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> `` You ca n't beat 2 guitars, bass, drum.'' <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> states this in the liner notes and proves it in each of the 14 songs on this album. His four-piece band turns out essential rock' n' roll, lean and muscular. And this close-to-the-bone playing is the only proper accompaniment for the down-to-the-marrow lyrics of <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s bleak look at his city. The wild side of city life that <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> once glorified has turned brutal in the age of crack and AIDS. Drugged-out parents beat their kids, love and sex are just a brief escape from the crack wars, the ghosts of AIDS victims haunt the `` Halloween Parade'' and about all you can depend on is `` the worst always happening.'' The album title might as well include a date _ sometime in late 1988. References to specific crime cases and to <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuliani </PERSON> threaten to turn the album into the audio equivalent of one day's issue of a tabloid newspaper _ lacking in the timelessness or universality that can touch people years later or miles away. But just as a human interest feature story in a newspaper can be more gripping than the latest shock headline, `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' is most successful when <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> focuses on individuals. In `` <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Had </PERSON> <PERSON> Juliette </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> comes in from the crack-ridden streets for a few moment's escape in bed with his Juliette. In `` Dirty Blvd.'' young <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> finds a book on magic in a garbage can and sits in his welfare hotel room wishing he could make himself disappear. The album's lyrical strengths and shortcomings are highlighted by a mix in which <PERSON> Reed </PERSON>'s unvarnished vocal is featured prominently. But if `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' proves to have staying power, credit the two guitars, bass, drum. _ By <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
