<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Director <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> does n't make box-office ticket machines sing. His movies are n't stuffed with car chases, naked women or automatic weaponry. He prefers strange characters, weird settings and unusual endings. Most of what <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> does rubs corporate Hollywood the wrong way. And that's why the arrival of his new film, `` The Adventures of <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON>,'' is such a minor miracle. While many other <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> filmmakers produce predictable, mass appeal fare, <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> grinds out ruminations on fantasy, idealism, history and death. `` I'm desperately trying to make popular films because they speak to a large audience,'' <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> said on a recent visit from his home in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. `` But I also want to turn people a little bit off the path they are charging down.'' <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>'s past films have been praised by critics as much for what the movies do as for what they do n't do. Both 1981's `` Time Bandits,'' about a schoolboy's exotic travels through the past, and 1985's `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>,'' a bleak scrutiny of a nonsensical future, refused to surrender their inventive premises. `` I had a very early talk with producer <PERSON> Arnon </PERSON> <PERSON> Milchan </PERSON> when we started ` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>,' `` <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> said. `` I said, ` <PERSON> Arnon </PERSON>, we have to approach this film in a very specific way. We have to think of it as the most spectacular failure the world has ever seen. Because the minute we start to think of it as a great film, or a good film or a popular film _ any of those things _ we then start compromising.''' Four years in the making, `` Baron Munchausen'' fits no mold either. In visually overwhelming style, the movie chronicles the fantastic travels of a 10-year-old girl -LRB- <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Polley </PERSON> -RRB- and the legendary German calvary officer <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Hieronymus </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> -RRB-, who was known for his exaggerated tales. -LRB- His exploits were chronicled by the German writer <PERSON> Rudolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Raspe </PERSON>. -RRB- The two, trapped in an 18th-century European city surrounded by threatening armies, set out in an improvised hot air balloon to save their compatriots. The couple's odyssey takes them to the moon, the center of the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and the stomach of a giant sea monster. While <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> says the film should appeal to a broad audience, its lack of stars and British flavor will present a marketing challenge to <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>. And <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>, already having survived the film's difficult production, knows he's not yet out of the woods. `` There are a lot of people here,'' he said with a sweep of his hand toward <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, `` who have worked very hard at training an audience. I think <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is the most brainwashed country in the world.'' Brainwashed, <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> said, into thinking that everything is safe, and nothing unusual is worth experiencing. `` McDonald's hamburgers are safe. They're not good or bad. They're safe. You know exactly what you're going to get. `` Everything here is so infantile. There is no future, there is no past, and the present is reduced to a nanosecond. People are just seeing the same thing over and over again. They're being pandered to all the time and their vision of the world gets smaller and smaller.'' Only a few moviegoers these days now want to be challenged, he said. `` It terrifies me. What happens is that the handful of people who are doing really interesting things end up only speaking to a very small audience. And that's what I do n't want to do.'' Whether <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> audiences love or hate `` Baron Munchausen'' is n't exactly the point What <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> is after is shaking the seats in which they so casually slump. `` When my kids were younger, I would read fairy tales to them _ ` Red Riding Hood.' And it's bowdlerized. Suddenly, the wolf does n't really eat Granny <PERSON> Granny </PERSON> actually has been somehow hiding _ she'd run and hide in the cupboard `` And the woodsman has been turned into daddy, who chases the wolf away. The whole point is just gone. And those fairy tales are meant to be frightening. They're meant to scare the kids. Children should know the world is not just a jolly place. `` And we just sit here and tell the kids it's all ` Sesame Street' time _ everything is wonderful I do n't mind that, but I think the balance is gone. ... People do n't want to see depressing endings. But most of the great works of art tended to be tragedies.'' Unlike `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>,'' a movie so terrifying that <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> originally refused to release it, `` Baron Munchausen'' celebrates the triumph of whimsy. `` I wanted to make an upbeat movie,'' <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON> said. `` I wanted fantasy to win. I was making a film primarily for my daughters -LRB- ages eight and 12 -RRB- _ and to tell this fairy tale, not another fairy tale.'' <PERSON> Gilliam </PERSON>, 38, a graduate of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and a frequent collaborator with the British comedy troupe <PERSON> Monty </PERSON> <PERSON> Python </PERSON>, said that as pleased as he is with `` <PERSON> Baron </PERSON> <PERSON> Munchausen </PERSON>,'' he'd never want to repeat the experience. `` You begin to wonder whether it is worth four years of your life. I would n't do it again. I hated the thing and I actually wanted to quit. `` It was the worst nightmare I've ever been involved in. By week two, I wanted out. It was like punishment for something I'd done. I actually felt like Job.'' Out of such anguish, though, do wonderful endings sometimes follow.
