<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Movie `Big' Inspires New Mandrell Act</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As country music performer <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> left her dressing room to entertain recently, backup singer <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> greeted her with the show business phrase `` break a leg.'' `` I probably will,'' she quipped. The reason she fears for her lower extremities is that she has just added some fancy footwork to her Las Vegas-style act. Inspired by the recent movie `` Big,'' she has purchased a `` walking piano'' like the one actor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON> played in the hit film. The instrument is a flat, long series of adjoining keys that sit on the ground. They are played by stepping on them. <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON>, 34, whose sisters, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> and <PERSON> Irlene </PERSON>, also are country music performers, is now using the unusual piano in her act. `` It's a novelty,'' she said in an interview before playing the instrument on <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nashville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> on cable TV. `` It's a toy that will be interesting to people. It's fun; we've been giggling half the day away when we practice.'' The electronic piano, which costs $ 15,000, weighs 600 pounds and is 14 feet long. It has 40 keys -LRB- 24 white and 16 black -RRB- which require 30 pounds of pressure to make a sound. It came in two sections, and her road crew put it together and made some technical adjustments to amplify the sound to make it better for settings such as showrooms. She will place a mirror behind her so the audience will be able to watch the intricate foot work. `` It's a toy,'' she said. `` An expensive toy.'' Three other members of her act will join her on the keys. They hop on and off and quickly move to different spots along the keys. The performance looks something like a Chinese fire drill where all four have hot feet. She did n't have to hire a choreographer to take advantage of her costly new prop. `` It's not really dancing,'' she said. `` It's playing an instrument with your feet.'' In the movie, <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON> is a boy who suddenly physically becomes a man but responds at the level of a child. He and his boss, a toy company executive, hop on the piano at the toy store and play a `` Chopsticks'' duet. `` I loved it,'' <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> said about the film. `` Movies usually bomb when I love them, but not this one. I love kids. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON> was believable as a child. I'm a big fan of his.'' R.C. <PERSON> Bannon </PERSON>, her husband who is a country songwriter, suggested they buy one and put it in her act. They called a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> toy store, ordered one and it arrived crated up in <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION> accompanied by a piece of paper with a telephone number to call with questions. She began rehearsing on the piano in February. She knows of no other performer who has incorporated the instrument into his or her act. `` It's not like the piano where you just sit and do your piece,'' she said. `` Believe me, it's a lot of work. `` I play the -LRB- regular -RRB- piano, so it's not like a whole new experience. And I dance, so the experience helped.'' <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON>, known to many TV viewers for her shampoo commercials, said she wo n't be too worried about hitting a wrong key. `` The fans like me because I'm not perfect,'' she said. The first two songs she learned on her new instrument are `` Down Yonder'' and `` The William Tell Overture.'' `` ` Down Yonder' is a standard country song,'' she said. `` The country music fans know ` The William Tell Overture' but it reaches the non-country fans too. It's challenging.'' She does n't plan to carry the new piano to the dusty fairs where nearly all country music stars perform in the summer. `` It's too big, too fragile. I do n't think it could endure the road. But people could set it up at home and it would last forever.'' She and her sisters starred in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> show `` <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandrell </PERSON> and the Mandrell Sisters'' for two seasons beginning in 1980. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON>, whose specialty is playing the fiddle, now performs in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> about 12 weeks a year plus makes records and does other appearances. Irlene, whose talent runs more toward comedy, is currently on the syndicated TV show `` Hee Haw.'' <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> appears periodically on TV specials and has recently resumed her recording career. <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> recently has been the opening act for ageless <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON>. `` He watched every one of my shows and made all these cute comments. He's really a lot of fun,'' she said. She said he's amusing even offstage and enjoys fostering his image as a ladies' man. He sent her candy one day with this note attached: `` We were great together last night.''
