<HEAD>NASA Lab on Leading Edge of Measurement Technology</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL BASKERVILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bridges, buildings, trains and planes that monitor their own structural well-being sound like science fiction, but they're results of new technology that lets scientists test things without destroying them. `` Our work is like re-inventing the wheel and making it work better,'' said physicist <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON>, who runs the <ORGANIZATION> Non-Destructive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Evaluation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> he started in 1971 at <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Langley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> The lab uses an array of measurement techniques _ thermal diffusion, ultrasonics, acoustics, magnetism, X-rays, lasers and holography _ to probe for internal defects in objects like space shuttle solid rocket motors, satellites, airplane wings, train wheels and railroad tracks _ and even ordinary bolts. Then there are `` smart'' materials that take care of themselves. `` We're investigating how to incoporate sensors directly into materials,'' <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON> said. `` It's easy with fiber-like materials like composites _ a fiber optic line is buried in the structure. An aircraft wing can be made the same way, and the same applies to larger structure like the space station.'' The technology is especially critical for the space station expected to be built in thes, lasers and holography _ to probe for internal defects in objects like space shuttle solid rocket motors, satellites, airplane wings, train wheels and railroad tracks _ and even ordinary bolts. Then there are `` smart'' materials that take care of themselves. `` We're investigating how to incoporate sensors directly into materials,'' <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON> said. `` It's easy with fiber-like materials like composites _ a fiber optic line is buried in the structure. An aircraft wing can be made the same way, and the same applies to larger structure like the space station.'' The technology is especially critical for the space station expected to be built in the 1990s because it will be a permanently orbiting platform bombarded by cosmic dust and stressed by temperature differences. Less glamorous would be its use in bridges, buildings, oil platforms and pipelines, `` anything where you need to measure strain, stress and temperature,'' said <PERSON> Heyman </PERSON>. Smart materials will sense that something may be malfunctioning before a major problem develops, he said. `` This nervous system we're building will be able to sense when we need help. I'm talking about the whole structure as a sensor. It can measure with phenomenal sensitivity.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Texas A&amp;M Scientists In Search Of The Perfect Grass</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLLEGE STATION, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As a plant, grass is taken more or less for granted. It grows. It gets mowed, watered and fertilized. It grows more. `` There's not just that much attention to it,'' said <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Engelke </PERSON>, a turf researcher for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` But everybody's got grass to cut.'' <PERSON> Engelke </PERSON>, who estimates he's one of just a dozen turf breeders in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, would like to see the care given to grass become even easier. He and a staff of 11 have 20 acres of grass in College Station, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>. One objective of their research is to give the homeowner `` a much higher quality plant with less input, less care, less maintenance,'' he said. `` And in the program we're introducing grasses that wo n't have to be mowed as frequently or grasses that produce little or no clippings. Homeowners, though, are n't the only people who stand to benefit from <PERSON> Engelke </PERSON>'s research. Most people believe turf is just there to look pretty, but its main purpose is to stabilize and conserve the landscape. <PERSON> Engelke </PERSON> hopes to introduce two new grasses this year to the grass-growing industry _ a $ 25 billion business nationwide. One is a buffalo grass capable of growing from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>; the other is a zoysia grass adaptable along the southern tier of states from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. The buffalo grass will be introduced to growers this year and available to the public in about three years. It would grow to only about four inches, need little or no fertilizer and pesticides, and crowd out less desirable grasses. <PERSON> Engelke </PERSON> wants it to be called `` Prairie Buffalo Grass'' because it reminds him of the rippling, wind-blown grass crossed by prairie schooners.
