<HEAD>Time, Warner Chiefs Expect Harmony And Few Changes In $18 Billion
Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It took two years of negotiations before <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> could agree to create the world's biggest media and entertainment concern through an $ 18 billion merger. But the executives who will head the new company say their protracted talks have paved the way to a harmonious future. `` I do n't know of an item we did n't explore,'' <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said Sunday. `` That is one of the things that makes me feel very secure in the future.'' Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> announced Saturday they would join forces in a merger of equals that would value the combined company, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, at $ 18 billion and would rank it as the biggest media conglomerate in the world, followed by <ORGANIZATION> Bertlesmann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> would have projected annual revenues of $ 10 billion, while <ORGANIZATION> Bertlesmann </ORGANIZATION> recorded 1987 revenue of $ 6 billion. The agreement between Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> followed two years of on-again, off-again talks between the two New York-based companies. The most-recent hiatus occurred as <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> pursued a $ 1.2 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, but the negotiations picked up steam after <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> completed that acquisition in January. Saturday's announcement also followed years of takeover speculation about Time that sparked periodic surges in the company's stock price The company shored up its defenses from time to time, most recently by extending its stock buyback plan and amending its shareholder rights plan in January. <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> _ who will serve as co-chairman and co-chief executive officer of the new company along with <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> _ said Sunday of the merger, `` This is an offensive move, not a defensive move. However, it is impossible to ignore the fact that the combination of Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> literally gives the two companies solidarity in the face of a trend toward consolidation in the media industry. Publishers including <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> have gone on shopping sprees in recent years, building media conglomerates that would have found either Time or <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> to be an attractive takeover candidate. The deal calls for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders to receive 0.465 share of Time for each share of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> they own. Since there are potentially 177.2 million <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> common shares, and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> closed Friday at $ 109.12 -LCB- a share, that puts a value on <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> of about $ 9 billion if the deal had closed Friday. In addition, there are 56.6 million shares of Time outstanding, giving it a market value of a little more than $ 6 billion based on Friday's close. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> stock closed at $ 45.87 -LCB- on Friday. Debt and preferred shares account for the balance of the $ 18 billion market value of the proposed new company. The deal is subject to approval by shareholders of both companies and by the federal government. Because the deal is a merger of equals rather than an acquisition, it can not be directly compared to such megadeals as the record $ 24.53 billion leveraged buyout of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> last month. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said in an interview there was no one factor that enabled the two sides to finally reach agreement. `` I'm not sure anything happened,'' he said. `` I think there is a certain time when things really begin to come together.'' The price of the merger was not a problem, according to <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>. `` Ninety percent of the discussions had to do with people, logistics and future plans,'' he said. Both executives said the congeniality of their contacts over the past two years cemented a relationship that will make it easy for them to work together as co-CEOs. It wo n't be the first <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> has served as a co-CEO. He and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON> shared the top job at <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> from 1967 until <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON>'s death in 1971. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> will serve together until <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>, 58, retires and becomes chairman of the executive committee of the combined company. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> will be succeeded as co-CEO by <PERSON> N.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, currently the president of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and who will hold that same post at <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Upon the eventual retirement of <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, who is 61, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> is expected to be sole head of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Few immediate changes are expected in the structure of the new company. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> and <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said there were no plans to sell any parts of either <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> or Time, and they did not expect any layoffs as a result of the combination. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> was reluctant to discuss what <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s plans were, but did say he expected the biggest impact of the merger to be on the company's overseas operations. Time is the nation's leading magazine company, with such titles as Time, People and Sports Illustrated, along with <ORGANIZATION> Time-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Books </ORGANIZATION> and the Book-of-the-Month Club. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> has major movie and television production interests, including <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> predicted the <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> cable television operations would be merged with <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s, creating the second-largest cable operation in the country, behind <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. Time's cable holdings include Home Box Office and <ORGANIZATION> Cinemax </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> also expected <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s book division to become part of Time's larger publishing empire. The merger announcement came nearly two months after <ORGANIZATION> War