<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Q&amp;A     03-06 0773</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Q&amp;A,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Questions And Answers About The Eastern Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some key questions in the 17-month labor dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and its Machinists union. Q: Who is on strike? A: The 8,500 Eastern workers who belong to the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION>. They are about equally divided between aircraft mechanics and ramp service workers, who fuel planes, handle baggage and drive motorized equipment on airport runways. Q: How much do Machinists make? A: Mechanics at Eastern earn a top wage of $ 18.83 an hour. That compares with $ 16 at non-union <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 18.78 at <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, $ 20.05 at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, and $ 20.10 at <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>. Ramp service workers earn a top hourly wage of $ 15.60. Comparable workers earn $ 15.51 an hour at American, $ 15.93 at <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, $ 16.53 at <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, $ 16.57 at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and $ 17.47 at <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> contracts for the work. Q: What does each side want? A: Eastern is seeking $ 150 million in wage and benefit concessions to help stem mounting losses at the airline. The Machinists want $ 50 million in raises but last week offered to delay increases for 15 months. Q: How has the dispute evolved? A: The Machinists have fought wage cuts since contract renewal talks began in October 1987. Pilots and flight attendants a year earlier reached concessionary agreements with the airline that slashed pay 20 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> intervened in the dispute in January 1988, but no progress was made during a year that included massive layoffs and cost-cutting. The dispute reached loggerheads last month after Eastern rejected binding arbitrtion and the mediation board declared a 30-day cooling-off period before a strike. More than 97 percent of the Machinists on Feb. 15 authorized a strike. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> refused to intervene to delay the strike. Eastern's last contract offer would have cut pay but kept it 13 percent higher than workers who took the 20 percent reductions. It was rejected Friday, and the strike began at 12:01 a.m. Saturday. Q: Could the Eastern strike affect other modes of transportation? A: Yes. The National Railway Labor Act permits secondary boycotts in air and rail travel. If rail union workers honor pickets, traffic on the nation's 12 commuter railroads and <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> could be severely disrupted. Also, other airlines could be picketed and the 14 million-member <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> has asked its members to honor the Machinists strike. However, the union decided Sunday to appeal a judge's order barring such secondary boycotts in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> metropolitan area and said it would not picket any railroads Monday. Q: What is Eastern's financial condition? A: Eastern says it has lost more than $ 1 billion this decade and is losing more than $ 1 million a day. It also has $ 2.5 billion in debt. The airline was bought by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> in February 1986 and since then has undertaken a series of cutbacks in an attempt to restore profitability. The carrier's workforce since the takeover has shrunk to about 30,000 from 42,000. Eastern also has sold planes, cut profitable routes, closed its <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, hub and taken smaller savings measures such as eliminating hot food on some flights. Eastern has about $ 400 million in cash to help it meet its financial obligations during the strike. In addition, the pending sale of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s Northeast shuttle to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> will bring in about $ 365 million. Q: Why is Eastern ailing? A: Management blames union militancy and unrealistic demands and says it trimmed back operations elsewhere and needs labor to make sacrifices. Labor maintains <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> is suffering because it did n't react aggressively and competitively to airline deregulation in 1978 In 1983, workers made wage concessions in return for future profits that never materialized and stock. <PERSON> Tey </PERSON> do n't want further concessions without proof Eastern is being managed with long-term commitment to its financial fitness. The unions also claim <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> wants to strip the airline of assets or dissolve it. Q: What are the strike's possible effects? A: The strike threatens to force the 60-year-old airline into bankruptcy. To forestall its demise, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> could lay off striking workers and sell other assets, such as planes, airport gates or international routes, to raise cash. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> could sell the airline, and <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> owner <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has been among potential buyers who recently have expressed interest. A separate settlement with pilots, who are honoring the strike, could allow the airline to keep more planes airborne. And <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> could change his mind and appoint an emergency panel that would force the Machinists to return to work for 60 days.
</TEXT>
