<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is a look at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, whose Machinists were on strike a third day today after negotiators failed to settle a 17-month-old contract dispute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, headed by Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, since 1986. Headquarters: <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Employees: 31,200, including 8,500 members of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, which includes mechanics, bag handlers and other ground workers; 3,500 pilots; and 5,900 flight attendants. Size of fleet: 250 jets. Cities served: 118, with its major markets in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. Number of flights: 1,040 daily. Passengers: 100,000 average daily. Main strike issues: <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which claims it lost $ 1 billion in the last decade and is losing more than $ 1 million a day, sought $ 150 million in wage concessions. The Machinists wanted $ 50 million in raises. Each side said last-minute offers brought the sides somewhat closer. Where negotiations stand: Talks under <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mediation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> supervision in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> were suspended at 12:01 a.m. Saturday. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> refused to appoint an emergency panel that would have delayed the strike 60 days. No new talks were scheduled.
