<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Magazine,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Stock Market Magazine Loses Free-Speech Argument</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today turned down the free-speech arguments of a financial magazine accused of violating an anti-touting provision of federal securities law. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that could force <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> to tell readers whether companies featured in its articles bought advertising space or paid the magazine for other services. The magazine, aimed primarily at small investors, is published 10 times a year in <LOCATION> Yonkers </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, by <PERSON> Angelo </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinelli </PERSON>, that city's former mayor Each issue contains general financial news and seven or eight articles on specific companies as investment prospects. According to the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here, the articles `` describe the featured companies in unabashedly glowing terms'' and never contain a negative report or even mild skepticism. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> sued the magazine in 1982, alleging that it violated securities law by failing to disclose `` consideration'' received from those companies described in its feature articles. The suit said such considerations included the purchase of advertising space in the magazine and the purchase from the publisher of article reprints. The commission sought a court order forcing the magazine to tell readers about considerations received in connection with all future articles. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Aubrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> threw out the civil suit in 1986. He said any order forcing such disclosure would be a `` prior restraint'' on publication, violating the magazine's free-press rights. The judge said, however, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> was free to criminally prosecute the magazine for alleged willful violations of the anti-touting provisions. The commission appealed, and the appeals court last June 21 reinstated the civil suit. `` The prior restraint doctrine is not precisely applicable to the requested relief in this case,'' the appeals court ruled. `` Orders that are carefully focused, address a continuing course of speech and are imposed after an opportunity for full merits consideration are not properly analyzed as prior restraints.'' The appeals court sent the case back to the trial court for a determination whether the anti-touting provision was violated. The magazine then sought <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> review. It said the appeals court ruling wrongly would allow the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> to dictate `` a significant element of the content of the articles it publishes, under threat of contempt.'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers urged the high court to reject the magazine's appeal as premature. `` The decision of the court of appeals does not ... determine that -LRB- the magazine -RRB- has or has not violated -LRB- the anti-touting provision -RRB- or establish what the terms of any injunction prohibiting future violations of that provision may be,'' the government said. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-982.
