<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-AgeBias     03-06 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Age Bias,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bans Tennessee Age Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to let <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> officials impose a retirement age of 55 for officers who enforce state wildlife laws. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the state failed to show that physical fitness and a healthy heart are necessary to do the job. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last October struck down the mandatory retirement age for officers of the <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. The officers' duties include investigating violations of hunting and fishing laws and arresting suspects. The appeals court said the age limit violates the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act aimed at protecting the rights of older workers. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> officials said wildlife officers also are responsible for rescuing boaters and water skiers, work long hours in bad weather and face life-threatening situations. The strenuous nature of the job is too demanding for those 55 and older, the state officials said, because older officers are more likely to be unfit and suffer from heart disease. But the 6th Circuit court said the state undermined its case by not requiring physical fitness tests or heart examinations for any officers, and by permitting some officers to stay on past age 55 due to economic hardship or political pressure. Such waivers of the mandatory retirement age `` were granted without any determinations as to job performance, physical ability or physical fitness,'' the appeals court said. Therefore, it said, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> `` has not treated physical and coronary fitness as reasonably necessary to the position of wildlife officer.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 said the federal age-bias law requires employers to show that employee qualifications _ such as physical fitness _ are reasonably necessary to carry out the employer's work. The court also said in that ruling that an employer must show that workers over a certain age lack such qualifications, or that it is impractical to test the workers individually to determine whether they are so qualified. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers, representing the federal <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in the case, said the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> dispute has limited application. There are only about a dozen similar cases in which states or cities allegedly have violated the federal age discrimination law, the government lawyers said. They also noted that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> amended the law in 1986 to make it easier for states and cities to impose mandatory retirement ages for firefighters and law enforcement officers. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1100.
</TEXT>
