<HEAD>Court Won't Revive Johns-Manville Reimbursement Suits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to revive lawsuits by <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> that sought government reimbursement for more than $ 35 million paid or owed to shipyard workers suffering from asbestos-related diseases and injuries. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that threw the suits by <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> out of a federal claims court. Thousands of workers exposed to products containing asbestos made by <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> have sued the company. Many of the workers were employed at government-owned shipyards, others at privately owned shipyards that built or repaired ships for the government. Many of the claims date back to World War II. <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> sought reimbursement from the government, contending that federal officials negligently approved use of asbestos in shipbuilding. The company also accused the government of failing to protect and warn workers about the hazards of exposure to asbestos. The corporation filed suits in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION>, a court here that handles various claims against the federal government. The claims court threw out the suits and a federal appeals court upheld the dismissal. The appeals court said <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> is barred from seeking reimbursement in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claims </ORGANIZATION> because the corporation also sued the government in a federal district court in another asbestos-related matter. The related case sought reimbursement for $ 45,000 <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> paid a worker injured by asbestos exposure after 1963. The appeals court said the fact that the cases stem from asbestos exposure some 20 years apart does not permit <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> to seek recovery in the claims court while also seeking reimbursement in federal district court for a similar claim. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Johns-Manville </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 88-1052.
