<HEAD>Michigan Law on Minority-Owned Businesses Found Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> law that required 7 percent of all state contracts be awarded to minority-owned businesses and 5 percent to businesses owned by women was unconstitutional, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The justices, without issuing any written opinion, upheld a federal appeals court's invalidation of the law. In a Jan. 23 decision, the high court itself struck down a similar affirmative action plan that set aside 30 percent of all city construction contracts in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, for minority-owned businesses. In that ruling, the justices made it far more difficult for local governments, and by extension state governments, to impose strict racial quotas as part of affirmative action plans. The 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> program, enacted in 1980, was unlawful because there was inadequate evidence of past discrimination by the state against minorities and women. State officials `` have relied upon certain conclusory historical resumes of unrelated legislative enactments and proposed enactments, executive reports and a state-funded private study conducted in 1974,'' the appeals court said. `` This documentation is not reflective of discriminatory action by the state of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>.'' The appeals court said there was `` little if any probative evidence'' of discrimination against minority groups, and it said evidence of discrimination against women `` is non-existent.'' The minority groups covered by the program are blacks, Hispanics, Orientals, Eskimos and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>. State officials said the quota figures were based on the percentage of businesses in the state owned by minorities and women. The set-asides were challenged by various contractors doing business with the state, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1980 upheld a federal law that set aside 10 percent of federal contracts for minority owned businesses. The case acted on today is <PERSON> Milliken </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Road Builders, 87-1860.
