<HEAD>Court Rejects Rate Restructuring Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by a group of rural electric cooperatives challenging the authority of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> officials to restructure rates charged to customers. The court, citing the lack of `` a properly presented federal question,'' let stand a ruling supported by major oil companies that buy power from the cooperative group. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last July that the state's public utility commission acted properly when it ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado-Ute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to redesign its rates The association, comprised of 14 rural electric cooperatives, had been charging what is known as a flat rate _ one not taking into account the differences between fixed capital costs and variable energy costs that fluctuate depending on fuel needs and costs. The utility commission ordered the cooperative association to adopt a pricing setup that reflects separate charges for capital and energy costs and varies according to seasonal demands of customers. The association's power needs generally are greater in winter. Supporting the change ordered by the state officials were <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Richfield </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the public utility commission had adequate grounds to order the cooperative association to restructure its rates because the old system resulted in `` an uneconomic under-utilitization of capacity.'' `` Rates charged should accurately reflect the utility's actual cost of providing service, including both capital costs and operating expenses,'' the state court said. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the cooperative association also argued that its constitutional rights were violated because the public utility commission based its findings in part on a key computer analysis that the association was barred from challenging adequately. The cooperatives said the they did not have an opportunity to examine the computer program and supporting documents. The coops also said the state regulators interfered with the power of the <ORGANIZATION> Rural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrification </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, a federal agency, to regulate the cooperative utilities. <ORGANIZATION> Colorado-Ute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has 14 members. One member, <ORGANIZATION> Empire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, opposed the appeal by the other 13. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Colorado-Ute </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PUC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-977.
