<HEAD>Federal Workers Don't Have Right to Sue in Federal Court in California
Union Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said today federal workers do not have a right to sue in federal court when they accuse the union representing them of unfair treatment. The justices, voting 9-0, ruled that the only recourse for the employees in such cases is to file an unfair labor practice charge with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>. Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, writing for the court, said the federal Civil Service Reform Act of 1978 does not `` provide a private cause of action to enforce federal employees unions' duty of fair representation.'' The court ruled against <PERSON> Efthinios </PERSON> <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON>, a Greek language instructor at the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Language </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Monterey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> had worked for the institute for nearly 20 years when in 1976 he was promoted to the higher-paying position of course developer Greek language instructor <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuntelos </PERSON> objected to the promotion and filed a grievance with the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the institute's workers. <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> is not a member of the union, but it represents him in collective bargaining. <PERSON> Kuntelos </PERSON> is a union member. The union decided to arbitrate <PERSON> Kuntelos </PERSON>' grievance without telling <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> about it. After a hearing not attended by <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON>, an arbitrator cleared the way for <PERSON> Kuntelos </PERSON>, in effect, to get <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON>' job. <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> objected to his demotion, but the union refused to arbitrate in his behalf. He filed an unfair labor practice complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>. But the union and <ORGANIZATION> FLRA </ORGANIZATION> settled the case when the union agreed to state it would not undertake similar acts in the future. <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> then filed a federal court suit against the union. A federal judge said the union breached its duty to give <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> fair representation and ordered the union to pay his lawyer fees. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overturned the ruling and threw out the suit. In upholding the appeals court decision, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said today that federal workers do not have the same relationship to unions as privately employed workers. The court enforcement procedures for private collective-bargaining contracts do not apply to federal employees covered by the civil service act, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. The case is <PERSON> Karahalios </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, 87-636.
