be Settled in State Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today said a contract dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and a computer firm should be settled in state court, not in arbitration. The court's 6-2 decision is a victory for <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and a setback for <ORGANIZATION> Volt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which had asked the justices to compel arbitration. Writing for the court, Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> _ not federal _ law governs the case. The dispute developed when <PERSON> Volt </PERSON> submitted a claim for additional compensation for extra work it said it performed installing a system of electrical conduits connecting computer facilities on the university campus in <LOCATION> Palo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION>. The contract signed by <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Volt </PERSON> contained a provision that any dispute would be submitted to binding arbitration. The contract also specified, in typical contractual language, that the pact would be `` governed by the law of the place where the project is located.'' When Volt demanded that its claim for additional compensation be arbitrated, <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> sued in state court. Its suit alleged breach of contract against Volt and two other companies with whom <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> did not have arbitration agreements. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> courts ruled that the contract dispute should be resolved in state court, and not in arbitration, because of a state law allowing arbitration to be postponed pending lawsuits involving third parties not bound by the arbitration. In seeking <ORGA