<FIRST>r f PM-Scotus-Minorities     03-06 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Minorities,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Reinstates Challenge to Miami Affirmative Action Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today reinstated a challenge to a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> affirmative action plan requiring 5 percent participation of businesses owned by women or minorities in building a rail transit system. The justices, by a 5-4 vote, ordered a lower court to reconsider its dismissal of the challenge in light of their Jan. 23 decision striking down a similar affirmative action `` set aside'' program in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> voted to leave intact the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> affirmative action plan. The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan required that 30 percent of all public works contracts go to minority-owned businesses. The <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> plan was challenged by a construction company that submitted the lowest bid on the project but was rejected for lack of minority participation. The project involved construction of an electrified third rail for the city's transit system, which is run by Metropolitan <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials. The construction is financed with 80 percent federal funds. <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> awarded the contract in 1979 to <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which submitted the second lowest bid of $ 8.37 million. The low bid, $ 8.08 million, was submitted by H.K. <ORGANIZATION> Porter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. County officials required that 5 percent of the work be farmed out to minority subcontractors unless the main contractor could show it made every reasonable effort but failed to get minority participation <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> said it was unable to arrange minority participation. The corporation said it has a plant in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that would assemble the electrified third rail, and that only four items from outside sources would be needed to complete the project. The firm said no minority firms produced any of those items. After its bid was rejected, the company sued for $ 1.5 million in damages. The firm said the <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> set-aside plan is a form of reverse discrimination that violates its constitutional rights. A federal judge threw out the <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> lawsuit, and the 11th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld that ruling. The appeals court, citing key <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings on affirmative action, said the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> plan is justified by a federal law mandating minority participation in federally financed public works projects. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 passed the Surface Transportation Assistance Act appropriating money for highways and mass transit. The law, without setting specific percentages, called for participation of minority business enterprises to alleviate past discrimination against women, blacks, Hispanics and other minorities. The 11th Circuit court said <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> `` was not constitutionally required to make additional findings of past discrimination regarding the awarding of this contract. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was concerned about a national problem. Its findings provide adequate support for such local projects.'' The appeals court conceded it was troubled by a lack of evidence to support the 5 percent figure for the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> project. But the appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> had upheld higher percentages for minority participation. The appeals court also noted that <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> failed to show it made every reasonable effort to get minority participation from subcontractors to support its bid. In urging the justices to reject <PERSON> Porter </PERSON>'s appeal, <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials noted that the federal regulations at issue in the case acted on today were amended by a 1982 law. The new law changes the concept of minority-owned businesses to require 10 percent participation in federally supported projected of small businesses owned by `` socially and economically disadvantaged individuals.'' The case is <PERSON> Porter </PERSON> vs. Metropolitan <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 87-1001.
