<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   03-06 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Share Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rose Monday but trading activity was thin as players began casting a cautious eye toward next week's presentation of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s fiscal 1990 budget. `` Everybody's really not doing too much because of the budget next week,'' one dealer said. Several factors combined to boost prices, including a strengthening of the pound and a shortage of stock among market makers. In addition, revised figures on British retail sales, showing a greater slowing than had previously been reported, encouraged hopes that inflation in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> might be subsiding. At the close, the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index was up 13.6 points, or 0.7 percent, at 2,072.8. The index rose as much as 17.8 points at midmorning but later moved down to show a minimum gain of 6.4 points at midday. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index was up 8.9 points at 1,706.4 at the close. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 500-share index rose 8.04 points to close at 1,180.53. Volume tapered off to 472.9 million shares from 632.7 million shares on Friday.
