<BYLINE>Eastern President's Turnaround Plans Blurred By Strike</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON>' birthday horoscope on Monday promised: `` You'll be on more solid emotional-financial ground in April.'' But Bakes, 43, did n't get the present he hoped for _ a return of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilots to work. Without the pilots, who are supporting a strike by the airline's <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, the airline's chances of survival by April are considered low. Bakes, in pleading Sunday for the pilots to cross the Machinists picket lines, declined to speculate how long Eastern could survive but said `` the economics are clear.'' He also referred to speculation about consequences such as bankruptcy that could stem from a prolonged strike at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which is $ 2.5 billion in debt and says it is losing $ 1 million a day. Since becoming <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> president 2 -LCB- years ago, Bakes has talked of plans to pull the carrier out of its 10-year financial tailspin, make it grow and make it profitable. But union leaders call Bakes one of `` the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> crew,'' the executive team that helped <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> turn <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> into a cheap-labor, predominantly non-union company <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> bought Eastern three years ago. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and his `` union-buster'' image have galvanized <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers who believe his priorities are attacking organized labor and milking cash out of Eastern. `` What we're seeing here is a remake of the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> movie,'' pilots union spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said Sunday, after Bakes made a televised plea for pilots to cross <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union picket lines. `` You've got the same players and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as the script writer and director. But this time, the first act has been different.'' In 1983, pilots crossed <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> picket lines at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, but both unions later had their contracts voided when the parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> took <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy reorganization. <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> said he was `` somewhat surprised'' and had miscalculated the extent to which <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots would support the Machinists. Eastern's strike contingency plans had counted upon the pilots to follow tradition and not support the Machinists, or for many of the pilots to defy their union leadership and cross the picket line. The tall, lean long-distance runner with bright, piercing blue eyes was born in <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, and graduated with honors from <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. Bakes served as an assistant prosecutor in the Watergate investigation, was a counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittes and then the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> and then, after the airline industry was deregulated, joined <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> as a vice president. In 1982, <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> became executive vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and the carrier's president and chief operating officer in 1984. There, he helped <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> return from bankruptcy reorganization as a low-cost, aggressive airline. Bakes joined <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> as its chief executive in October 1986 and in January 1987 unveiled a plan to turn the airline around with a six-point program that included marketing expansions and $ 490 million in labor cost cuts. He has promised <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has shrunk steadily under <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, will grow again if its labor costs can be cut. Bakes said he inherited a tense labor situation that predated <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, himself and chief Eastern negotiator <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is a company that's lost $ 1.5 billion since deregulation. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> ... owner of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has only been involved for three years. `` What we've tried to do is say: ` Give it a chance.' We will put contractual guarantees that perhaps will get over the initial distrust. `` With a successful company, when we're growing, buying airplanes, refurbishing, trust will come,'' Bakes said.
