<HEAD>Seeks To Join World Trade Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> has reapplied to join the 96-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the main pact setting rules for world trade, a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> source said Monday. The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a Paraguyan delegate brought his nation's bid to a regular meeting Monday of <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s governing <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which is open to all members. After the overthrow of longtime military strongman <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> last month, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>'s new government had notified the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> administration that it wants to pursue its bid to join, which it abandoned in 1974. <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to consider the request, the source said. Reaching a decision seems likely to take months, if not years. Asked whether the timing of the bid was related to the new government's coming to power, the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> source said only that <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> already had indicated renewed interest in joining for about a year. <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> is an agreement promoting free trade and also a forum for negotiations and resolution of trade disputes. <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> sets mutual privileges and obligations. An attempt at expanding their scope, aimed at further freeing global commerce, is currently underway in a four-year round of world trade talks due to wind up in 1990.
