<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv07   03-06 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 07,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Tuesday, March 7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Business in Small Amounts: Fixing Up Houses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On reviewing the monthly housing statistics, you might think that one of today's most popular participant activities is moving, preparing to move or thinking about moving. It is n't quite true. It is true nevertheless that real estate and housing markets have been particularly busy in recent months and years, in spite of foreboding by economists and despite rising prices and interest rates. January housing starts soared to 1.69 million units, 170,000 units higher than in December 1988 and 310,000 thousand higher than in December 1987. Single-family resales last year reached 3.63 million units, the highest since 1978. But, while such statistics are impressive and to some extent unexpected, there is an aspect of the housing market that is even more active. Remodeling, that is, seems to have become the national pastime. While final figures are n't in, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Builders </ORGANIZATION> already has declared that remodeling and fix-up expenditures last year exceeded $ 100 billion for the first time, double the amount spent five years earlier. While the exact amount for the year has n't been determined, it is known that in the first three quarters the annual rate was better than $ 102 billion and that preliminary indications were for a strong fourth quarter. The spending rise has been what economists tend to call `` dramatic.'' After varying between about $ 45 billion and $ 49 billion in the four years from 1980 through 1983, the total soared to $ 69.8 billion in 1984. It has risen without interruption since then, to $ 80.3 billion in 1985, $ 91.2 billion in 1986 and $ 94.1 billion in 1987. Even when adjusted for inflation, says <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Klein </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> remodeler and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> NAHB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Remodelers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, this huge increase `` makes the remodeling industry the fastest growing sector of the construction industry.'' Whether growth will continue is questionable, because almost all segments of housing markets are cyclical. The <ORGANIZATION> NAHB </ORGANIZATION> expects growth of four to six percent for the next three to five years, or little more than the inflation rate. Some non-housing people would n't be surprised, however, to see the trend continue, especially if the cost of new housing continues to rise. They point to these factors as contributing to the remodeling and repair statistics: _ The rising cost of housing, which often makes it more advantageous to remodel than move New houses often absorb all of the old equity; remodeling may leave some for other purposes. _ The desire to remain in mature communities with good schools and desirable amenities, rather than moving to new communities with prospects of higher taxes for new schools and municipal improvements _ Equity growth and growing access to that equity through tax-advantaged loans _ Convenience as well as savings Anyone who has moved recently knows it can be costly _ for moving expenses, set-up costs, lawyers, new mortgages and the points that accompany them. There may be inconvenience in either instance _ moving or remodeling. But in remodeling you can at least stay put amid the noise, confusion and dirt. According to an <ORGANIZATION> NAHB </ORGANIZATION> survey, the top remodeling activities in 1987 were room additions, which accounted for 25.5 percent of all remodeling, and kitchen remodeling, 20.2 percent. Complete rehabilitation accounted for 7.9 percent. As many homeowners might guess, the major expenditures by type of work were painting, plumbing and roofing, with heating and central air conditioning not far behind. Luxuries, such as swimming pools, were far down the list.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Tues., March 7</NOTE>
