<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Bakes, 2nd Ld - Writethru,0819</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline President's Plan Not Working Because Pilots Aren't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11-13th grafs, bgng `This morning...', with 4 grafs to
UPDATE with federal lawsuit filed. Picks up 14th graf, `The tall...'. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Since coming to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> as president 2 -LCB- years ago, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> has insisted he has firm plans to pull the carrier out of its 10-year financial tailspin. The crippling strike that continued in its third day today indicates his employees do n't really believe him. Instead, union leaders call Bakes one of `` the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> crew,'' the executive team that helped <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> turn <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> into a cheap-labor, predominantly nonunion company It's <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and his `` union-buster'' image that has galvanized <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s workers, who believe his priorites are attacking organized labor and milking cash out of Eastern. `` By all the actions they've already taken, it's clear where he's taking the airline,'' pilots' union spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said Sunday, after Bakes made a nationally televised plea for pilots to cross <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union picket lines and return to work `` He -LRB- Bakes -RRB- is trying to deflect the issue away from <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>. `` What we're seeing here is a remake of the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> movie. You've got the same players and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as the script writer and director,'' <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said. `` But this time, the first act has been different.'' Cole referred to 1983 when pilots crossed <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> picket lines at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, only to join the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> in having their contracts voided when the parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> took the carrier into bankruptcy reorganization. Bakes admitted Sunday he was `` somewhat surprised'' and had miscalculated the extent to which pilots would support the Machinists. Eastern's contingency plans had counted on pilots crossing the picket lines. `` If the pilots had come to work Friday night, I'd be at the Miami Grand Prix this afternoon and you'd all be home with your families,'' Bakes told reporters. This morning, Bakes accused the pilots of misleading the airline, and later in the day, the airline dropped the other shoe by filing suit against the pilots, saying the work stoppage was illegal. `` The pilots have been saying over the last year that if the Machinists did strike, they would come to work. That's why we were so surprised,'' Bakes said today on `` CBS This Morning.'' `` This is the pilots strike that really should n't have been,'' added Bakes. Eastern filed the request for a restraining order to halt the strike with a federal judge in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, who did not immediately schedule a hearing. The tall, lean long-distance runner with bright, piercing blue eyes turned 43 today. A newspaper horoscope for those with birthdays today promises: `` You'll be on more solid emotional-financial ground in April.'' However, Bakes is unlikely to reach that ground with Eastern if the strike does n't end soon. He declined to speculate on how long Eastern could stay alive, but said `` the economics are clear.'' He referred to speculation about the consequences of a prolonged strike, which include bankruptcy. Bakes said Sunday the company is keeping up its payments on nearly $ 2.5 billion in debts. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, native, graduated with honors from <ORGANIZATION> Loyola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>, served as an assistant prosecutor in the Watergate investigation, was a counsel for <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittees and then the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. After the airline industry was deregulated, he joined <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> as a vice president. In 1982, he became executive vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and the carrier's president and chief operating officer in 1984. There, he helped <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> return from bankruptcy reorganization with a low-cost, aggressive airline. Bakes joined <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> as its chief executive in October 1986. Three months later, he unveiled a plan to turn the airline around with a program that included marketing expansions and cutting labor costs overall by $ 490 million, or about 30 percent. He has promised <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which has shrunk steadily under <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, will be rebuilt to grow if its labor costs can be cut. Bakes agreed that trust is an issue. `` We would hope that over time there will be much more trust among all the Eastern people,'' he said, adding that he inherited a tense labor situation that predated `` <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> and -LRB- chief negotiator -RRB- <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>. `` <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is a company that's lost $ 1.5 billion since deregulation. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> as chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> ... owner of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has only been involved for three years. `` What we've tried to do is say: ` Give it a chance.' We will put contractual guarantees that perhaps will get over the initial distrust. `` With a successful company, when we're growing, buying airplanes, refurbishing, trust will come,'' Bakes said.
