<HEAD>U.S. Electronics World Trade Deficit Decreased 25 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics trade deficit with the world shrank about 25 percent in 1988 to $ 9.6 billion but the deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> grew 2 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports increased more than 28 percent to $ 58 billion from $ 45.2 billion in 1987, while imports increased 17 percent to $ 67.6 billion from $ 58 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics companies' exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> shot up, but a small percentage increase in imports was still enough to cause the deficit to swell. The electronics trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> grew to $ 20.5 billion from $ 20.1 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> grew more than 43 percent, to $ 6.3 billion in 1988 from $ 4.4 billion in 1987. Imports from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> increased 9.4 percent to $ 26.8 billion. `` This significant reduction in our trade deficit with the world is the result of a surge in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics exports,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Iverson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION> president and chief executive officer. `` Unfortunately, the same progress was n't achieved with our trade problems with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he added. `` The Japanese electronics industry must realize that trade is a two-way street and that the open markets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must be matched by the same in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' The fourth-quarter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics trade deficit with the world decreased by almost 20 percent to $ 3.0 billion from $ 3.7 billion in 1987. Exports rose to $ 15.7 billion from $ 12.7 billion and imports to $ 18.6 billion from $ 16.4 billion. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electronics trade deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> for electronics products and services slowed its rate of growth in the 1988 fourth quarter to 1.5 percent to $ 5.6 billion from $ 5.5 billion. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> improved to $ 1.8 billion in the 1988 quarter from $ 1.3 billion in 1987 and imports from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> rose to $ 7.4 billion from $ 6.9 billion. The <ORGANIZATION> AEA </ORGANIZATION> represents more than 3,500 companies in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
