<HEAD>Orders For New Construction Off 5 Percent in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contracts for new construction fell 5 percent in January from the high level of December, when public works projects had surged, F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. F.W. Dodge, a division of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said fluctuations in contracting for public works projects have been a big influence on the building sector for several months. Commercial and industrial construction showed renewed strength in January while residential building slowed. Contracting for public works and utilities in January was 20 percent lower than December's unusually strong level. The January decline brought the annual pace of contracting in this sector to a more normal level, F.W. <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON> said. The value of all newly started construction in January declined to an annual rate of $ 243.6 billion from December's annual rate of $ 256.2 billion. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON>'s vice president and chief economist, said the construction sector entered 1989 on a weak note and could deteriorate as the year goes on if the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> becomes increasingly aggressive in its battle against inflation. The building business is very sensitive to interest rate movements and interest charges have been rising lately as the central bank pursues a tight-money policy. `` One month hardly sets a trend, but if the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> stands firm in its determination to tighten credit further as inflationary pressures continue to mount, the coming months could make January look good,'' <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said.
