<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices began the week slightly higher Monday, aided by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s reaffirmation of oil production cuts and a report showing a drop in <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> output last month. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the April contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, settled 11 cents higher at $ 18.67 a barrel, after falling 16 cents in volatile trading Friday. The April contract had risen as high as $ 18.86 a barrel Monday, but declined on profit-taking, analysts said. Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the April contract for wholesale home heating oil settled 0.63 cent higher at 51.43 cents a gallon, after falling 1.07 cents Friday. April unleaded gasoline, which declined 0.68 cent the previous session, settled at 51.59 cents, up 0.60 cent. `` The confirmation of the Soviet cutback on production was the principal issue in the market,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON>, an energy analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Top Soviet energy officials said Monday that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is prepared to cooperate closely with <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> to stabilize world oil markets The statements follow a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> announcement Friday that the Soviets will cut oil exports by about 5 percent in the first six months of 1989, as part of an effort by non-OPEC producers to shore up world oil prices. <PERSON> Byers </PERSON> said the oil market also got a boost Monday by a report shoing daily oil production among the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> declined to 19.4 million from 20.2 million barrels. The 13-nation cartel agreed in November to slash output starting Jan. 1, to try to boost prices to $ 18 a barrel. Since then, analysts say, the oil nations have cut crude flow to meet their daily quota of 18.5 million in the first six months of the year.
