<FIRST>r f BC-DuPont-Ozone     03-06 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont-Ozone,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING for all needing.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Du Pont Announces Long-Term Alternatives To CFC Cleaning Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> says it has developed two products that could become long-term replacements for a chemical commonly used as a cleaning agent that is suspected of damaging the Earth's ozone layer The products are intended as substitutes for CFC-113, a chlorofluorocarbon used by the electronics and other industries requiring high standards of cleanliness in such equipment as wiring assemblies. Cleaning agents account for about 20 percent of the world market for CFCs, which also are used in refrigeration, aerosols, and blowing agents, including for insulation and cushioning. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>, which accounts for about half of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production of CFCs and is the world's largest producer, plans to stop making the chemicals, and has been researching possible alternative products. With the latest two products, <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> has developed candidates to replace CFCs in each of the four major areas in which the chemicals are used, said <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunham </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> group vice president. He made the announcement Sunday at an international conference on ozone protection in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and a summary of his remarks was released in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The 120-nation conference has focused attention on the chemical compounds that scientists say are destroying the ozone shield that protects the Earth from the sun's cancer-causing ultraviolet rays. The compounds are blamed for creating an ozone hole roughly the size of the continental <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> every winter. A smaller hole has also been spotted over the Arctic. One of <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON>'s long-term cleaning agent substitutes is a fluorocarbon-based blend that has about 90 percent less ozone depletion potential. Laboratory tests show it might be a superior cleaning agent in removing residue from wiring assemblies in the electronics industry. The other candidate contains a mixture of solvents and surface-active agents and it is designed to remove residue in a process using a final water rinse. It has no potential to deplete the ozone layer. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> has applied for patents on both blends and limited quantities of each are available for evaluation. The company said that depending on market reaction and further testing, the fluorocarbon-based product could be ready for commercial use in several years and the other product could be ready by the end of this year. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> plans to introduce a series of product alternatives to CFCs over a three-year to five-year period beginning in 1990. The company expects to phase CFCs out of several major market segments in the early to mid-1990s, but complete phaseout may take until the turn of the century. The company said it has spent or authorized nearly $ 100 million on developing substitutes for CFCs and plans to spend $ 45 million more this year. An investment of more than $ 1 billion would be needed to completely restructure its <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> business to produce alternative products, <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
