<HEAD>Continental Employees Unsympathetic to Strikers at Sister Airline</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> employees showed little sympathy Monday for the walkout at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, saying many of them earn less money than the strikers at the troubled sister carrier. Pilots for <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, itself the target of wage cuts and job actions during a tumultuous 1983 reorganization under <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, predict their Eastern counterparts will suffer for honoring picket lines <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> owns both airlines. `` My personal opinion is that the pilots _ or for that matter anyone else _ should not have gone out on strike. I think they're going to lose their jobs and they're probably going to lose the airline,'' said one pilot, who spoke on the condition of anonymity `` I think <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s going to shut that thing -LRB- Eastern -RRB- down and either sell parts of it or bankrupt it,'' he said, adding that <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots he talked to in advance of the strike had hoped to keep flying. `` I do n't see how they can continue.'' Of more than a dozen <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> employees interviewed, none expressed misgivings about aiding <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> management by accepting additional passengers bumped from the sister carrier's flights. However, some <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> laborers suggested their comments were restricted by management. `` It's going to be tough to try to find anyone to talk to,'' said one worker. `` They're really cracking down on us.'' With only four daily <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> flights through <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> airports, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> workers say they have seen only a slight rise in passengers and shipping since the strike began. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> is based in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and Eastern is in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. Despite increased security and fears that striking <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers may target <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> because of its relationship to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, there have been no reported attempts to block <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> operations, union and airline officials said Many of the pilots, flight attendants and other workers at <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s Intercontinental Airport, the airline's main hub, said they considered the labor strife unrelated to their operations, and uncalled for when compared with salaries at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> or in other industries. Nearly all of them, however, said they hoped to see an end to the strike and the ultimate survival of Eastern. `` What <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> did is look at their salaries and then compare them to salaries in the marketplace _ what those people would make working somewhere else,'' said another <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> pilot, who asked not to be named. `` Let's face it _ throwing a bag is throwing a bag no matter where you do it,'' he said. `` This is a supply and demand business and they're in business to make a profit. They have to answer to their shareholders.'' The sentiments apparently spread through the ranks at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> on Monday, although many employees refused to be interviewed. `` The problem is n't really the mechanics, it's the baggage handlers,'' said one worker. `` They outnumber the mechanics and they're the ones who pushed this thing, and they're making a lot of money for what they're doing.'' He said that his wife, a nurse, makes about $ 6 per hour less than an Eastern baggage attendant who may have no advanced education. <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, who was laid off after <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> filed for bankruptcy protection in 1983 but later was rehired and rose to a supervisory position, said union members at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> apparently missed a valuable history lesson. `` I think they should have foreseen what was taking place and know what he -LRB- <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> -RRB- would do _ get rid of their jobs,'' she said of the possible response to the strike.
