<HEAD>Platinum Rallies On Japanese Buying, Technical Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Platinum futures prices gained strongly Monday after a modest rally led by Japanese jewelry makers pushed prices through key resistance levels, triggering widespread buying. On other markets, gold and silver futures also advanced; copper futures declined; energy futures gained; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Platinum settled $ 7.40 to $ 8.30 higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> with the contract for delivery in April at $ 546.70 a troy ounce. Japanese commercial traders, who recently had been absent from the platinum market, began buying futures early in the session, which encouraged others to enter the market. The rally slowly gathered steam, then accelerated rapidly in afternoon trading after the April contract's price surpassed $ 544 a troy ounce, analysts said. `` We hit buy stops right over that, ran up to $ 548, then pulled back,'' said <PERSON> Bette </PERSON> <PERSON> Raptopoulos </PERSON>, a metals-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Observers noted an easing of concern about the possibility that a strike in the base-metals section of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Rustenburg </LOCATION> metals complex would spread to the platinum refinery, which processes about half of the world's platinum. `` That's definitely a contributing factor but it's not as prominent as it was last week,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Trading volume in precious metals futures was thin, both on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> and on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange, where gold and silver futures are traded. Gold settled $ 1.10 to $ 1.20 higher with April at $ 390.50 a troy ounce; silver was 0.6 cent to 0.8 cent higher with March at $ 5.809 a troy ounce. Copper futures retreated on the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after five straight days of gains. The decline was linked to the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s report of a relatively large, 4,500-ton increase last week in its warehouse stocks of copper, and to a 337-ton increase over the weekend in warehouse stocks registered with the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Copper settled 1.4 cents to 3.1 cents lower with May at $ 1.42 a pound. Oil futures climbed moderately higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> following an <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> report showing a reduction in <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> crude-oil output last month. Meanwhile, Soviet energy officials said Monday they were willing to extend a previously announced 5 percent cutback in crude-oil production beyond the original 6-month deadline in a bid to help boost prices. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 21 cents higher with April at $ 18.67 a barrel; heating oil was .32 cent to .63 cent higher with April at 51.43 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .06 cent to .87 cent higher with April at 51.59 cents a gallon. Wheat futures made solid gains on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> following a weekend of drier-than-expected weather in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, the heart of the winter-wheat country. Wheat also was supported by reports that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was seeking to buy 400,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices. Wheat settled 2 \ cents to 7 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.35 a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 1 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.79 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 2 -LCB- cents to 4 \ cents higher with March at $ 2.09 -RCB- a bushel; soybeans were 2 -RCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 7.70 -LCB- a Livestock futures settled mixed in lackluster trading on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Frozen pork bellies finished sharply higher, erasing about half the losses sustained in last Friday's steep sell-off Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .12 cent higher with April at 77.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .43 cent lower with March at 82.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .28 cent lower to .52 cent higher with April at 43.87 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were 1.85 cent lower to 1.38 cent higher with March at 38.95 cents a pound.
