<HEAD>Exxon Chairman Might Accept Gas Tax Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said Monday he might be willing to accept a gasoline tax increase of 5 cents a gallon if the money was used to repair aging roads and bridges `` There's a lot of money needed for infrastructure,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> highway system needs a great deal of work done on it.'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> spoke at a news conference preceding an Economic Club of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> luncheon. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said he disagreed with proposals that would use the increased tax receipts for uses other than roads and bridges. `` A large increase in the fuel tax is not an easy option for fiscal relief,'' he said later in his formal address. On another matter, <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> expects stable crude oil prices in the coming year with no marked increases for more than two years. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> predicted that the price of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brent </LOCATION> crude oil will average $ 15 to $ 17 a barrel this year, with <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude about $ 1 a barrel more. The predictions represent no change from the current price of $ 16.50 for <ORGANIZATION> Brent </ORGANIZATION> crude and slightly over $ 18 for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>. `` After two or three years, we see some growth in prices,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> told reporters. The Exxon chief executive officer said he would n't dispute predictions of $ 25 - to $ 30-a-barrel prices by 2000 But he said, `` I would n't bet a nickel on it either.'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said he did n't know how long the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' December agreement to limit the countries' total production to 18.5 million barrels a day would last Such agreements `` all hold up for a while,'' he said. He refused to forecast <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s earnings for the year, but said they would depend heavily on crude oil prices.
