<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Seeks Journalism Charter Amendment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> on Monday asked its shareholders to adopt a charter amendment requiring 80 percent shareholder approval for any merger or sale that might threaten its newspapers' journalistic goals The `` super-majority'' would also apply to any merger putting more than 20 percent of the company under foreign ownership. `` Our board believes the company's newspapers serve a unique and vital public interest in our society,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Batten </PERSON>, president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>. `` The proposed charter amendment is directed at preserving their journalistic excellence, integrity and independence ...'' He said the company's newspapers have won 50 Pulitzer prizes, including 22 in the past four years. The proposal is to be voted on at <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>'s April 28 annual meeting. <PERSON> Batten </PERSON> said he was not aware of any threatened or rumored takeover effort against <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION>, which owns 30 newspapers. He noted that more than half of the company's shares are in the hands of the current directors, officers, employees and members of the founding families. The `` super-majority,'' as management called it, would be avoided only if the board studied the merger or buyout plan, and determined it did not threaten the company's journalistic mission, <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> said. The company wants to extend the rule to cases involving foreign ownership, noting that `` restriction on foreign ownership of our country's media are not uncommon.'' The proxy statement says that federal law already prohibits foreign ownership of more than 20 percent of the stock of any licensee of any broadcast station.
