 <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' roughly $ 400 million in cash will drain fast because the strikebound carrier must pay competitors to fly waylaid passengers and it's facing a $ 70 million debt repayment within weeks, a leading debt-rating agency said Monday. `` The strike poses a serious threat to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s survival, and management may choose to cease operations or seek bankruptcy protection if more pilots do n't return to work soon,'' <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poor </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said in a bulletin about the finances of the Miami-based airline. Eastern was struck by its <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union Saturday and pilots and flight attendants have been honoring picket lines. S & amp; P said the airline began the year with $ 402 million in cash but the reserve fell slightly in January and February because of operating losses. Eastern has said it is losing about $ 1 million a day. `` Refunds and payments to other airlines flying passengers ticketed to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> will dissipate most of its cash reserves within several weeks,'' S & amp; P's bulletin said. Under so-called interline agreements among airlines, passengers ticketed on Eastern may use their tickets on competitors, which get a reimbursement from the airline later. Eastern has been forced to transfer thousands of passengers from canceled or delayed flights to seats on other airlines. S & amp; P also said Eastern may have to repay $ 70 million worth of unspecified secured debt at the end of March. Secured debt is a loan backed by assets of the borrower, which in Eastern's case could include aircraft.
