<HEAD>Eastern Shutdown, Air Slowdown Show Power of Pilots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 17-month labor dispute at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, capped by the virtual shutdown of the strike-torn carrier Monday, displays the power of pilots over their employers. The decision by most of the 3,600 Eastern pilots to join the working-class Machinists' strike dealt a crushing blow to <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> after a long history of financial losses and labor-management tensions. And `` pilot power'' is poised to expand its reach Tuesday, when pilots across the country planned a job action that could delay every flight on every major airline. Eastern on day three of the strike said it was shutting down nearly all operations and idling 5,000 to 6,000 workers. The company was quick to blame the pilots, saying it could not afford to continue operating because they had honored the Machinists' picket lines. `` The pilots are conducting their own economic strike against the company,'' <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. Why did Eastern pilots, who earn an average $ 80,000 a year, cast their lot with mechanics and baggage handlers who make about $ 19 and $ 15 an hour respectively? `` The older pilots do n't have a chance to go to another airline,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, an Eastern pilot. `` We're going to lose our profession.'' `` The fact that we're out here -LRB- picketing -RRB- is <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, period,'' said <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, 47, who has flown for Eastern for 22 years. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, who controls <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> through parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, has been a lightning rod for the pilots' anger. He is widely mistrusted by pilots and other <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers because of what they call his triumphant union-crushing campaign at sister carrier <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. They also accuse <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> of diverting precious <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> assets to <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. The Eastern pilots have been torn between their dislike for <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> and reluctance to quit the airline and sacrifice years of seniority. A shortage of pilots nationwide means they could easily find jobs at other airlines, but they would have to relinquish seniority and accept lower pay and benefits, said <PERSON> Kit </PERSON> <PERSON> Darby </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Future </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professionals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` The job market -LRB- for pilots -RRB- is extremely good,'' <PERSON> Darby </PERSON> said, noting that the airline pilots earn an average $ 82,500 a year plus substantial benefits. Eastern had said about 200 pilots out of 3,600 were flying during the strike, but the pilots union put the number at 88. Eastern has operated only a fraction of its customary 1,040 daily flights during the strike. <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> has asked all pilots nationwide to strictly follow aviation rules Tuesday `` to ensure the safety of the -LRB- air traffic -RRB- system,'' which he said had been weakened by the Eastern disruptions. <PERSON> Duffy </PERSON> said the action would slow air traffic, but insisted that was not the intent. `` We expect a very good response from pilots at all carriers,'' <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazor </PERSON> said. `` Pilots are going to recognize that there are problems generated out of the Eastern strike that have a ripple effect throughout the system.'' <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> pilots prepared to join the slowdown, and pilots at <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> also expressed support.
