<HEAD>Software Company Wins Violated Copyright Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ruled in favor of a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> software company in a copyright infringement case that may protect software manufacturers against what is called the `` look and feel'' of clones. The judge, in <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, ruled recently that three competitors infringed on the copyright of the Costimator program made by <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>. The Costimator helps users to estimate the time and cost of manufacturing parts. The competitors did not copy the mechanics of the Costimator software but duplicated its on-screen appearance, what is commonly called the `` look and feel'' of the program. The ruling was made in late January, but <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technologies </ORGANIZATION> officials said Monday that they delayed publicizing the decision until the 30-day appeal period had expired.
